<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Holocaust     09-19 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Holocaust,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American To Build First Soviet Memorial To Jews Killed in
Holocaust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lithuanian-born American Arbit Blatas has returned
to his homeland to build the first Soviet monument to Jews killed
during World War II, his wife, former Metropolitan Opera star
Regina Resnik, said Monday.
   Lithuanian authorities chose Blatas to build the memorial in the
old Jewish section of the ancient city of Vilnius, the capital of
the republic on the Baltic Sea, said Miss Resnik.
   She said that Blatas, a Jewish sculptor and painter whose mother
died in a Nazi gas chamber, returned to Lithuania this month to
discuss with architects and Vilnius city officials plans for the
monument as part of the first Jewish state museum in the Soviet
Union.
   The monument will be similar to one Blatas built in New York
City on Dag Hammarskjold Plaza near the United Nations, she said.
   That monument depicts seven stages of the Holocaust, from
deportation of Jews to the ``Final Solution,'' Hitler's plan to
exterminate the Jews.
   Miss Resnik, now a Broadway actress, spoke in a telephone
interview from Vilnius.
   Hitler's Nazi forces are believed to have killed at least
220,000 Jews in Lithuania, all but wiping out the area's Jewish
population. Lithuania had one of the largest Jewish populations on
Soviet territory and was a Jewish cultural and scholarly center.
   Lithuanian Jewish activists began a campaign six months ago to
restore the Jewish ghetto of Vilnius, and work is now under way,
Miss Resnik said. Generally, Soviet officials portray Hitler's
attack as a common tragedy for all Soviet citizens and are
reluctant to acknowledge the especially heavy toll suffered by Jews.
   But Lithuanian authorities gave their blessing to the Holocaust
monument and museum, and several articles on the projects have
appeared in the state-run local press, Miss Resnik said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
