<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     09-19 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meat Consumption To Drop Next Year for First Time Since 1981</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in seven years, Americans
will each consume a smaller portion of meat next year, averaging
about 2 percent less than they did in 1988, according to a forecast
by the Agriculture Department.
   The 1989 per capita forecast of red meat and poultry consumption
is 215.9 pounds, down from an estimated record of 220.1 pounds this
year.
   Overall, total red meat and poultry production is expected to
decline about 1 percent in 1989 from this year's record level.
Lower beef output and a leveling off in the pork and turkey supply
will more than offset increases in broiler production.
   Even so, U.S. total production of red meat and poultry is
expected to be the second largest on record.
   The per capita consumption estimates are all in retail weights,
reflecting cuts as they are sold to consumers. The weights do not
take into consideration further trimming or boning at home prior to
cooking, shrinkage during cooking, or table waste.
   Ron Gustafson of the department's Economic Research Service said
it will be the first time since 1982 that per capita meat
consumption has not matched or exceeded the previous year's average.
   In 1982, he said in a telephone interview Friday, the average
consumption of red meat and poultry was 201.8 pounds for each
American, down from 207 pounds in 1981.
   Looking at the 1989 projections, which were published in a newly
released outlook report by the agency, beef consumption is expected
to decline further to 66.7 pounds per capita from 71.8 pounds this
year.
   Pork consumption is expected to average 62.8 pounds per person
next year, down slightly from 63.7 in 1988.
   Including small amounts of veal, lamb and mutton, total red meat
consumption in 1989 is forecast at about 132.4 pounds per person,
down from 138.4 indicated for 1988. Total poultry, by comparison,
is expected to increase to around 83.6 pounds in 1989 from 81.7
this year.
   Although some of the decline in per capita red meat consumption
can be attributed to the health concerns of some consumers, USDA
officials say there are many other factors, including the economy
and how much money families have to spend on food. The cattle
cycle, with its patterns of supply buildup and then gradual
liquidation, is another factor.
   Gustafson said that still another recent factor has been the
closer trimming of retail cuts of beef since 1986. With more retail
stores removing much of the fat from beef cuts, there is less
moving into consumer use _ which reduces the poundage, compared
with earlier years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite this year's yield-slashing drought,
people should keep in mind that surplus crop production still is a
major problem in U.S. agriculture, says Orville L. Freeman,
president of the Agriculture Council of America.
   ``The drought of 1988, bitter as it is for U.S. farmers, should
not obscure the fact that the chronic long-term problem in
agriculture has been one of overcapacity and that we must continue
to seek and expand markets,'' Freeman said in a council newsletter.
   The ACA is a privately supported organization based in
Washington. Its major interests include U.S. agricultural trade
policy and programs.
   Freeman, who was secretary of agriculture for eight years in the
Kennedy and Johnson administrations, said it is well to remember
that world food shortages in the mid-1960s and mid-1970s were
followed quickly by surplus production.
   ``True, the drought year 1988 is a much greater hardship for
American farmers than those other years,'' he said. ``But while
praying for the return of good weather next year, we must continue
to create customers for our products and work toward a world system
that encourages trade.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once again, the Agriculture Department is
trying to tell us that Jack Frost really doesn't paint the autumn
leaves with vivid colors.
   ``Another story is that Indians kill the celestial bear each
fall and his blood drips from heaven to give the leaves their
hues,'' the USDA says.
   But Stan Krugman of the department's Forest Service says frost
has little to do with the beautiful fall colors, although cooler
weather does enhance them.
   Here's his explanation:
   ``During the summer the tree continually replenishes the
chlorophylls it uses up making food, and the leaves remain green.
As autumn approaches, changes in daylight and temperature slow food
production, and the tree uses up the chlorophylls faster than it
replaces them.
   ``As the chlorophylls decrease, so does the green color,
allowing other pigments that were hidden by the leaves' greenness
to show through.''
</TEXT>
