<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Election     09-19 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Election,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab Vote Could Be Crucial In Israeli Elections</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in report for Monday AMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How Israeli Arabs vote in the Nov. 1 election
may be crucial in deciding a close vote between Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc and Foreign Minister Shimon Peres'
Labor Party.
   ``The two major parties are running neck and neck. The Arabs
might well decide the election, especially if they desert the Labor
Party,'' said Elihu Katz, a pollster for the Israel Institute of
Applied Social Research.
   About 330,000 Arabs living in Israel are eligible to vote this
year, and they could control 14 or 15 seats in the 120-member
Parliament if all cast ballots.
   In the last elections in 1984, the Arab vote gave Peres' party
about three seats. That turned out to be the margin of advantage
Labor had over Likud, 44 to 41 seats.
   But Israeli pundits and Arab politicians say Labor has lost
ground with the 800,000 Arabs with Israeli citizenship in the
nation of 4.4 million.
   This is largely the result of increased Israeli Arab
identification with the 1.5 million Palestinians who live in the
lands captured from Jordan and Egypt but who do not have the right
to vote.
   Since Dec. 8, 266 Palestinians have been killed, thousands
wounded and about 18,000 jailed as a result of the uprising against
20 years of Israeli occupation.
   ``I believe that the Labor Party is going to loose 50 percent of
its traditional (Arab) voters this year because of the situation in
the West Bank and Gaza Strip,'' said Abdel Wahab Droushe. ``Labor
leaders speak about peace, and they do the opposite.''
   Droushe deserted the Labor Party in April to form his own
Democratic Arab Party. He said he was unable to serve in the same
party with Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin, who ordered the army to
use bullets, clubs and mass arrests to stop the protests.
   Labor also was embarrassed by the collapse of its peace
strategy, which had relied on Jordan's King Hussein to find
moderate Palestinians acceptable to Israel and form a joint
negotiating team. Hussein cut most links with the West Bank and
Gaza and made clear he was no longer willing to go along with such
a plan.
   Emanuel Gutmann, a political science professor at Hebrew
University, said losing the Arab vote could be the difference in a
tight race with Likud. Labor and Likud were forced to share power
after each failed to form a ruling coalition on its own after the
1984 elections.
   ``The reason there was a government of national unity was
because there was parity between the left and right. It is unlikely
there will be a repeat of this parity if Labor loses two or three
seats because of the Arabs,'' Gutmann told an election seminar.
   The battle for the Arab vote is seen in ads carried by
Arabic-language newspapers.
   ``This election is going to decide the future of all of us ...
either peace or war,'' states a Labor Party ad in the weekly Al
Sinara in Nazareth.
   Despite its hardline policies and opposition to yielding any
occupied land, Likud advertized in the Nazareth weekly Kol Al Arab
stressing its ``honesty'' and ability to lead.
   Likud politicians have argued that the conservatives made peace
with Egypt and are the only bloc that can speak for all of Israel
in peace talks.
   In the last elections, about 70 percent of the 260,000 eligible
Arabs voted and about half of those casting ballots chose Israeli
parties. Labor garnered 65,000 votes to 10,000 for Likud.
   Getting a feel for how Arabs will vote is difficult because
Israeli pollsters do not survey Palesinians, in part because
Israeli opinion takers are viewed with suspicion in Arab areas.
   The only organized opinion sampling is by the Bustani
Advertising Co., and its findings tended to support those of
Israeli analysts such as Gutmann and Katz who said the Arabs would
shun Israeli parties for more radical Arab ones.
   Awad Abu Sini, 52, who owns an appliance store in Nazareth, said
he told Peres during a visit last month that the Labor Party was in
trouble and ``we hope to hear something new.''
   Abu Sini said he would like to see a pledge from Labor leaders
to ease harsh army measures in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   ``The West Bank is only a half-hour away. We have ties of
religion, language and family. We are the same people with the same
feelings and future. If they use such force there, maybe they will
use it here,'' he said.
   But Abu Sini said despite such feelings he would still vote for
Labor because it offered the best hope for peace negotiations.
</TEXT>
