<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-Newcomers     09-19 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Newcomers,0824</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>200,000 Ethnic Germans Flooding Into West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOENIGSTEIN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a scene repeated throughout
the country, ethnic Germans from Eastern Europe are crowding into
the village of Koenigstein in hopes of starting a new life in the
West.
   Nearly 500 recently arrived ethnic Germans are staying in
Koenigstein. They are just a small part of a record wave of 200,000
expected to arrive in West Germany this year.
   Most of them come from the Soviet Union and Poland, with smaller
numbers from Romania and other East European countries.
   ``Sure, there are problems and difficulties,'' says Koenigstein
Mayor Antonius Weber. ``Our resources are overtaxed. But the people
are there, and we have to do what we can,'' he said in an interview.
   In Koenigstein, 483 ethnic Germans were crowded into two
temporary housing facilities last week in this town of 16,500
nestled in the scenic Taunus Hills near Frankfurt.
   ``We simply can't refuse,'' says Weber of the new arrivals.
   Private initiatives are being started. The ZDF television
network has announced it is setting up, in conjunction with a
nationwide charity organization, a program to find private
individuals willing to help the newcomers with the numerous
problems they face.
   ``The incorporation of several hundred thousand ethnic Germans
from Eastern Europe is one of the biggest challenges of the next
few years,'' ZDF officials said in announcing the program.
   Officially, the federal government welcomes the arrivals as
German citizens and praises the Soviet bloc's increased willingness
to permit their emigration centuries after their forebearers
settled in parts of Eastern Europe.
   But with Red Cross estimates saying the number will climb to
600,000 by the turn of the century, many towns and cities are
having trouble coping with the results of Bonn's open-door policy.
   After arriving at various transit camps such as Friedland near
the East German border, the ethnic Germans are gradually sent to
other parts of West Germany _ straining social services already
kept busy with tens of thousands of asylum-seekers from Third World
countries.
   Eventually, the ethnic Germans are given help to find their own
housing and a job.
   Their difficulty understanding the German language has been a
major problem, especially since the children are required by law to
attend school almost immediately after their arrival.
   ``Many of my colleagues tell me that in many towns and cities
throughout the country, the ethnic German chldren need extra
attention in the classroom because of language problems,'' says
Gerhard Fischer, a 36-year-old high school teacher in Offenbach.
   Heinrich Franke, the federal government official in charge of
overseeing the nation's work force, was even more blunt about
language problems.
   ``The language barrier is the largest stumbling block to getting
a job for the ethnic Germans,'' Franke told reporters.
   Franke noted that the government this year will spend 600
million marks ($450 million) for language instruction, much of it
for the ethnic Germans. He said that is double the amount called
for in the federal budget.
   The Soviet Union alone has granted exit visas to more than
15,700 ethnic Germans this year, and nationwide the results of the
influx from Eastern Europe have been far-reaching and dramatic. The
federal government has been hammering out a comprehensive package
to aid their intergration into German society.
   West German federal officials say this year's expected wave of
200,000 ethnic Germans is more than double last year's 86,000
people.
   The southern state of Baden-Wuerttemberg has announced a plan to
build 10,000 apartments for up to 40,000 ethnic Germans this year
and next year.
   ``It just can't be the case that we welcome these ethnic Germans
_ but make them live shabbily for years in gymnasiums, tent cites,
containers and even on boats,'' state Interior Minister Dietmar
Schlee told a news conference in Stuttgart.
   In fact, officials say that integration is the key word if the
country of 61.3 million people is to successfully absorb the influx.
   ``We can't have `ethnic German cities,''' says federal building
Minister Oscar Schneider. ``They should live throughout the country
_ and must not be isolated.''
   Schneider called for a speedy progress on a program that already
has an allocation of $600 million from the federal government for
new homes and apartments for the ethnic Germans.
   With the birthrate falling among West Germans, there has been
some speculation that the government welcomes the ethnic Germans as
a means to halt the slide.
   Der Spiegel magazine quoted Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
often-repeated phrase that ``our rich land'' can open its arms to
Germans from Eastern Europe.
   ``Plus they're hard-working people who are ready to bring a
bunch of kids into the world,'' Der Spiegel commented in a major
report on the newcomers in August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
