<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ConcertViolence     09-19 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Concert Violence,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fights Close Down Central American Festival</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four people were injured and at least a dozen were
detained when gang violence erupted at a Central American
Independence Day Festival on Sunday, police said.
   More than 100 police officers in riot gear were called into
Tropical Park to break up widespread fights and close down the
festival, where an estimated 30,000 people gathered to hear an
assortment of Hispanic bands.
   ``We had bottles thrown, broken heads, a lot of arrests were
made,'' said Metro-Dade police spokesman Al Hidalgo-Gato. ``It was
due to the extensive amount of gang members present at Tropical
Park.''
   One man with a gunshot wound in his chest and another who was
shot in the buttocks were admitted to Baptist Hospital of Miami,
said emergency room nurse Jose Segarre.
   The hospital also treated a police officer and a concertgoer who
were hit in the head with bottles and two women who suffered heat
exhaustion, Segarre said. All were in stable condition Sunday
evening.
   ``Fights were happening throughout the park,'' said Lori
Alterman, an assistant promotion director at WPOW-FM, which
sponsored one of the stages on which musicians performed.
   ``There was pushing and shoving, but whenever you put thousands
of people in a small area it's going to happen,'' she said.
   ``All the stages and vendors were told to close down,'' she
added. ``Police handled it excellently, without any major riots.''
   Traffic was tied up for hours on the nearby Palmetto Expressway
as thousands of people unaware of the early end to the concert
tried to enter the park.
</TEXT>
