<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CleanAir     09-19 0807</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clean Air,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congress Talking But Not Progressing Much Toward New Clean Air Act</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Congress Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is heading into the final weeks of
its 1988 session talking optimistically but showing no overt action
on its biggest piece of unfinished environmental business:
rewriting the Clean Air Act.
   ``It's possible to get a good bill this year,'' says Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee,
where closed-door negotiations on an anti-pollution package have
been moving slowly.
   In the Senate, George Mitchell, D-Maine, is ``more optimistic
than he's ever been'' about getting floor time for a comprehensive
bill that received Environment Committee approval more than a year
ago, says press secretary Diane Dewhirst.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, and Senate Majority Leader
Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., have clean air legislation on their short
lists for possible floor debate as Congress heads for adjournment
by mid-October.
   Wright has not been a major player in drafting a blueprint to
combat smog and other urban pollution into the next century and
impose stiffer controls on acid-rain pollution and airborne
emissions of toxic chemicals.
   Byrd, however, is the principal factor in the Senate impasse,
largely because of his interest in protecting his state's coal
industry, which could lose business under a variety of acid-rain
control scenarios.
   The lame-duck majority leader has said little publicly about the
situation. On Friday, through press secretary Tina Evans, he said:
``There's a lot of pressure to deal with clean air legislation this
year. ... This is a very difficult and controversial issue and
whether common ground can be found remains to be seen.''
   Earlier Friday, Wright was asked what Byrd had told him about
the legislation's future in the Senate this year. ``He's hopeful he
can steer it to a successful conclusion in the Senate,'' Wright
replied.
   Sources on both sides of the Capitol say Byrd's major concerns
are gaining more time for coal-burning power plants and factories
to clean up their emissions and providing some sort of economic
cushion for mine workers hurt by any move away from coal caused by
acid rain controls.
   Even the Environmental Protection Agency is stepping up its
involvement as adjournment nears. EPA Administrator Lee Thomas, who
favors new efforts against urban pollution but opposes acid rain
provisions, is now telling lawmakers they should consider new
provisions to control airborne pollutants.
   From the lobbying sidelines, the environmentalist Clean Air
Coalition and its rival, the industry-backed Clean Air Working
Group, both say they want a bill this year, but they are far apart
on its contents.
   Coalition chairman Richard Ayres says his side wants the
strongest bill it can get and won't hesitate to pull the plug on
its push for a bill this year if the House and Senate develop
``proposals too weak to clean up the air in this century.''
   The industry group opposes acid rain controls as premature and
not supported by scientific consensus. Its administrator, William
Fay, says the group supports ``a prompt and sensible solution'' to
urban pollution from carbon monoxide and smog-producing ozone.
   At last count by EPA, about 100 cities and metropolitan areas
were not complying with limits on these pollutants. Congress' most
likely remedy would be to give them more time to clean up but
require tougher steps.
   Dingell and other Energy and Commerce negotiators haven't even
addressed the acid rain question.
   They are still hung up on the urban-pollution issue of whether
vehicle-makers should have to produce less-polluting cars, trucks
and buses _ a subject close to the hearts of Dingell and auto
industry constituents.
   Environmentalists blame Dingell and his allies for the
slow-moving negotiations. Industry lobbyists point the finger at
Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., the chairman of the Energy and
Commerce health and the environment subcommittee, an advocate of
tough tailpipe emissions standards.
   For their parts, Dingell and Waxman are throwing no rocks, at
least in public. Sources close to the bargaining say the overall
strategy is to mark time until it appears the Senate will produce a
bill before risking any unnecessary showdowns and bloodletting on
the House side.
   One thing the entire process cannot stand with time running out
in 1988 is a contentious, lengthy House-Senate conference to
resolve what likely would be major differences in legislation
produced by each chamber.
   Mitchell and Dingell have discussed ways of avoiding a rerun of
1986 when they and others spent tortuous, fractious months
resolving House and Senate bills to beef up the ``Superfund''
hazardous waste cleanup program.
   The two lawmakers reportedly have reached at least tentative
agreement on steps to avoid a drawn-out conference over clean air.
   Under the arrangement, Senate provisions on acid rain would form
the starting point for conferees, who would begin their
negotiations over urban pollution provisions with what emerges from
the House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
