<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0127EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Blacks-Dukakis     09-19 0670</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blacks-Dukakis,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Black Leaders Hope To Give Dukakis Edge With New Voters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Black political leaders say Michael Dukakis
failed to energize blacks but hope drives to register and mobilize
voters beginning late this month will help produce the winning
difference for the Democratic ticket.
   ``He may not have the charisma of Jesse Jackson, or the charisma
of a John Kennedy,'' said Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga. ``But black voters
can sense the difference between Dukakis and Bush, between a
Republican and a Democrat. I think we're ready to go out and
mobilize our people.''
   Blacks voters in areas like Lewis' home state of Georgia,
California, and throughout the industrial North can provide the
winning margin for Dukakis in November, said several members of the
Congressional Black Caucus, interviewed at their annual legislative
conference over the weekend.
   Dukakis met privately in Washington last week with several
members of the caucus and endorsed their plans for a
double-barreled effort to energize black voters beginning Sept. 29.
   The plan's organizer, District of Columbia House delegate Walter
Fauntroy, said members of the black caucus and leaders of black
organizations will travel to 14 targeted states to register voters,
then re-visit those states and 42 cities beginning Oct. 14 to
encourage blacks to get to the polls. Fauntroy said the states
targeted are places where a heavy black turnout can overcome as
much as a 60 percent to 70 percent GOP advantage among white voters.
   ``I am confident that (the enthusiasm) will be back as we launch
this drive,'' Fauntroy said.
   Several black lawmakers said the energy generated during the
party's national convention in July in Atlanta, which stemmed from
an effort to give defeated presidential candidate Jesse Jackson a
greater role in the campaign, had been largely squandered over the
past two months.
   ``There was not as close a working relationship'' between the
Dukakis and Jackson camps as there should have been, said Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y. ``As late as it has been in coming, things
are picking up,'' Rangel said, but added: ``It hasn't trickled down
yet'' to rank-and-file black voters.
   Rep. George Crockett, D-Mich., said Dukakis appears to be afraid
that courting blacks too visibly will antagonize the ``Reagan
Democrats,'' white blue-collar voters, he has been trying to woo
back into the Democratic column.
   ``I don't see any evidence of going all out to get the black
vote,'' Crockett said.
   Dukakis sought to generate renewed energy in a speech Saturday
to the gathering of black leaders, calling the election ``a
struggle for the soul of America'' with particularly high stakes
for blacks.
   ``It's a struggle we must win, and I need your help to do it,''
the candidate said. ``I need your ideas. I need your energy. I need
your active involvement at every level of the campaign. Because our
adversaries are not just George Bush and Dan Quayle. Our
adversaries are despair and resignation and indifference and
complacency.''
   Dukakis acknowledged it will take ``the largest voter turnout in
American history'' for Democrats to win in November.
   And he acknowledged, in a poke at his own relatively dry
speaking style, that he has been unable to excite blacks in the way
Jackson does. ``I've been working with him to sharpen his message,
improve his delivery, and develop more charisma,'' he said of
Jackson.``And he's getting better.''
   According to several participants, Dukakis' support is due as
much to antipathy for the Reagan administration as to the
Democrat's positive message.
   ``There's a growing feeling on the part of black America that
Bush will be a copy of Mr. Reagan,'' said Lewis. ``There is almost
a hostile feeling on the part of blacks against this
administration, and Bush has been a part of that.''
   Added Rep. Major Owens, D-N.Y.: ``Regardless of what mistakes
are made by Dukakis, we decided we have to go ahead and repudiate
the Reagan administration. We have to deliver for this ticket.
We're putting our differences aside. We'll argue after we win.''
</TEXT>
