<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudioStrikes Bjt   09-19 0971</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Studio Strikes, Bjt,0991</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Possible Teamsters Strike Underscores Shift In Hollywood Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At issue was the Hollywood balance of power,
and the Teamsters chief didn't mince words. Negotiations with
producers yielded ``the worst contract offer ever made to a union
in the history of our great and prosperous business.''
   The letter Earl Bush sent Wednesday to his 2,200 studio drivers
echoed a familiar refrain. For the second time this year, a
Hollywood labor leader was telling his membership that television
and movie producers were picking a fight, forcing a strike.
   As scriptwriters did in March, Teamsters are expected to do
later this month _ walk off the job. Though the unions represent
vastly different talents, their disputes share a common theme:
determining the split of the entertainment industry's spoils.
   While big-name studios, producers, actors and agents consolidate
clout and record income, a variety of entertainment industry
workers _ such as writers, plasterers and screen extras, who just
lost their pension plan _ are being asked to make do with less,
union leaders say.
   ``We don't have any demands,'' said Bush, secretary-treasurer of
Teamsters Local 399. ``We're trying to stop the take-aways. They're
taking care of themselves awfully well. And they're talking about
our demands being high.''
   There's no question that some Hollywood power brokers and power
hitters are pocketing monumental paychecks. Last year, Disney head
Michael Eisner took home at least $26 million in salary, stock
options and bonuses. Actor Bruce Willis collected more than $5
million for several weeks' work on ``Die Hard.'' And the annual
incomes of any number of Hollywood hotshots easily exceed many
lottery jackpots.
   But producers still complain about rising costs, tougher
competition and dwindling television advertising revenues. The days
of double-digit growth, they say, are gone.
   ``The urgent need to curb below-the-line (behind-the-camera)
costs associated with filming motion pictures and television shows
in Los Angeles ... has reached crisis proportions,'' said J.
Nicholas Counter III, president of the 217-member Alliance of
Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   Producers bent on trimming costs are taking their shows to
non-union stages, states and countries _ thereby reducing
transportation, as well as other production fees, by as much as
half. To stem what it calls ``forced-away'' productions, the
producers alliance is asking the Teamsters to take pay cuts up to
$2 an hour and rewrite overtime rules.
   ``The networks have come to us and said we've got to hold those
costs down, that they can't absorb them any longer,'' Counter said.
``There are Teamster rates in other parts of the country that are
$3-$4 an hour less than what we have under our current contract.
... We can take on another major strike ... to change these
contracts around.''
   Hollywood featherbedding is almost as old as Hollywood itself.
Hair dressers charge $350 for a day's work, even if they're curling
and teasing for a few hours. One union insists that different floor
sweeping crews be used for when sets are built and when they're
torn down. And Teamsters do, occasionally, earn $16.61 an hour for
playing cards and eating doughnuts between dispatches.
   But, Bush asserted: ``Are the (producers) going to tell Arnold
Schwarzenegger that he has to take a 15 percent pay reduction? Or
are they going to tell Sylvester Stallone, `You won't get $15
million anymore?'''
   So why, he asked, do they tell a driver who does physical labor
``that he has to take a pay cut to bring business back to town?''
   ``They're trying to take the littlest working force in the
industry and they're going to cut them just to show everybody. ...
We'll work with the producers. But they've gotta cut theirs also.''
   Said veteran director Richard Brooks: ``One of the reasons costs
are higher is that the studios themselves perpetuate this whole
thing. They say, `We're going to give this actor $8 million to play
this picture.' And the guy driving the truck, or my camera
assistant, or the makeup man, says, `Eight million bucks! What ...
are they talking about? We work six or seven days a week.''
   Whatever the case, the producers hold the cards, and it's not a
weak hand. The International Alliance of Theatrical Stage
Employees, Hollywood's biggest union with more than 24,000
behind-the-camera members, already has pledged that it will not
strike when its contract expires in January.
   Although it says its no-strike stance is a matter of contractual
obligation, some observers wonder if the union isn't simply fearful
of coming up short in a long and damaging strike.
   Hollywood labor pacts typically mirror previous contract
negotiations with other studio unions. The problem with such
``pattern bargaining,'' Hollywood unionists say, is that the
contracts negotiated by a weak guild will be used as a model in
subsequent negotiations, creating a domino effect.
   Because of this, there is concern among industry labor leaders
that the outcome of the Teamsters dispute will have a direct effect
on negotiations with the mammoth Screen Actors Guild, whose
contract expires next year.
   Brian Walton, executive director of the Writers Guild of America
West, suffered through this year's five-month strike against the
producers.
   ``They pick on unions because they believe that they can,''
Walton said. ``The writers' strike was totally avoidable. ... It's
not unreasonable to say the strike cost the producers somewhere
between $150 million and $200 million. And they stand to save maybe
$2 million (on the final contract terms).
   ``I think that the evidence of the '80s in Hollywood
demonstrates a conscious, long-range agenda to render guilds and
unions increasingly irrelevant. They don't want them to be players
in the economic picture,'' Walton said.
   Counter dismisses any such motivation. ``It's an issue of
competitiveness,'' he said, noting California's loss of production
to other states, Canada and Mexico. ``We have to remain
competitive.''
</TEXT>
