<HEAD>Sniper Kills Suspected Mafia Member in Prison Yard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 'ndrangheta is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>REGGIO CALABRIA, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sniper killed a suspected Mafia
member as he strolled in a prison yard, police reported. The victim
was to have appeared before a judge to answer questions about a mob
war in the region.
   Pasquale Rocco Libri, 26, died after receiving a single shot in
the face on Sunday, police said. The sniper apparently was hiding
in a partially constructed building near the prison, police said,
and escaped in a car.
   Libri was in jail on charges of attempted homicide and
membership in the 'ndrangheta, a local version of the Mafia,
according to authorities. His father and uncle reportedly head a
'ndrangheta clan.
   The victim, his father and uncle were indicted recently on
charges of Mafia membership at the conclusion of an investigation
into the 3-year-old war between organized crime gangs in Calabria,
the tip of the Italian ``boot.''
   Libri was scheduled to appear before a judge in December to
answer questions about the organized crime war.
