<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--NevadaQuake     09-19 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Nevada Quake,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Quake Felt From Reno to Lake Tahoe Area</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MENLO PARK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small quake rattled western Nevada,
but there were no reports of injuries or damage, according to the
U.S. Geological Survey.
   The temblor measured 4.6 on the Richter scale and struck at 7:57
p.m. Sunday, said spokeswoman Pat Jorgenson. Its epicenter was 105
miles southeast of Reno.
   The quake was felt as far away as Carson City and South Lake
Tahoe, Jorgenson said. A minor aftershock was recorded at 8:20
p.m., but the agency did not record a magnitude.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude.
   A magnitude 3.5 quake can cause slight damage in the local area,
4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage.
</TEXT>
