<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Deaths     09-19 0941</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaths,0981</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Burton Benjamin</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burton Benjamin, a CBS executive and news
producer, died at age 70.
   Benjamin held a number of positions during 29 years at the
network before he retired in 1985, including executive producer of
the ``CBS Evening News'' and ``CBS Reports.''
   He died Sunday at his home in Scarborough after a long illness.
   In 1982, Benjamin was called on to lead the internal CBS inquiry
into the controversial ``CBS Reports'' documentary, ``The Uncounted
Enemy: A Vietnam Deception.'' The CBS program led to a libel suit,
settled out of court, in which Gen. William C. Westmoreland
disputed charges that he ordered subordinates to lower their
estimates of enemy troop strength in Vietnam.
   Benjamin recently wrote a book, ``Fair Play,'' about the episode.
   From 1978 to 1981, Benjamin served as vice president, director
of news, and supervised the development of ``CBS Sunday Morning.''
   He was the executive producer of the ``CBS Evening News with
Walter Cronkite'' from 1975 to 1978. CBS said that during his years
with the network, Benjamin received eight Emmy awards and a Peabody
award.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Albert Jenner</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert E. Jenner Jr., an attorney who worked for
the U.S. House committee that considered the impeachment of former
President Richard Nixon, is dead at 81.
   Jenner, whose legal career spanned five decades, died Sunday
after a long illness.
   In 1973 and 1974 he was chief special counsel to the House
Judiciary Committee, which recommended that former President
Richard Nixon be impeached.
   He also served as senior counsel to the Warren Commission, which
investigated the 1963 assassination of President John Kennedy.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Fred Thompson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fred D. Thompson, a former vice president of The
New York Times and assistant to the president of the Times Co.,
died at 72.
   Thompson joined the Times in 1971 after the company bought
Family Circle magazine. He was president and chief executive of the
magazine from 1969 until 1975, when he was named the Times' vice
president for advertising.
   In 1979, Thompson was appointed assistant to Walter Mattson,
president of the Times Co., a position he held until his retirement
the following year.
   He died Sunday after suffering a heart attack while vacationing
in Scotland.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Louis Quinn</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louis Quinn, a veteran gag writer turned
character actor who became known to millions of TV viewers as
Roscoe the horse player on the hit 1950s and '60s detective show
``77 Sunset Strip,'' is dead at 73.
   Quinn began his writing career in radio after graduation from
Los Angeles High School, turning out material for such stars as
Orson Welles, Paul Whiteman and Milton Berle and for such shows as
``The Breakfast Club.''
   When Berle moved from radio to television, Quinn followed and
wrote for ``The Texaco Star Theater,'' which featured the comedian.
   Quinn gained perhaps his widest audience from 1958 to 1963 when
he played Roscoe, the comical horse-race handicapper who hung
around a Los Angeles detective agency in ``77 Sunset Strip.''
   Quinn died Wednesday at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center of lung
cancer.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>William Mitchell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMFIELD HILLS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William L. Mitchell, creator of
the now-classic Corvette Stingray and a former General Motors
executive, died of heart failure at the age of 76.
   Ranked as one of the top 10 auto designers of all time by Car
and Driver magazine, Mitchell was a winter resident of North Palm
Beach, Fla.
   He died Monday in Michigan and was buried Friday in Bloomfield
Hills.
   A vice president of design at GM for 19 years, Mitchell molded
the appearance of hundreds of car models, including the 1963 Buick
Riviera and the 1970 Camaro. His designs were transformed into more
than 72.5 million automobiles, according to GM.
   The Stingray was introduced in 1963, when the Corvette was about
10 years old, and quickly became the dream of sports-car lovers.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Walter Chrysler</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NORFOLK, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walter P. Chrysler Jr., an art collector and
museum benefactor whose father founded Chrysler Corp., died
Saturday of cancer. He was 79.
   Chrysler devoted much of his life to building a
multimillion-dollar art collection that is housed at the Chrysler
Museum in Norfolk, called one of the top 20 in the nation by the
Wall Street Journal.
   He purchased his first work of art, a Renoir, for $350 at age
14. He went against trends, buying paintings by unrecognized
artists. In the 1970s, he sold a Picasso for $1.6 million that he
had bought 30 years earlier for $450.
   In addition to his art collecting, in 1934 Chrysler founded the
Air-Temp division of Chrysler, which developed the first air
conditioning system on wheels.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Beulah Mae Donald</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOBILE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beulah Mae Donald, who won a $7 million
judgment against the Ku Klux Klan for the beating death of her son,
died Saturday at 67.
   Her son, Michael Donald, 19, was strangled and fatally beaten
and his body hanged from a tree in March 1981. Two Ku Klux Klansmen
were convicted in the case, but Mrs. Donald file a civil lawsuit
against the Klan.
   On Feb. 12, 1987, a jury awarded Donald's estate a $7 million
judgment against the Klan. The United Klans of America Inc.
headquarters building and property in Tuscaloosa were deeded to the
family.
   In December, Mrs. Donald was named one of Ms. Magazine's 1987
Women of the Year.
   ``I wanted to know who all really killed my child,'' she said.
``I wanted to be assured ... I wasn't even thinking about the
money. If I hadn't gotten a cent, it wouldn't have mattered. I
wanted to know how and why they did it.''
</TEXT>
