<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Up In Tokyo, Stocks Rise Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar inched up today after fluctuating
throughout the day, while share prices rose slightly on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange.
   The dollar closed at 133.80 yen, a .04-yen gain from Friday's
close of 133.76 yen. Although the currency opened higher at 134.0
yen, it fell slightly after moving in a range of 133.75-134.10 yen.
   The United States on Wednesday announced it had a trade deficit
of $9.5 billion for July. That was less than expected, and the news
led investors to different views on the U.S. currency, according to
Takamasa Yamazaki of the Daiwa Bank.
   ``About 60 percent of the investors thought the dollar was still
strong, but the rest of them thought the dollar would not go any
higher,'' Yamazaki said, adding that the former group bought the
dollar while the latter sold it.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues closed at
27,901.00, gaining 34.62 points, or 0.12 percent from Friday's
close of 27,866.38. Although the market's major index rose to
28,016.78 shortly after the trading began, it gradually fell.
   ``The market was in pretty good shape. Since late last week,
trading volume has increased,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of the Nikko
Securities in Tokyo.
   ``The market finally appeared to have regained its energy,'' he
added.
   In a moderate trading with estimated volume of 1 billion shares,
steels and heavy machines attracted investors.
