<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Noriega-US     09-19 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega-US,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega: New Underground Coup Attempts Detected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian leader Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega says
his forces have detected new attempts to oust him, perhaps linked
to President Reagan's order authorizing covert operations in
Panama, according to a published report.
   In his first U.S. newspaper interview since he was indicted on
federal drug charges by two Florida grand juries in February,
Noriega also told The Miami Herald the Reagan administration has
sent two recent messages inviting him to resume bilateral talks
that collapsed in May.
   The general, commenting on rumors that the U.S. government is
backing dissident Panamanian military officers to promote a coup or
to set up a rebel movement, said his defense forces have spotted
``efforts to contact people'' and ``money to buy people'' for a new
attempt to topple his regime.
   ``We, the military, can never dismiss these kinds of things,''
Noriega said in the interview conducted Thursday near Panama City
and published Sunday. ``In security matters, every information has
to be analyzed and followed.''
   The rumors, he said, escalated two months ago when The
Washington Post reported that Reagan had signed a secret order
authorizing a series of unidentified covert actions aimed at
ousting Noriega. The plan reportedly included ``psychological
warfare'' actions.
   ``We have received information from people who have participated
in these (seditious) meetings,'' Noriega said. ``They are
discussing the kind of plans you make if you are seeking to stage a
coup.''
   Noriega welcomed recent invitations to resume bilateral talks,
calling the U.S. overtures a ``positive step'' and adding that his
government is ready to start ``serious, scientific and realistic''
negotiations immediately.
   U.S. officials confirmed that there have been meetings with
``members of the ruling coalition'' in the last few days, but added
these were part of ``regular meetings with a cross-section of
Panamanian political leaders,'' the Herald said. They denied these
were proposals for new negotiations.
   Noriega said he is ready to meet face-to-face with ousted
President Eric Delvalle ``without preconditions,'' if that helps
solve Panama's crisis.
   Previously, Noriega has said he would never sit down with
Delvalle, who unsuccessfully tried to fire him as commander of
Panama's Defense Forces early this year.
   The U.S. government last May offered to lift two drug
indictments against Noriega, if he would step down. Both
presidential candidates, Vice President George Bush and
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, have said they oppose a deal
that would result in dismissal of the indictments.
</TEXT>
