<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in early European trading today
and gold prices continued to fall.
   Foreign currency dealers in Frankfurt, West Germany, said there
was some light selling pressure as some market participants tested
the dollar's downside looking for weak points.
   Dealers in London said the dollar is not expected to venture
outside the trading ranges it established last week but could ease
toward the bottom of that range.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,
the dollar inched up 0.04 yen to close at 133.80 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 133.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:
   _1.8690 West German marks, down from 1.8763
   _1.5800 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835
   _6.3500 French francs, down from 6.3795
   _2.1087 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1151
   _1,393.35 Italian lire, down from 1,398.50
   _1.2225 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2232
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6765, little changed from
$1.6758 late Friday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $407.25 a troy ounce,
down from $412.00 bid late Friday. At midmorning Monday, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $409.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $408.50, down from $411.00 bid late
Friday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 3.07 to close at a bid $411.40.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.27 a troy
ounce, down from Friday's $6.40.
</TEXT>
