<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     09-19 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wind Knocks Out Power in Colorado; Remnants of Gilbert Cause Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain from what had been Hurricane Gilbert extended from Texas to
Illinois this morning, and winds whipped cold air through the
northern and central Rockies and knocked out electricity in several
Colorado towns.
   Strong thunderstorms stretched across the northern Plains and
across the upper Mississippi Valley, middle Missouri Valley and
central Plains.
   Winds up to 92 mph felled trees and utility lines and caused
power outages in several cities from the Wyoming border south to
the Denver metropolitan area, authorities said.
   The biggest outage occurred in Fort Collins, Colo., where some
5,000 utility customers lost power Sunday night. All but about 500
had their power restored by this morning.
   ``Lots of trees down, lots of lines, lots of calls,'' said Carol
Hendry, a Boulder County sheriff's office dispatcher.
   Dan Leszcynski of the National Weather Service in Denver said
the strong winds had no relation to Gilbert's remains.
   The tropical depression that was once the center of Gilbert was
located over central Oklahoma this morning, moving northeast at 45
to 50 mph.
   Rainfall in the 12 hours that ended 3 a.m. EDT totaled 1 to 2
inches in western Oklahoma. Locally heavier rains produced 3 to 4
inches, some areas reported up to 8 inches of rain since Saturday.
   Rain also fell across the Pacific Northwest, and gale warnings
were posted for the Washington and Oregon coast this morning.
   A freeze warning has been posted for the Cache Valley in Utah
tonight. Freeze advisories have been issued for parts of Wyoming
and Colorado.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from the
northern Plains into the upper Great Lakes south to the lower Ohio
Valley.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms were expected from eastern
parts of the Plains across Arkansas, the Tennessee Valley and
western areas of the central Appalachians into western New York
state. Widely scattered thunderstorms were predicted in Alabama,
southern Georgia and Florida.
   Rain also was forecast in Pacific Northwest, and mountains of
western Montana and northern Idaho.
   Winds should be gusty at times from the northern Plains across
the upper Mississippi Valley to the Great Lakes region.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 70s and 80s in much of
the East; 90s in the Gulf Coast states; 60s from northern Minnesota
across the northern Plains to the northern and central Rockies; 60s
and 70s from the Rockies to the West Coast; 80s and 90s in the
desert Southwest and California's interior valleys.
   The nation's temperatures at 3 a.m. ranged from 24 degrees at
Lake Yellowstone, Wyo., to 85 at Blythe, Calif.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 68 cloudy; Boston 65 foggy; Buffalo 66 foggy;
Charleston, S.C. 72 foggy; Cincinnati 68 partly cloudy; Cleveland
69 foggy; Detroit 64 foggy; Miami 77 fair; New York 64 foggy;
Philadelphia 64 foggy; Pittsburgh 66 foggy; Portland, Maine 59
foggy; Washington 67 foggy.
   _Central: Bismarck 44 rain; Chicago 67 rain; Dallas-Fort Worth
80 windy; Denver 48 windy; Des Moines 72 cloudy; Indianapolis 68
cloudy; Kansas City 74 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 71 cloudy;
Nashville 72 fair; New Orleans 79 fair; St. Louis 76 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 63 fair; Anchorage 55 windy; Las Vegas 69
fair; Los Angeles 62 fair; Phoenix 80 fair; Salt Lake City 42 fair;
San Diego 64 partly cloudy; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 50 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 55 fair; Toronto 64 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
