<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Soviet-Fire,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Put Out At U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small fire broke out today in the U.S. Embassy
in Moscow, but was extinguished within a few minutes and caused no
damage or injury, the embassy said.
   An embassy statement said the fire began at about 10:30 a.m. in
the fuel tank of a torch being used for repair work in a stairwell.
   As a precaution, the building was evacuated, but employees and
visitors returned after about five minutes, the statement said.
   U.S. press attache Richard Gilbert said the fire, which was
confined to the stairwell, was put out in about five minutes by
embassy staff. Soviet firefighters arrived, but their help was not
needed, Gilbert said.
   On Feb. 17, a fire began on the fifth floor in the same section
of the embassy and was quickly put out. There were no injuries. In
April, a fire in an unused kitchen of the residence of U.S.
Ambassador Jack Matlock destroyed some American art stored there.
