<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ArtInstituteWing     09-19 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Art Institute Wing,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Art Institute Opens New Wing With Major Gauguin Exhibition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Art Institute of Chicago has opened a new $23
million wing with the most comprehensive exhibit of Paul Gauguin's
work in more than 80 years.
   About 250 people attended a ribbon-cutting Saturday for the
Daniel F. and Ada L. Rice Building, the largest addition to the
museum in its 109-year history.
   The three-story building increases the museum's gallery space by
nearly a third _ from 168,100 square feet to 222,760 square feet.
   Of the nation's major art museums, the Art Institute trails only
the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York City, the Philadelphia
Museum of Art and The National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C.,
in gallery space.
   The Gauguin show, running until Dec. 11, includes more than 250
works from private and public collections around the world. It
showcases other sides of Gauguin's art besides the colorful
Tahitian and South Sea Island paintings for which he is best known.
   Museum spokeswoman Eileen Harakal said it is the most
comprehensive exhibition of Gauguin's work since 1906, when the
Salon d'Automne in Paris mounted an exhibition three years after
the artist's death.
   Construction of the building is part of a long-range $57 million
plan launched in 1982 to renovate the Art Institute. The Rice
Foundation donated $10 million to the museum.
</TEXT>
