<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Dornan-Gays     09-19 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dornan-Gays,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Wife Wife Reveals Brother Has AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A town meeting erupted into a
shouting match when the wife of Rep. Bob Dornan screamed, ``Shut
up, fag'' at a gay activist. Then, in a public apology, she
revealed to her husband that her brother is dying of AIDS.
   Sallie Dornan shouted the epithet at Jeff LeTourneau during a
heated exchange Sunday between the gay activist and her husband, a
conservative Republican.
   LeTourneau and about 30 other chanting protesters were then
escorted from the auditorium by police at Dornan's request, but
LeTourneau was allowed to return and pose the last question of the
session. He demanded an apology.
   ``I'm very sorry I did that,'' said Mrs. Dornan, her voice
breaking. ``You were all yelling at my husband, whom I love.
   ``I apologize, but it will not rid the anger in my heart. My
brother is dying. ... I want you to understand there's great anger
and pain inside of me.''
   She later told reporters that one of her four brothers is a
homosexual and is dying of AIDS. The congressman said he knew his
brother-in-law is a homosexual but not that he has acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   ``To tell you the truth, I didn't know until this minute,'' said
the Orange County congressman, who then asked his wife, ``Why
didn't you tell me?''
   ``I didn't want to hurt you,'' she said.
   She had yelled ``Shut up, fag'' at LeTourneau during an argument
he and Democratic opponent Jerry Yudelson were having with Dornan
over the congressman's vote to give foreign aid to the Bolivian
government.
   LeTourneau accepted Mrs. Dornan's apology.
   LeTourneau had earlier organized a rally of a gay rights group
to protest Dornan's stand on gay issues. Dornan is seeking a third
term.
   About 25 people participated in the rally. Some group wore
T-shirts reading ``Queer and Present Danger,'' and demonstrators in
black shrouds carried a mock coffin and read names of those who had
died of AIDS.
   After the session, LeTourneau said Dornan had denounced the term
``gay'' on the House floor and refused to back legislation to bar
discrimination based on sexual preference.
   Dornan confirmed he opposed the legislation but said he has been
``on the cutting edge'' of anti-AIDS legislation, contributed part
of his $12,400 pay raise to help AIDS hospices and helped publicize
the issue of AIDS.
   Dornan said his ``heart goes out'' to homosexuals, ``but I am
not going to let them wreck every town hall meeting.''
</TEXT>
