<DOCNO> AP880919-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0942EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Casualties     09-19 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Casualties,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Says It Lost 123,000 Soldiers, 11,000 Civilians In Gulf War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said its 8-year-old war with Iraq
claimed the lives of 123,220 soldiers and 11,000 civilians.
   Islamic Guidance and Culture Minister Mohammad Khatami also said
in an interview Sunday that 60,711 other military personnel were
listed as missing in action. Khatami, speaking on Tehran radio,
monitored in Nicosia, said Iran believed many of the missing are
prisoners of war in Iraq.
   The death toll cited by Khatami was well below estimates of
300,000 Iranians killed that Western military analysts considered
to be conservative. It was the first time Tehran announced war
casualty figures.
   Iraqi officials have claimed more than 800,000 Iranians were
killed before a U.N.-sponsored cease-fire took effect Aug. 20.
   Khatami gave no figures for Iran's wounded. Western analysts
estimated earlier this year that 600,000 to 700,000 people had been
wounded in the war.
   U.S. and other Western analysts have estimated 120,000 Iraqis
were killed and 300,000 wounded in the conflict.
   Iran held a 3-1 manpower edge over its foe, but for much of the
war the Iraqis fought from heavily fortified defense lines that
helped minimize their casualties.
   Khatami, who is also a deputy commander at military
headquarters, said Iran's Revolutionary Guards suffered the worst
casualties, with 79,664 killed.
   The Revolutionary Guards bore the brunt of the fighting and
repeatedly launched human-wave offensives against Iraq's formidable
defenses.
   Khatami said 35,170 soldiers of the regular army were killed.
The officer corps of the army, built up by Shah Mohammad Reza
Pahlavi, was crippled by revolutionary purges after the monarch was
toppled by Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's Islamic Revolution in 1979.
   Khatami said 5,061 members of the paramilitary gendarmerie also
were killed, while a military engineering force lost 2,075 people.
In addition, 1,270 police and revolutionary committee members were
killed, he said.
   The Iranian minister said Iraqi attacks on Iranian cities
claimed the lives of 11,000 civilians.
   Diplomatic sources said several thousand civilians were slain in
a seven-week ``war of the cities'' earlier this year, when Iraq
fired about 300 long-range missiles into Tehran and other cities.
   Towns along the border were shelled almost daily by Iraqi
artillery and short-range rockets.
   Authorities in the Iraqi capital of Baghdad listed 18,000
Iranian prisoners of war in July but said the total was probably
closer to 35,000 because many Iranians were captured in offensives
shortly before the cease-fire.
   Iran has told the International Committee of the Red Cross that
it holds 46,098 Iraqis. But a U.N. team that visited Iranian
prisoner camps July 23-30 estimated the figure was closer to 70,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0066 </DOCNO>
