<2ND_LINE>PM-Provincial Strike,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Columbia Workers Go On Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are Canadian.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A provincewide strike by
27,000 civil service workers closed most government offices today.
Some 1,500 prison guards who joined the strike Saturday agreed to
return today under court order.
   The guards, members of the British Columbia Government Employees
Union, are among about 2,000 workers whose services were designated
essential.
   Officials said most government offices would be closed today,
including land titles offices and registries for births, deaths and
marriages.
   The union, whose contract expired July 31, struck after a
39-hour negotiating session failed to resolve the issue of wages.
The walkout Saturday stalled six inland ferries and affected the
government's 216 liquor stores.
   The guards walked out at many of the 33 provincial correctional
facilities Saturday, creating a situation government negotiator Bob
Plecas called ``tense and explosive.''
   Royal Canadian Mounted Police officers were brought in to handle
security, and inmates were locked in their cells at a Vancouver
prison. There were also reports of fights at a juvenile facility in
Burnaby.
   Late Sunday, British Columbia Supreme Court Justice Bruce Cohen
ordered guards back on the job.
   ``It looks like all of our corrections members will be going
back to work in compliance with the court order,'' said union
spokeswoman Sheila Fruman. ``Some won't be back until the morning
shift change. But they will be going back.''
   The last wage demands made public by the union totaled 25
percent over three years. Plecas said the government offered 5
percent in each year of a three-year contract. Ms. Fruman said the
guards earn about $15 an hour.
</TEXT>
