<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1024EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iraq-US 1stLd-Writethru a0434 09-19 0919</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iraq-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0434,0947</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Charges Of Chemical Weapon Use Dent Iraq's Friendship with U.S.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 11-12 to UPDATE with comments of Iraqi foreign
minister. Picks up 11th graf pvs, `Deputy Foreign Minister...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American allegations that Iraq is using
outlawed chemical weapons against Kurdish rebels have touched off a
wave of anti-Americanism in Iraq.
   But although the conflict may damage U.S.-Iraqi relations, there
appears little likelihood of a return to the bitter hostility that
made Iraq a leading foe of U.S. Middle East policies in the 1970s.
   The U.S. Senate on Sept. 9 accused Iraq of using poison gas in a
campaign of ``genocide'' against its autonomy-seeking Kurdish
minority.
   The State Department said it had proof of Iraqi poison gas
attacks, based on American examination of Kurdish refugees in
Turkey. Britain also condemned Baghdad, citing ``compelling
evidence'' provided by Washington.
   The Senate demanded economic sanctions against Iraq, which is
struggling to cope with a foreign debt estimated at $70 billion
incurred during its 8-year war with Iran.
   Iraq denies the gas allegations and has responded with a wave of
fierce anti-American rhetoric. Its state-controlled newspapers and
broadcasts have branded the Senate the ``American Knesset,'' a
reference to Israel's parliament, and claimed it seeks to help
Israel by weakening a powerful Arab country.
   The Iraqis organized a march by 20,000 people past the U.S.
Embassy. Many chanted slogans in English denouncing alleged
American human rights abuses.
   Questioning America's right to preach, Iraqi television screened
an hour-long documentary depicting the 1945 atomic bombing of
Hiroshima.
   It also showed Vietnamese children with napalm burns and
Palestinian victims of Israeli attacks as well as film of rats
crawling over homeless Americans sleeping in New York City sewers.
   The anti-American propaganda is the strongest since the United
States and Iraq resumed diplomatic ties in 1984 after a 17-year
break caused by U.S. support of Israel in the 1967 war with the
Arabs.
   Today, Foreign Minister Tarik Aziz said future relations with
Washington depend on whether the U.S. adminstration agrees to the
Senate calls for sanctions against Iraq.
   ``If the American adminstration yields to the campaign of the
Senate and the Zionist lobby, this will have negative effect on
relations between the two countries,'' Aziz told reporters in
Baghdad.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Nizar Hamdoon told The Associated Press
last week that Iraq's response did not indicate any shift in its
basic orientation.
   But, he added, ``If the (U.S.) policy continues, if the tension
continues, obviously trade opportunities and other matters ...
would be in jeopardy.''
   Diplomats in Baghdad said they expected the burst of rhetoric to
pass if the chemical weapons charges do not continue.
   Iraq badly needs Western, if not American, credit to help
rebuild its war-battered country and reward its weary population
with consumer goods.
   It also seeks diplomatic support in its negotiating struggles
with Iran at peace talks in Geneva.
   U.S. relations with Iraq improved gradually during the Persian
Gulf war, aided by Iraq's growing ties with pro-Western states in
the region and U.S. hostility toward Iran's Islamic fundamentalist
government.
   Iraq also appreciated U.S. naval intervention in the gulf to
protect its Arab neighbors' shipping from Iranian attacks.
   But the Iraqis remain deeply suspicious of the United States and
sensitive about signs that foreign countries are tilting toward
Iran in the postwar era.
   Iran's size, oil wealth and position on the southern Soviet
flank have made it a focus of Western diplomacy for decades, and
Tehran's more pragmatic leaders are seeking to end the country's
self-imposed isolation.
   But Iraq, too, is a strategic country. Its oil reserves are
second only to those of Saudi Arabia, it flanks NATO member Turkey
and it is argued that Iraq's war with Iran blocked the expansion of
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's Islamic crusade.
   Iraqi leaders claim the Western allegations of chemical warfare
are designed to help both Israel and Iran.
   Their suspicions are rooted partly in Israeli and American
efforts to aid Iran during the war and by strong U.S.
identification with Israel, which regards Iraq, with a
million-strong battle-hardened army, as a major potential threat.
   Israel bombed an Iraqi nuclear plant in June 1981 to prevent the
possible development of an Arab atomic bomb.
   Baghdad expressed skepticism about the timing of U.S. actions.
During the war with Iran, Iraq said it used chemical weapons after
Iran used them first. Iraq drew United Natons condemnation, but no
sanctions.
   Both Turkey and the Red Cross say they have been unable to
substantiate the gas charges that drew the latest U.S. criticism.
   And diplomats critical of Iraq's treatment of the Kurds refuse,
even in private, to characterize it as genocide.
   They said the Iraqis, who lost hundreds of thousands of
casualties to conventional arms in the war, have trouble
understanding the West's reaction to chemical warfare charges.
   The crisis has rallied Arabs behind Iraq. Kuwait's Foreign
Ministry on Wednesday summoned U.S. Ambassador Nathaniel Wilson
Howell to express ``extreme concern'' over the U.S. charges, an
official statement said.
   It reported that Foreign undersecretary Suleiman Majed
Al-Shaheen told Howell: ``Kuwait regrets the way the American media
exploited such allegations to launch a campaign against Iraq at a
time when neutral parties ... announced they did not find evidence
that Iraq has used chemical weapons.''
   It added that Kuwait ``believes that invoking such questions by
the U.S. Senate will only ... undermine the chances of concluding a
comprehensive peace agreement'' between Iran and Iraq.
</TEXT>
