<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Britain     09-19 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Britain,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Says It Fired Warning Shots At Helicopter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China said today its troops fired only warning
shots to keep a British helicopter away from a disputed island in
the South China Sea.
   A Foreign Ministry statement denied British press reports that
the Chinese troops fired at the Royal Navy helicopter, and called
the incident ``entirely a misunderstanding.''
   The British Embassy said Thursday that the helicopter was
searching for a sinking Taiwanese trawler in the South China Sea on
Aug. 23 when it was hit by gunfire from a Chinese garrison on the
Paracel Islands. The Paracels, a chain of islands in the South
China Sea, are claimed by China and Vietnam. China seized the
islands from South Vietnam in 1974.
   The embassy said the helicopter, based on the British frigate
Sirius, was nicked but not significantly damaged and no one was
injured.
   The Foreign Ministry at first refused to confirm or deny that
Chinese troops fired, saying only that media reports were incorrect
and the incident was closed.
   But in today's statement, China said the helicopter ``went
beyond the originally designated flying range and flew at low
altitude over China's Zhongjian island (in the Paracels).''
   ``Under such circumstances, our troops stationed there fired
warning shots,'' the statement said. ``This was entirely a
misunderstanding. Now this matter has been resolved.''
</TEXT>
