<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Japanese-Internment     09-19 0192</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japanese-Internment,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toll-Free Telephone Number Set Up for Inquiries on Japanese
Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has set up a toll-free
telephone number and an office in the Justice Department for anyone
inquiring about restitution payments to people of Japanese ancestry
interned by U.S. authorities in camps during World War II.
   The toll-free phone number is 1-800-228-8375, the Justice
Department announced today. In the Washington area, the number is
835-2094. Calls will be received from 8:30 a.m. to 8:30 p.m.
Eastern time, Monday through Friday.
   Letters should be mailed to the newly established Office of
Reparations Administration, P.O. Box 66260, Washington, D.C.
20035-6260.
   The Office of Reparations Administration in the department's
civil rights division will be responsibile for identifying those
who are eligible for the restitution and for making the payments.
   The restitution was authorized in the recently enacted Civil
Liberties Act of 1988.
   The Justice Department, meanwhile, is developing regulations for
determining eligibility for the payments, said William Bradford
Reynolds, head of the Justice Department's civil rights division.
   The Office of Reparations Administration will be headed by
Robert Bratt, head of the executive office of the civil rights
division.
</TEXT>
