<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Killing Snowball-Throwing Teen-ager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was convicted of murder and sentenced
to five to 10 years in prison today for shooting a teen-ager who
was throwing snowballs at his house.
   Judge Eugene H. Clarke Jr. also found Edward Smith, 49, guilty
of weapons possession and recklessly endangering in the 1987
slaying of Peter McGettigan, 16. The judge announced his verdict
after a non-jury trial last week.
   McGettigan died of a gunshot through the spine. Smith testified
that he fired twice to scare off a group of teen-agers who had been
taunting his family and throwing snowballs. He said he had no
intention of killing anyone.
   Smith received the mandatory minimum term for third-degree
murder. He could receive up to seven more years when sentenced on
the other charges Nov. 29.
