<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Sweden-Refugees     09-19 0541</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sweden-Refugees,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farming Town Defies Sweden's Refugee Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Sweden-Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in a small farming community
rebelled against Sweden's generous refugee policy and
overwhelmingly rejected a government request to accept a few dozen
immigrants.
   Sunday's local referendum in the southern district of Sjobo was
closely watched by a nation anxious that a negative vote could be
seen as the surfacing of supressed racism. The referendum was a
part of nationwide elections.
   The result came as a surprise, with two out of three voters
saying ``no'' to a proposal to take in the refugees. The TT news
agency reported 6,237 people voted against housing the immigrants
and 3,000 voting in favor of the proposal.
   It was the first time Swedes openly defied their country's
long-standing policy to provide sanctuary to political refugees, as
well as language training, job skills, housing, education and
generous social benefits.
   ``This is a sad result. Everyone is a loser,'' said Madeleine
Ramel, head of the social welfare board that would have taken care
of the immigrants. ``It is unfortunate for Sjobo.''
   Mrs. Ramel said she feared the referendum results would prompt
other communities to reassess their policy of accepting immigrants.
   The agency said the voting was quiet, but some opponents of the
proposal carried placards for ``A white Sjobo,'' and ``Sjobo: a
Swedish example.''
   Last year 18,000 people _ the highest rate in Europe _ sought
political asylum in Sweden, a neutral nation of 8.4 million,
according to government figures.
   In an effort to relocate the immigrants outside the main cities,
authorities sent letters to 284 municipal districts asking their
help.
   The letter to Sjobo did not specify how many refugees the town
would be asked to shelter or give their national origin, but local
officials said the number would have been between 20 and 40.
   The Sjobo town council split on the issue last fall and voted
25-24 to put the question to a referendum.
   Council chairman Sven-Olle Olsson, head of the Center Party and
leader of the fight to keep the immigrants out, argued the farming
community lacked apartments and jobs to keep its own young people
from moving to the cities.
   On Sunday, Olsson also won a clear endorsement for himself when
his party won 23 seats on the 49-member council, eight more than it
previously held.
   Olof Johansson, national leader of the Center Party, expressed
``deep regret'' at the outcome and indicated Olsson and other local
activists would be expelled from the party.
   ``But Sjobo is special. It is not (like) all of Sweden, thank
God,'' Johansson said.
   Until now, Sweden has not seen the right-wing backlash to
immigration that has affected countries like France and Denmark.
   Analysts attributed the quiet acceptance of foreigners to a
labor shortage and plentiful jobs, and to a tradition of humanism
that was reflected in Sweden's efforts to rescue Jews from Nazi
Germany in World War II.
   But hostility toward newcomers has been evident under the
surface and has occasionally erupted into minor incidents.
   ``A lot of Swedes have a negative attitude toward immigrants. It
is normally surpressed, but having a referendum is bringing it to
the surface,'' said political scientist Anders Sonnerstedt of Lund
University.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
