<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TrailofTears 1stLd-Writethru a0494 09-19 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trail of Tears, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0494,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wagon Train Follows `Trail Of Tears'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to UPDATE with river crossing
completed. PICKS UP 4th graf pvs, `I've got ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A.J. ``Curly'' Weil is a 72-year-old cowboy
who's making a dream come true on the wagon train along the Trail
of Tears, the route taken by Cherokee Indians driven from their
land in the Southeast 150 years ago.
   ``I've always wanted to go on a wagon train trip across the
country and now I'm doing it,'' the crusty Grayville, Ill., retiree
said Sunday night as he unhitched his four-horse team from the
covered wagon he built this summer.
   Weil put his wagon and horses on a ferry and crossed the
Tennessee River to Georgetown this morning, the third day of the
Trail of Tears Commemorative Wagon Train's journey to Tahlequah,
Okla. The journey began in Cleveland, Tenn.
   ``I've got a niece who married an Indian whose great-grandmother
was forced to make this trip back in 1838, when she was just 14,''
Weill said. ``She made it to Oklahoma and lived to be 94.''
   A total of 13,000 Cherokees were forced to give up their land in
the Southeast and resettle in Tahlequah, Okla., a 1,000-mile march
that claimed about 4,000 Indian lives.
   The wagon train train is expected to average 16 miles a day as
it follows the winding route that the Cherokees took as they walked
through Tennessee, Kentucky, Illinois, Missouri, Arkansas and
Oklahoma.
   ``It's not going to be easy, taking a wagon train 1,000 miles,
but I think we can make it,'' said Weil, whose 16-foot wagon was
one of nine camped in a field a mile east of the river Sunday night.
   ``That's three more than we had when we started on Saturday,''
Weil said. ``We'll keep picking up wagons all along the way. It's
hard to tell how many we'll have when we get to Oklahoma.''
   He added, ``My horses ain't broke too good at this point, but
they will before the end of the week.''
   A former oil field construction worker, Weil knows all about
breaking horses and mules.
   ``I've been riding horses all my life,'' he said. ``My dad
homesteaded in western Kansas and I was breaking horses and mules
when I was just a sprout.''
   ``Those were the days,'' he said. ``Now I'm an old man and this
is my last big ride. I'm going to make the most of it. I'm going to
take my wagon across the country.
   ``I'm doing it for all those Cherokee Indians who were forced to
make this trip 150 years ago; I'm doing it for my dad and, the
truth is, I'm doing it for myself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
