<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Gibraltar-IRA     09-19 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gibraltar-IRA,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gibraltar Police Say Warnings Shouted Before Shooting IRA
Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GIBRALTAR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gibraltar policeman testified today he heard
British commandos shout ``Stop! Police!'' before shooting to death
two Irish Republican Army members in this British colony.
   A third IRA guerrilla who was a short distance away also was
shot and killed in the March 6 incident.
   The police officer's statement supported earlier testimony by
Special Air Service commandos that they ``had no alternative but to
shoot'' Mairead Farrell, Daniel McCann and Sean Savage last March
on a Gibraltar street.
   The officer's testimony came on the 10th day of an inquest by
Gibraltar Coroner Felix Pizzarello and an 11-man jury into the
shootings of the three unarmed IRA members.
   Critics of the government of British Prime Minister Margaret
Thatcher have claimed the shootings proves there is an unofficial
``shoot-to-kill'' policy against IRA members. The outlawed IRA
seeks to drive the British from Northern Ireland and unify the
province with the Irish Republic.
   The commandos and British intelligence officers have testified
they believed the three IRA guerrillas possessed a radio-control
device capable of setting off a bomb in a car they had parked near
the site of a changing- of-the-guard ceremony.
   The commandos pumped more than two dozen bullets into the heads
and backs of the three. The commandos testified they had planned to
arrest the three but opened fire when Ms. Farrell and McCann made
threatening movements. Savage was walking nearby.
   Shooting for the head was the only way to eliminate the
possibility one of the three would push a button to set off a bomb,
the commandos said.
   Police found no radio-control device and no bomb in the car
parked by Savage in Gibraltar, although the IRA said the three were
members on active service.
   Two days later police discovered a car packed with 141 pounds of
Czech-made explosives in the coastal resort of Marbella.
   Intelligence officials said the bomb was to be activated by two
electronic timers. They speculated the IRA members parked the first
car in Gibraltar to save a parking space for the car carrying the
explosives.
   The Gibraltar police officer, identified only as ``P,''
testified from behind a curtain that hid him from the public and
the press. He said he was on surveillance near the spot where the
IRA members were killed when he saw two of them approaching,
followed by two commandos.
   ``I distinctly heard a shout of `Stop! Police,' from the
soldiers,'' the officer said.
   He said McCann's hand went to his chest and Ms. Farrell reached
inside the black shoulder bag she was carrying. At that point, the
two commandos opened fire, the officer said.
   The officer said he thought McCann was reaching for a gun and
that Ms. Farrell ``was going for the detonator.''
   ``So the soldiers had no alternative but to shoot,'' said the
commandos' lawyer, Michael Hucker.
   ``Yes, sir,'' the officer responded.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
