<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SingingCabbie     09-19 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Singing Cabbie,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer-Cabbie Killed On Job Memorialized By Friends And Singers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Professional singers gathered in a tiny funeral
chapel in Harlem for a memorial for one of their own, a 44-year-old
basso whose life was music but who was killed while moonlighting as
a cab driver.
   Leslie Dorsey was shot by robbers who stole his money and papers
on Labor Day. Police listed him as a gypsy cab driver with a
tentative identification and it was nearly a week before his family
learned he had been killed.
   He was driving a cab while awaiting scheduled performances in
the chorus of seven New York City Opera productions this season.
   Friends from his childhood, classmates from the old High School
of Music and Art and singers with whom he performed over the years
attended the memorial service Saturday. Some sang favorite songs of
Dorsey's, others reminisced.
   While he did not get enough work to make a living from singing,
Dorsey was a respected performer with nearly perfect pitch and
music was the mainstay of his life, his friends said.
   ``Leslie was always encouraging the rest of us singers to keep
on auditioning and never give up,'' said Janet Jordan, who appeared
with Dorsey in a European tour of ``Porgy and Bess'' in l976.
   Dorsey performed in opera, pop, jazz and rhythm and blues. With
the City Opera he was an associate chorister, a pool of singers
that augments the regular chorus.
   He toured for a year with Judy Collins in 1979 and also worked
with Roberta Flack.
   ``You get a performance, and after the performance you get
temporary work,'' said Barbara Mahajan, an opera singer and part
time church secretary. ``Leslie worked very hard, and he was making
very little money in order to do what he believed in.''
   Dorsey was divorced. He had three children two in college and
one still in junior high.
</TEXT>
