<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush-1stLd-Writethru a0416   09-19 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-1st Ld-Writethru, a0416,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Accuses Dukakis of `Anti-Business Scheme'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 11 grafs new with Bush speech; picks up pvs 4th graf
bgng, On Tuesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE> By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BENSALEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today accused
Michael Dukakis today of pursuing an ``anti-business scheme'' as
Massachusetts governor that has produced higher taxes and soaring
business bankruptcies.
   The vice president told the Bucks County Chamber of Commerce
that his Democratic presidential rival this year ``raised all sorts
of taxes: the income tax, the sales tax and one that might be of
special interest to this audience.''
   That one, he said, involved a cutback in a ``Subchapter S'' tax
law that had the effect of doubling taxes on Massachusetts
businesses employing fewer than 35 people.
   ``A question of attitude,'' Bush said. ``It is here that I think
my opponent fails. Frankly, since he's never been in business, I
don't think he understands the full effect of his own anti-business
scheme.''
   Continuing several days of attacks on Dukakis' home-state
economic record, Bush said the governor is ``out of the
mainstream'' of Democrats by opposing a reduction in the capital
gains tax.
   ``Here is the most telling statistic of all for what a Dukakis
administration might mean for small business,'' Bush said. ``In the
first six months of this year, the number of business bankruptcies
nationally was down by 23.5 percent compared to the same period
last year. In the exact same period, the number of business
bankruptcies was up by 23.7 percent in Massachusetts.''
   Bush said he wants to help small business with overhaul of
product liability laws to keep insurance costs down.
   The vice president also said that between 1980 and 1985 the
number of businesses owned by women increased by nearly 50 percent.
   Bush said 5 million new businesses have been created while
inflation and interest rates have fallen during the eight years of
the Reagan presidency, and that small business firms' earnings rose
9.9 percent in 1987.
   The vice president's planned visit today with Roman Catholic
Archbishop Anthony Bevilaqua and retired Cardinal John Krol was
postponed because of foggy weather that prevented the campaign
plane from landing in Philadelphia.
   Bush planned a light schedule of campaign appearances this week
to give himself time to prepare for his first campaign debate with
Dukakis on Sunday.
   On Tuesday he travels to New Jersey to visit the Annin flag
company, a business he has cited in speeches as a sign that
patriotism has been on the rise during the Reagan presidency. Bush
says flag sales were down when Jimmy Carter was president, but that
after Reagan's election, business was booming again.
   Later in the week, Bush plans a brief campaign trip to Texas.
   As he prepares for the Sunday debate at Wake Forest University
in North Carolina, Bush told reporters he is ``not too good on
these statistics'' and needs briefing time to familiarize himself
with statistical information on various topics that likely will
come up.
   Bush and his team have not been hesitant to mention often that
Dukakis is a debating expert and should be expected to perform well.
   Bush said last week that he isn't nervous about going up against
Dukakis, ``but I'd like to do well.''
   ``He's better than I am'' on technical style, Bush said, adding,
``So I've got to do something else.''
   He said he hoped he would be able to project who he is as a
person, in keeping with his recent efforts to show a compassionate
side.
   ``It has to be what you feel and what you are,'' he told
reporters flying with him last week on Air Force Two.
   But Bush reflected a calm demeanor toward the debate, saying,
``I don't view it as make or break, or the end of the world, or the
biggest moment of my life.''
</TEXT>
