<1ST_LINE>r p AM-WashPrimary     09-19 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wash Primary,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democratic Senate Race Heats Up in Final Stretch, GOP A Shoo-In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HAL SPENCER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When he entered the Democratic race for
U.S. Senate, U.S. Rep. Don Bonker said he relished the
``long-distance'' climb it would take to catch his better known
primary opponent, U.S. Rep. Mike Lowry.
   In the days leading up to Tuesday's primary, Bonker was still
running uphill after Lowry.
   On the Republican ticket, Seattle attorney and former U.S. Sen.
Slade Gorton was considered a shoo-in for the nomination for the
post being vacated by retiring Republican Sen. Dan Evans.
   Gorton's two primary opponents had little name recognition and
even less money. As of Aug. 31 Gorton had amassed $891,110 in
donations.
   Political polls gave Lowry, 49, the edge and then some in the
primary.
   He enjoyed an enormous advantage: The resident of the suburb of
Renton is a far more familiar face in the populous Seattle area,
which he has represented for nearly five terms in the House. Bonker
is from Vancouver, in southwestern Washington on the Columbia River.
   Bonker, 51, leads Lowry in the amount of campaign money raised,
although he spent a huge chunk of it early, trying to make himself
better known to voters. As of Aug. 31, Bonker had collected
$849,694, while Lowry raised $803,000.
   Both candidates spent hundreds of thousands of dollars on
last-minute media buys.
   Bonker, a seven-term congresssman, pinned his final push partly
on a pair of statewide TV ads that painted him as a ``doer,'' and
Lowry as a slightly buffoonish blow-hard.
   Bonker also attacked Lowry as a rebel with the wrong cause among
the state's otherwise unified congressional delegation.
   Lowry just smiled and continued to call Bonker ``an excellent
congressman and good friend.''
   Actually, their records are similar and, despite his moderate
image, Bonker's voting record is as liberal as Lowry's.
   But the two differed on at least two vital but somewhat
parochial issues, neither of which seems to have caught fire among
voters. In fact, in eastern Washington the contest was dubbed the
``Invisible Campaign.''
   Bonker favors a measure, stalled in House committee, that would
allow states to ban the export of raw logs as necessary to pull
small and medium sawmills from an economic slump. Lowry opposes the
idea, saying it would cost jobs, hurt the state's badly depleted
common school fund which depends on timber revenue, and invite
foreign trade retaliation.
   Bonker also favors the basing of a Navy ship in Everett, saying
the home port would produce jobs. Lowry calls that ``home
porking,'' and says it is a waste of tax dollars and an
environmental threat.
   While the two Democrats slugged it out, Gorton was busy blasting
both of them as anti-defense liberals from the same pod.
   Gorton, 60, lost his Senate seat in 1986 to Democrat Brock
Adams. Many felt the upset lay partly in Gorton's icy image and
perception that he had stopped listening to voters.
   Gorton vows to ``hear better, to listen better.'' Among other
things, he opposes higher taxes and favors efforts to control crime
and illegal drugs.
   Also on the Republican ballot is Port Angeles attorney Doug
Smith, 59, a former Pentagon and White House aide under presidents
Nixon and Ford who calls Gorton a ``liberal'' and ``loser.''
   The other GOP hopeful is former state Supreme Court Justice
William Goodloe of Seattle, who said recently that his campaign is
focusing on two issues: The ``sicknesses'' of too much campaign
money flowing from political action committees, and pornography.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
