<DOCNO> AP880919-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1235EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Gorbachev Bjt   09-19 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Gorbachev, Bjt,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev To Complainers In Krasnoyarsk: Perestroika is the Answer</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Promises, promises, promises _ but no action, the
people complained to Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   Perestroika, perestroika, perestroika, he answered, referring to
his program to restructure the economy.
   The Soviet leader logged hundreds of miles last week in a major
trip to check the pulse of the people. The pulse in eastern
Siberia, he found, was rapid _ from anger. He got an earful of
complaints about everything from apartments without hot water to
stores without meat.
   ``I felt it's already impossible to talk to the people,'' the
57-year-old Communist Party general secretary told local officials
on only the second day of a five-day visit to Krasnoyarsk.
   ``Wherever I was _ on the street, in a factory, or here _ the
people are simply at your throat. And I think they're right.''
   Gorbachev was hearing that perhaps more than anything else
Soviets want a better place to live and more food on their tables.
   By choosing Krasnoyarsk for the trip, Gorbachev was asking for
complaints.
   On July 29, he told a plenary session of the party's
policy-making Central Committee in Moscow that medical service and
other ``urgent problems'' were particularly acute in the region,
which is 2,000 miles east of Moscow and encompasses one-tenth of
the entire country.
   Since the plenum, Soviet television, newspapers and magazines
have railed about food and consumer goods shortages and the
resulting long store lines that symbolize the hardships Soviets
endure every day. The media also has complained about the failure
of the government to satisfy the peoples' basic needs.
   Gorbachev has repeatedly said improving the daily lives of
Soviets is a priority in his reform drive. Soviet and Western
economists have said that Gorbachev must offer rewards in the form
of better housing, food, consumer goods and higher pay if he is to
get more work out of people.
   For now, though, people seem unhappy, and Gorbachev returned
Monday from a six-week vacation in the Crimean sun to face angry
complaints shouted at him by residents of a tiny village of
Yemelyanovo near Krasnoyarsk.
   ``We have no hot water. You do what you can to wash,'' one man
shouted.
   Other residents complained about poor medical facilities in the
region, a shortage of housing and a lack of meat in stores.
   The angry streetside exchange in Yemelyanovo and elsewhere,
broadcast on the popular evening news program ``Vremya,'' were a
marked departure from previous citizens' discussions with top
Soviet officials.
   Before Gorbachev took power, citizens largely kept their
complaints to themselves, praising government policies when meeting
with officials or asking uncritical questions. But Gorbachev, with
his populist style, encouragement of openness and his desire to
stay in touch with the people, changed that.
   The leadership emphasized the importance of the trip by making
it one of the longest that Gorbachev has made within the Soviet
Union since he became general secretary in March 1985, and by
devoting hours of television coverage and the front pages of most
newspapers to it daily.
   The leadership's concern was reinforced by another, simultaneous
trip by KGB Chairman Viktor Chebrikov to Vladivostok, a Pacific
port. Chebrikov, who like Gorbachev is a member of the ruling
Politburo, also heard complaints about work and living conditions,
medical cases and shortages of consumer goods.
   Gorbachev did not deny that perestroika had failed to improve
people's lives adequately. His response to the complaints was to
blame local and central officials and people who had not fully
endorsed perestroika and were sticking to the ``old ways.'' Still,
he said, changes for the better are evident in increasing
production of consumer goods, housing and dairy and meat products.
   ``We have policies that are criticized from all sides, but no
one can suggest anything else,'' he said. ``We have a different
mood, different position, different relation to the country and the
people.''
   But he said patience was required because tough times are ahead.
   ``Do you think that I, as general secretary, do not want all the
problems to be solved as soon as possible? How nice it would have
been if we could reach agreement today and have things sorted out
tomorrow.''
   And at the end of the visit on Friday, Gorbachev, sounding like
a cheerleader or politician on the campaign trail, told Krasnoyarsk
party and government officials he had learned that ``Citizens of
Krasnoyarsk have accepted perestroika.'' Then, he asked, ``Am I
making the correct conclusion?'' The audience broke out in
thunderous applause.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Andrew Katell is an Associated Press
correspondent in Moscow.
</TEXT>
