<HEAD>With PM-Burma</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Reviewing Assistance Following Coup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration said today it is
reviewing assistance programs for Burma to determine whether aid
should be cut off or reduced in light of the military coup and
violence in that country.
   ``The United States is deeply concerned about and deplores the
violence that has erupted once again in Burma,'' White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   ``Whatever the country's political problems, they cannot be
solved by Burmese killing one another,'' Fitzwater said.
   ``The United States urges Burmese military authorities
immediately to cease shooting at demonstrators and calls upon those
demonstrating to refrain from provocative actions. It further calls
upon military authorities to enter into discussions with opposition
leaders on arrangements for an early transition to multi-party
democracy, which Burmese in overwhelming numbers are demanding and
which the authorities say they are prepared to grant.''
   ``In light of developments over the past 48 hours, we are
reviewing our assistance programs to Burma,'' the spokesman said.
   The United States is providing $14 million in aid to Burma in
the current fiscal year.
   Fitzwater said the review was being conducted ``with an eye
toward should it (the aid program) be eliminated or changed in any
way.''
