<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bangladesh-Floods     09-19 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bangladesh-Floods,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flood Victims Begin Returning Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FARID HOSSAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people have started
returning to the homes they abandoned when rising waters from
overflowing rivers inundated them more than two weeks ago,
officials said Monday.
   They face the prospect of rebuilding their homes and lives after
most of their meager belongings have been lost.
   Bangladesh is one of the world's poorest nations with a per
capita income of $150 per year. The flooding, the worst in the
nation's history, affected 40 million people, more than a third of
Bangladesh's 110 million population.
   At least 53 of the country's 64 administrative districts were
covered by flood waters at the height of the disaster, officials
said.
   Relief Ministry officials, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said Monday that hundreds of flood victims, mainly in the northern
districts, were leaving relief centers and high dikes where they
sought shelter and returning home.
   ``We have reports that displaced people have started going back
home as flooded rivers have receded, improving the situation,'' one
official said. ``It is difficult to estimate the number of
returnees at this stage.''
   An independent Bengali-language daily, the Sangbad, said more
than 168,000 people affected by floods in Pabna district, 75 miles
northwest of Dhaka, had returned to their homes over the past week.
   ``A major problem the victims are now facing is lack of money to
rebuild their ruined houses,'' the paper said Monday.
   Refugees are still arriving in Dhaka, a city of 6 million
people, in search of food, shelter and jobs. Dhaka's central
Kamalapur rail station is crowded with flood refugees who arrive
daily. At least 2,000 people arrived from other parts of the
country over the weekend, station officials said.
   ``The floods, like a demon, has taken everything _ my house and
crops,'' said Nur Ali, a farmer. Ali, who came to Dhaka with his
wife and two teen-age daughters on Saturday, is living at the
railroad station.
   ``We have been living on the roads for more than two weeks, and
we received barely any relief,'' said Ali, adding that he hopes to
find a job in the capital as a day laborer.
   More than 1 million people are living in the 476 flood-relief
centers set up in Dhaka, which also was badly hit by the flooding.
Food supplies at the centers in the capital are better than those
elsewhere, refugees said. Each day, adults receive one pound of
rice and children one-half pound.
   Several journalists unions in Bangladesh criticized the
government for inadequate relief efforts and said in a statement
Sunday that the government was suppressing facts about the
intensity of flooding and the death toll.
   ``The suppression of facts in such an emergency would be harmful
to the nation,'' the statement said.
   The government death toll from the floods, generally considered
understated, is 1,000. Newspapers, carrying their own daily
tallies, estimate that at least twice as many people have died.
   Of these, newspapers said, nearly 1,000 people died of diarrhea
and other water-borne diseases such as cholera. According to the
reports, more than 1 million people have contracted diarrhea from
drinking the muddy flood water.
   The government says only 200 people have died of diarrhea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
