<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NovelApproach     09-19 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Novel Approach,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Adds History, Facts, to Danielle Steel's Best-Sellers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Eisenbarth waits anxiously to read every
one of Danielle Steel's novels, but she's more than a fan _ her
research provides believable backdrops for the steamy melodramas.
   The friends' working relationship began one day over lunch in
San Francisco, when Ms. Steel was fretting over some factual
details in ``The Ring.'' It was her first hardcover book, published
in 1980, and chronicled three generations of women.
   ``I offered to look some things up, and we went on from there,''
said Ms. Eisenbarth. ``I had no inkling that she would become as
successful as she has, and I had no idea it would be as much fun.''
   Many of Ms. Steel's novels _ which include ``Zoya,''
``Passages'' and ``Fine Things'' _ wind up on The New York Times
best-seller list. In fact, she's had as many as three on the list
at one time. Her books _ 35 in all _ have been published in 27
languages, and more than 85 million copies are in print.
   Ms. Eisenbarth, a history major in college, receives long plot
summaries from Ms. Steel for new books. She then spends nearly four
months researching details of the time period described in the
outline.
   ``She makes up the story and I provide the background,'' Ms.
Eisenbarth, 41, said in a telephone interview from the west Chicago
suburb of Naperville. ``I play a small part in making them seem
realistic.''
   Ms. Steel said her researcher's role is crucial to the success
of her books.
   ``Nancy has been my mainstay for years and years and years,''
Ms. Steel said from her home in San Francisco. ``She's modest in
talking about her role, but her part is really very, very
important.''
   Ms. Eisenbarth's research takes her not to exotic locales, but
to libraries.
   Because Ms. Steel is ``so glamorous and exciting, everybody
thinks my job is glamorous and exciting, but it's really most of
the time in the stacks,'' said Ms. Eisenbarth, who has researched
14 Steel novels.
   She relies on personal diaries, pictures and social histories.
   Ms. Steel insists that every detail be correct, down to the
perfume a historical figure might have worn or the name of a club
where he or she might have gone.
   Still, Ms. Eisenbarth said, there's always one fact in every
book that she has trouble tracking down, and usually finds after
the book is published.
   ``I could not find the color of General Rommel's eyes, so I made
them a glittery blue,'' she said. ``Later I found a (color) picture
and his eyes were clearly brown.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0107 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FERCComplaints     09-19 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FERC Complaints,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioners Say Access To Staff Restricted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two members of the Federal Energy Regulatory
Commission who frequently disagree with one other united Monday in
complaining to a Senate committee that their chairman is cutting
them off from the commission staff.
   ``I do not like the constraints I am laboring under,'' Charles
Stalon, a Democrat who has been behind many of the commission's
deregulatory initiatives, told the Senate Energy and Natural
Resources Committee.
   His colleague, Charles Trabandt, a Republican who has urged a
go-slow policy on further deregulation, said, ``My staff cannot get
the answer to any question without the prior approval of the
chairman and I think that's unfortunate.''
   Trabandt said he thought the ``work product'' of the commission
staff ought to be subject to some kind of review, but he and his
assistants should be able to get ``factual and legal information
available to the staff.''
   ``I do believe I ought to be able to call on the staff to draft
alternative proposals for my fellow commissioners,'' Stalon said.
   By law, the FERC chairman, Martha Hesse, has sole control over
the commission staff, save for personal assistants each of the five
commissioners may hire.
   Ms. Hesse is traveling in Europe and spokeswoman Tamara
Young-Allen said, ``There will be no comment for now.''
   Trabandt and Stalon appeared at a hearing on their renominations
to the commission by President Reagan. With them was Texas oil and
gas consultant Jerry J. Langdon, nominated last month to a vacancy
on the commission.
   The committee earlier approved nominations for the other two
FERC seats as part of a package deal with the White House to break
a year-long deadlock over the makeup of the commission. The deal
gives Democrats three of the five seats but leaves Ms. Hesse, a
Republican, as chairman.
   The complaints from Trabandt and Stalon emerged under
questioning from senators.
   The ranking Republican committee member, Sen. James McClure of
Idaho, said, ``There is some reality to (reports of) difficulties
in the management of the commission.''
   He said he hoped the planned confirmations of the three holdover
commissioners and two newcomers would lead to ``better
relationships inside the commission.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
