<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cuban Flotilla,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Small Human Rights Flotilla Turned Away By Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEY WEST, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small boatloads of Cuban exiles trying
ng to sail to that island nation as a human rights protest returned
here Monday after Cuban coastal authorities turned them back.
   The ``Reunion Flotilla'' was timed to coincide with the visit of
the United Nations Human Rights Commission to Cuba.
   The two boats _ along with two other boats carrying reporters _
were stopped by Cuban gunboats Sunday night, said WSVN-TV reporter
Brian Cabell, who accompanied the flotilla.
   He said two representatives of the group went on board one of
the Cuban gunboats and talked with officials for 15 minutes. The
exiles then decided to return to Key West.
   ``We were never threatened really by the Cubans,'' Cabell said
Monday. ``Though for a few anxious moments we thought we might be
rammed by the gunboat.''
   He said the organizers were satisified they had demonstrated
that Cuba was violating their rights by not allowing Cubans to
enter and leave the country as they pleased.
</TEXT>
