<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People     09-19 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charlton Heston doesn't speak Chinese, but that
hasn't stopped him from directing an all-Chinese cast in the
Beijing debut of the play ``The Caine Mutiny Court Martial.''
   ``Since I know the play very well myself I've been able to
follow the lines quite well in a language I do not understand,''
the Academy Award-winning actor said Monday at a news conference
following two days of rehearsals with the People's Art Theater of
Beijing. The debut is Oct. 18.
   When translations fail, he says, he acts out what he has in mind
and the Chinese actors follow suit.
   ``It's a heady feeling _ it makes you feel you are speaking
Mandarin'' Heston said.
   Heston acted in more than 250 stage performances of the ``Caine
Mutiny'' in the United States, playing the lead role of Captain
Queeg, a World War II Navy captain whose tyranny and mental
instability during a typhoon drove his men to mutiny.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Valerie Harper says she hopes her
victory in the legal battle with Lorimar Television will erase her
image as a ``hellish demon.''
   But Lorimar attorney Don Engle says he is preparing an appeal to
the jury's decision Friday that Miss Harper had been wrongfully
fired from Lorimar's ``Valerie'' series and awarded her $1.4
million compensation for lost wages. She and her husband also were
awarded a percentage of the show's gross profits, which could total
$15 million.
   ``There were so many half-truths, and out-and-out untruths about
me, my performing, about my stability as a person, my psychological
state,'' she said at her Beverly Hills home Saturday. ``It's good
copy, a hysterical woman, particularly with the sexism that's
rampant out there.''
   She says the verdict was sweet. ``It's so nice to see
`wrongfully fired' after all I've seen is fired, fired, fired,''
she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Art Garfunkel, once divorced and once half the
singing team of Simon and Garfunkel, has wed Kim Cermak of the rock
group Lime.
   The non-denominational ceremony was held outdoors Sunday at the
Brooklyn Botanic Garden after hours, said Garfunkel's manager, Ken
Greengrass.
   As a soloist, Garfunkel, 46, has made six albums. He also has
performed in movies including ``Catch-22'' and ``Carnal Knowledge.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paul Schrader, director of the movie ``Patty
Hearst,'' which opens Friday, says the story of the heir to the
Hearst media empire should live on and on.
   ``It's our current-day folklore,'' said Schrader, who is known
for ``American Gigolo'' and ``Mishima.'' ``It was like Polaroid
folklore _ it happened instantly. It turned from a news event into
part of a common folklore in a matter of months.
   ``It will endure because of the inherent elements: an heiress
kidnapped by white revolutionaries wanting to be black, who becomes
involved in bank robberies and other events. It's kind of Billy the
Kid territory,'' he said.
   Patricia Hearst Shaw was kidnapped in 1974 by a terrorist group
calling itself the Symbionese Liberation Army. The FBI captured her
after she had traveled with the group for 19 months. She served two
years of a seven-year jail term before being pardoned by
then-President Carter.
   Mrs. Shaw now lives in Westport, Conn., with her husband,
Bernard, and their two daughters.
</TEXT>
