<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BRF--NewYorkPoll     09-19 0158</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--New York Poll,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Edges Bush in New York State Poll</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis has a slight edge over Vice President George Bush among
likely voters in New York state, according to a poll released
Monday.
   The Marist College Institute for Public Opinion reported that of
601 likely New York voters surveyed last week, 48 percent said they
favored Dukakis while 42 percent chose his Republican opponent. The
number of undecided stood at 10 percent.
   The results signal a statistical dead heat, given a margin of
error of 4 percent in the poll.
   In March, the Marist pollsters reported that 47 percent of New
Yorkers surveyed favored Dukakis, 41 percent preferred Bush and 12
percent were undecided.
   New York, a major battleground state with 36 electoral votes,
has been considered a Dukakis stronghold, because Democrats have a
3-2 lead in registration over Republicans and because Dukakis is
from neighboring Massachusetts.
</TEXT>
