<DOCNO> AP880919-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1538EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RailSafety     09-19 0620</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Safety,0635</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Track Defects Go Unrepaired, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's railroads are ignoring many track
defects reported by their inspectors, some of whom say they've been
ordered to falsify reports by noting only severest problems, The
Pittsburgh Press reported Monday.
   ``I walk the track in the terminal area, do my job, find defects
and put them on my reports, and I just get a world of hell from my
supervisors,'' said Paul Abbott, a track inspector for seven years
and now an assistant track foreman at Norfolk Southern's train
yards in Roanoke, Va.
   Abbott told the Press that as late as mid-August he found dozens
of serious defects in the Roanoke yards, ``far, far more than the
(Federal Railroad Administration) will permit,'' but was told not
to report the safety violations.
   The Press said Abbott's comments were representative of two
dozen inspectors from Conrail, CSX, Boston & Maine, Illinois
Central, Norfolk & Southern, Pittsburgh & Lake Erie and other
railroads who said their supervisors have ordered them to falsify
inspection reports.
   The defects Abbott cited included seven broken rails, six
mismatched rail joints and scores of rotten ties.
   Norfolk Southern spokesman Robert Aumen denied ``forcefully and
unequivocally'' that Abbott had ever been ordered to falsify
inspection reports.
   But on a tape recording, which the newspaper said Abbott made
and union representatives played for FRA inspectors, division
engineer William Schafer tells Abbott: ``All I'm asking you to do,
if you go out and find something, uh, that's an FRA defect that's
not going to cause any derailments, don't put it down on a piece of
paper. There's no way we're going to be able to fix all that.''
   Schafer told the newspaper he never ``instructed anyone to
ignore or overlook unsafe conditions.''
   ``I was trying to maintain this terminal, using good judgment
and the company's resources to its fullest benefit,'' Schafer said.
   Abbott's complaints led to a three-day FRA inspection that found
25 safety violations at the Roanoke yards two weeks ago. All the
defects were repaired, Schafer said last week.
   Top managers at all the railroads said track maintenance is not
being overlooked, but supervisors acknowledged that maintenance
commonly is deferred because of personnel and material shortages
and management's reluctance to take tracks out of service.
   ``Some railroads just don't care about their yards and won't
spend the money to make them safe,'' said William Mitchell, a
senior track inspector with the Ohio Public Utility Commission.
   ``My phone rings all the time with calls from Conrail track and
yard supervisors pleading with me to come and inspect their yards
so I can write up the defects. They say that my report is often the
only way management can be forced to give them a few thousand ties
or some switches or new rail they've been waiting for for months to
make their yards safe to use,'' he said.
   ``I'd say our yard tracks on Conrail are in pretty good shape
for the most part,'' countered Richard Hasselman, Conrail vice
president for operations.
   The newpaper also said that during its nine-month investigation,
it obtained a SOO Line inspection report compiled April 8, 1987,
that called for replacing 27 ties at the precise spot where nearly
a year later a 28-car derailment spewed hazardous chemicals into
the air and forced an evacuation of Annandale, Minn.
   The railroad said the accident occurred because the rails had
widened beyond their proper gauge. The 27 ties, a key to
maintaining proper gauge, never were replaced, the paper said.
   SOO spokesman John Bergene said the railroad's investigation did
not find the damaged ties to be a big factor in the accident and
that investigators have not determined why the rails spread.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
