<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GangViolence 1stLd-Writethru a0468 09-19 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gang Violence, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Anti-Gang Sweeps Bring 870 Arrests, But Violence Rages</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead and 8th graf, ``The violence,'' with 2 grafs to
update with additional death and wounding.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAUREN BLAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police swarmed through gang-infested
territories and arrested nearly 900 people, half of them gang
members, but street violence raged with at least three dead and
nine wounded, authorities said.
    Nearly 400 officers arrested more than 360 people Saturday
night and early Sunday, police said. Officers brought in at least
510 people Friday night.
   ``Part of the purpose is the message to the gang members _ the
message to the community that we're here,'' Police Lt. Fred Nixon
said Sunday. ``We can show it's statistically significant also.''
   More than 200 people have died in gang-related killings in Los
Angeles County this year. Such homicides in the gang-plagued
community of south-central Los Angeles dropped 17 percent from
January through August, with a dramatic 50 percent decline in July
and August alone, according to figures released last week.
   The crackle of gunfire and spilled blood are a weekend ritual in
the grafitti-pocked neighborhoods staked out by street thugs. The
sweeps have been conducted periodically since April.
   This weekend's effort was concentrated south-central Los Angeles
and the San Fernando Valley. More than half those arrested were
suspected gang members, police said.
   The charges ranged from felony drug crimes to misdemeanors.
Police also wrote hundreds of traffic citations and confiscated 66
cars, eight guns, plus cocaine, marijuana, and $1,400 in cash, Sgt.
Larry Mazur said.
   The violence continued Sunday, when one reputed gang member was
slain and a bystander wounded in a drive-by shooting in the
south-central area, authorities said.
   In another gang-related incident Sunday, two suspected gang
members were stabbed and critically wounded during a fight in
Pomona, police said.
   Four males were arrested for investigation of attempted murder
in the brawl, said Sgt. Ron McDonald.
   Less than an hour after the sweeps ended in the San Fernando
Valley, a 22-year-old man was killed and one was wounded in a
drive-by shooting in suburban Sun Valley, police said.
   The motive wasn't known, but investigators said it was
gang-related.
   ``It appears at this time they were totally innocent,''
Detective Mike Coffey said of the victims. ``The car drove by and
for some reason fired shots at them.''
   Just before that attack, two gang members and an innocent
bystander were hit by shots fired from a passing car near the Los
Angeles Memorial Coliseum. Hospital officials refused to release
the victims' conditions.
   An attack Saturday night in the south-central area killed a
16-year-old boy and wounded a 17-year-old, said Lt. Dave Hepburn.
   Investigators said the killing may have resulted from a drug
deal gone bad.
   In another gang-related shooting, a 17-year-old Long Beach youth
riding his bicycle in south-central Los Angeles was wounded Sunday
evening by gunfire from a passing car. He was in stable condition,
said Sgt. Paul Hast.
   Earlier in the weekend, two reputed gang members were booked for
investigation of attempted murder in suburban Burbank after opening
fire on a crowd at a hamburger stand Friday night, Burbank Police
Sgt. Rick Madrid said.
   Officers who were watching the stand because of two other
drive-by shootings in the area during the past two weeks saw
several people limp away after the attack, but nobody reported an
injury to authorities, Madrid said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
