<1ST_LINE>d i AM-US-WesternSahara     09-19 0151</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Western Sahara,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polisario Attack Criticized by U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Monday criticized last
week's reported renewed fighting by Algeria-backed Polisario
guerrillas in the Western Sahara and urged all sides to support
United Nations peace proposals.
   ``The Sept. 16 attack by Polisario forces harms the efforts of
U.N. Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar to develop a formula
for peaceful resolution of the Western Sahara problem,'' spokesman
Charles Redman told reporters.
   ``We call upon the parties to cooperate with the Secretary
General's efforts, which the United States has consistently
supported,'' he added.
   Spain ended colonial rule in 1975 over the sparsely-settled
desert territory and it was annexed by Morocco over the opposition
of Polisario, an independence movement backed by Algeria, Morocco's
eastern neighbor.
   Polisario and Morocco agreed conditionally late last month to a
plan for a U.N.-supervised cease-fire followed by a referendum on
the territory's future.
