<DOCNO> AP880919-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DeltaCrash-Pilot     09-19 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delta Crash-Pilot,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilot Says He's Thankful So Many Survived Crash, Grieves For Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of Delta Air Lines Flight
1141, which crashed on takeoff last month, says he grieves for the
14 people who died but is grateful that 94 people survived the
accident.
   ``I'm so thankful for all those people who were able to get
out,'' Capt. Larry Davis said. ``I felt like when impact began,
that we were all dead.''
   ``I think God saved us from death,'' Davis, 48, told the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram in an interview published Monday.
   Davis said there was no time to pray before the Boeing 727 went
down Aug. 31 at Dallas-Fort Worth International Airport.
   ``Everything happened in 11 seconds and I was totally occupied
with the airplane during that time,'' Davis said at his home south
of Greenville, about 40 miles northeast of Dallas.
   ``At times, I experienced great grief over the people that died
in the accident,'' he said. ``I still have a lot of grief over
that, and I have to admit that to the world.''
   Davis' jaw remains wired shut from facial injuries he sustained,
and he also suffered back injuries. He cannot eat solid food
because of his wired jaw wires, but he said the bands should come
off soon.
   Davis said although he already has been served papers for a
lawsuit filed in connection with the crash, he is confident God
will see him through.
   ``I feel like the Lord is definitely in control of everything
that is taking place and that is going to take place,'' he said.
``I pray that the truth will be known.''
   He would not comment on the cause of the crash when contacted
Monday by The Associated Press.
   Some, including the Greenville City Council, have praised Davis
because so many people survived the accident.
   But Davis says he didn't do anything out of the ordinary.
   ``I think every Delta pilot would do the same thing,'' he said.
``You do everything you can.''
</TEXT>
