<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SmuggledArtifacts     09-19 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Smuggled Artifacts,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smuggled 1,000-Year-Old Peruvian Artifacts Seized</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-one pre-Columbian artifacts smuggled out of
Peru in furniture shipments have been seized in Miami, Customs
officials said Monday. Some of the pieces were 1,000 years old and
worth up to $5,000, they said.
   The cache included pieces of pottery, textiles and wooden items,
which were displayed at a news conference by authorities. They
called it the biggest seizure of antiquities here in recent memory,
and said arrests were expected in the case.
   ``We haven't determined the value,'' said Ken Stroud, head of
the Customs fraud unit. ``But some pieces run from $1,000 up to
$5,000 _ it depends on who's doing the buying.''
   Some of the items were 1,000 years old, according to an
evaluation by the Lowe Museum here, and Peruvian archaeologists
were expected to arrive soon to further identify the artifacts.
   All the pieces had been stamped by the Peruvian government,
showing they were legally registered under that nation's laws,
which forbid exporting antiquities.
   ``If it's removed from Peru, it was either smuggled out or
stolen first and smuggled out,'' Stroud said.
   The artifacts were found in July and August by Miami
International Airport inspectors making routine searches of
Challenge Air flights for drugs, Stroud said. They were hidden
inside furniture shipped here from Lima, Peru. Some of the pottery
had been painted in garish colors to make it look modern.
   Stroud said the airline was not implicated and had cooperated
fully with Customs authorities.
   ``We feel we're getting very close'' to making arrests in the
case, Stroud said. ``We just have a few loose ends to tie up.''
   He said the artifacts were most likely destined for private
collecters, because museums are aware of the legal restrictions in
Peru.
   Customs delayed announcing the seizures while the case was under
investigation, but decided to go public in part because they feared
the pieces would deteriorate in the humid warehouse where they were
stored, Stroud said.
   He said Customs was in contact with the Peruvian Embassy on
Monday to make arrangements to return the antiquities under a
treaty the United States has with that country.
</TEXT>
