<2ND_LINE>AM-Adopted Family,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Luck Improves For Woman `Adopted' By Besieged Businessman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DELRAY BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An impoverished woman ``adopted'' by a
businessman who was then besieged by creditors says she is turning
her life around now that social workers have helped her land a job
and day care.
   James Gisclair promised to ``adopt'' Anita Hunter, 28, and her
five children, move them from a Miami slum, and provide child care
and a job.
   But news coverage of Gisclair's promises brought creditors who
besieged the Boca Raton businessman for payments and pressed him
into court.
   Gisclair did move the Hunters from their hovel-like home and put
them in an apartment here, but because of transportation and
day-care problems, Ms. Hunter said she wound up without work and
with little food for her children.
   Then the state Department of Health and Rehabilitative Services
learned of her plight and moved quickly Friday to help.
   ``It was obvious that she was a motivated woman. She was a prime
candidate for Project Independence,'' said department spokesman Cam
Freedlund. The project offers recipients child care, transportation
to a job and federal rent subsidies.
   ``It's like Jim (Gisclair) started it and HRS finished it,''
said Ms. Hunter, who went to work in an HRS office. ``They finished
the job for him. Everything really has turned out for the best.''
   Meanwhile, 43-year-old Gisclair is scheduled for sentencing Nov.
3 in federal court on a bank fraud charge stemming from a $1.5
million civil judgment. He faces up to two years in prison.
</TEXT>
