<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brite     09-19 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brite,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKVILLE CENTRE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some towns regulate the size of
new houses. Many others have a say in home additions.
   Rockville Centre wants to lord over a common lawn fixture _
``For Sale'' signs.
   Officials call the signs ugly.
   A proposed ordinance would impose a $300 monthly fee on such
signs, to be paid by the homeowner.
   In addition, the ordinance would allow only one sign per
property, limit the sign's size to 3 feet by 3 feet and require
that the sign sit 30 feet from the curb.
   Mayor Eugene Murray says the intent is not to do away with the
signs or to collect money for the village. He says officials want
to improve the quality of the signs and preserve the village's
appearance.
   The village must hold a public hearing on the proposal. Murray
said lawyers for the village are drafting the changes.
</TEXT>
