<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     09-19 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain And Thunderstorms In The Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Moisture from the remains of hurricane Gilbert combined with a
cold front Monday to produce rain over the central part of the
nation, and rain also was scattered over the Northwest.
   Showers and thunderstorms were over much of the lower Ohio
Valley and parts of the upper Great Lakes region and the upper
Mississippi Valley.
   A few showers and thunderstorms were over southern Missouri and
northern Arkansas, and showers lingered over eastern sections of
Nebraska and the Dakotas. High wind caused some tree damage in the
Chesterfield area of West St. Louis County, Mo.
   Fayetteville, Ark., got 1.55 inches of rain in the six hours up
to 2 p.m. EDT.
   A few showers and thunderstorms developed were over the southern
Atlantic Coast states. Charleston, S.C., got 1.12 inches of rain in
the six hours up to 2 p.m.
   Showers also developed ahead of a cold front crossing the
northern Pacific Coast region, and were scattered across the
Pacific Northwest into the northern Rocky Mountain region.
   Temperatures remained in the 40s in the northern Rockies, and
record lows for the date included 20 at Alamosa, Colo.; 23 at
Milford, Utah; and 22 at Richfield, Utah.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 43
degrees at Cutbank, Mont., to 94 at Chandler, Ariz. Monday
morning's low was 10 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   For Tuesday, scattered showers and thunderstorms, developing
ahead of a cold front, were forecast across much of the area from
the central and eastern Gulf Coast to the Great Lakes region and
the northern Atlantic Coast states. Scattered showers were forecast
along another cold front from Montana to western Utah and eastern
Nevada.
   Highs only in the 50s were predicted in western Montana and near
Lake Superior; below 70 across much of the area from the northern
Great Basin of Nevada and western Utah and Pacific Northwest to the
upper Great Lakes; above 80 from the central valleys of California
through southern Arizona and across the southern Plains to the
southern and middle Atlantic Coast; and in the 90s in the desert
Southwest, from south-central Texas to the central Gulf Coast
states, and across southern and central Florida.
</TEXT>
