<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Three Years Probation and Psychiatric Counseling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who pleaded guilty to dropping 66
ground nitroglycerin tablets into his grandmother's coffee was
placed Monday on three years' probation and ordered to undergo
psychiatric evaluation.
   Superior Court Commissioner Irwin Garfinkel imposed the sentence
on Alfred Sevilla, 23, who plead guilty last month to one count of
mingling a harmful substance with food or drink.
   Deputy District Attorney Nikola Mikulicich said he had asked
Garfinkel to order a psychatric evaluation before sentencing and
was disappointed the judge imposed probation before Sevilla was
evaluated.
   ``I don't know if he's a danger to others or not,'' Mikulicich
said. ``I wanted more information.''
   Sevilla faced a maximum of five years in prison.
   The results of Sevilla's evaluation will be given to the court
and the probation department, the prosecutor said. It will be
determined then whether he will be required to undergo counseling.
   Irma Rangel, 67 reported finding crushed, broken and whole pills
in a coffee jar when she started to prepare a cup. No one suffered
any ill effects from the tampering.
