<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel-Satellite 1stLd-Writethru a063Ai-3F 09-19
0538</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel-Satellite, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arab League Concerned About Israeli Satellite</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2 grafs for 6th graf pvs, bgng: ``The satellite ...'' to
UPDATE with Maksoud statement about satellite's potential as spy
system; picks up 7th graf pvs, bgng: ``State Department ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Arab League representative voiced concern
Monday about Israel's launch of a test satellite into orbit and
said it meant the Arabs would have to strengthen their defenses.
   Clovis Maksoud, who represents the Arab League in the United
States, said the satellite gave Israel ``a serious strategic
leverage'' since the country already had the capability to fire
long-range missiles.
   Maksoud, in an interview, stressed steps taken jointly by Israel
and the United States to strengthen their strategic ties.
   He cited Israel's inclusion in the U.S. program to develop a
space-based defense against ballistic missiles and ``Israel's
record which is replete with disclaiming nuclear capability.''
   As a result, Maksoud said, the launching of a test satellite
``warrants enhancing Arab defensive capabilities'' so that any
Mideast negotiations produce a peaceful outcome ``rather than
ratifying Israeli hegemony.''
   The satellite is designed for communications purposes, but the
Arab League official said it could be used to monitor Israel's foes.
   ``We are deeply concerned that such a communications satellite
can be modified into a spy system and, therefore, further enhance
the strategic imbalance which the American-Israeli strategic
agreement has introduced,'' Maksoud said.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman, meanwhile, said
the United States was not involved in any way with the Israeli
program.
   ``We don't have any details of the launch beyond what was
reported by the Israelis,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the U.S. Space Command in Colorado, Cmdr. Dugald
Gillies, said Monday that American radars and sensors picked up the
Israeli satellite shortly after launch. Its orbit has been
calculated to have a high point of 716 miles and a low point of 155
miles, he said.
   ``It is circling the earth every 98.836 minutes and the
satellite has an inclination (to earth) of 142.86 degrees,''
Gillies added. ``It was launched early Monday Eastern Daylight Time
and is in a near polar orbit.''
   Defense officials at the Pentagon said they were unsure exactly
what the satellite's payload included.
   ``But we're leaning toward more of an experimental
communications package as opposed to a true spy satellite,'' said
one source who asked not to be identified.
   ``This launch is impressive because it's a first, but I don't
think this particular satellite is going to offer much more ability
to keep tabs on their neighbors,'' the source said.
   Redman stressed that Israeli leaders had given public assurances
that their goal was ``peaceful purposes of space research and
technological advancement.''
   Israel is the eighth nation to place a satellite into space. The
country is one of the most advanced technologically in the world
and is generally believed to have nuclear capability.
   Israeli leaders, preferring to keep potential foes off guard,
have responded ambiguously to such assertions but also have given
assurances the country would not initiate a nuclear conflict.
   Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and Foreign Minister
Shimon Peres said the launch should not touch off an arms race with
Arab countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
