<DOCNO> AP880919-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2020EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d w AM-Congress-UN     09-19 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-UN,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conservatives Move To Block Release Of U.S. Payments To U.N.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Republican members of Congress have
introduced a resolution that would withhold part of the U.S. dues
payments to the United Nations that President Reagan ordered
released last week.
   The resolution, introduced by Sen. Jesse Helms of North Carolina
and Rep. Pat Swindall of Georgia, would block the release of $28.8
million of the $144 million that Congress appropriated to the
United Nations in fiscal 1988.
   Swindall said he introduced the resolution Friday because
Reagan's decision to release the dues payments ``cripples
congressional efforts to reform the U.N.'s anti-American programs.''
   Congress ordered the Reagan administration last year to withhold
part of the U.S. dues until Reagan certified that the United
Nations was making progress toward reducing its staff, adopting new
budget procedures and ending Soviet abuses of the U.N. civil
service system.
   Reagan made that certification last week in announcing that the
U.S. would release the $44 million withheld from its dues payment
in fiscal 1988 and would pay the full $144 million appropriated for
fiscal 1989.
   The 1987 law authorizing the U.N. dues payment specifies that
Congress can block payment of the final 20 percent of the dues if
it approves a joint resolution within 30 days of the president's
certification.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
