<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0577,0718</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>22 West Bank Educational Programs Closed, Spurring Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 13th grafs to UPDATE with passports of Americans
seized, more casualties, army comment; PICKS up 8th pvs: Israel
has...; ADDS four grafs with detail on passports.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel closed 22 adult education programs in
the West Bank Monday as part of a new offensive against Palestinian
activists in the occupied lands, prompting protests by hundreds of
Palestinians, witnesses said.
   In the occupied Gaza Strip, meanwhile, an 18-year-old
Palestinian died of wounds he received in clashes with Israeli
troops last week, his relatives said.
   The death raised to 269 the number of Palestinians who have died
in the 9-month-old uprising in the occupied territories. Six
Israelis also have died.
   Soldiers shot and wounded four Arabs Monday, including a
15-year-old boy struck in the stomach, after Palestinian protesters
stoned soldiers in the West Bank towns of Nablus and Qalqiliya,
hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed three Palestinians were wounded in clashes in
Nablus and Qalqiliya and in the West Bank town of Jenin.
   Also Monday, the army said it confiscated the passports of six
Americans who allegedly took part in the anti-Israel protest.
   One of the Americans, 33-year-old Bill Doares of New York, told
The Associated Press that an army officer grabbed the passports
without explanation after the group watched from a distance as
troops fired rubber bullets to break up a peaceful protest by
Palestinian women.
   The latest casualties brought to 46 the number of Palestinians
wounded in the last three days. The Haaretz daily attributed the
rising numbers of Palestinian casualties to the widening use of
plastic bullets, and said soldiers are permitted to fire them even
if their lives are not in danger.
   Haaretz quoted military sources as saying this allowed troops to
be as tough as possible with demonstrators without risking large
numbers of Arab fatalities. Unlike live ammunition, plastic bullets
generally are not lethal except when fired from a distance of 20
yards or less.
   The army declined comment except to say soldiers must adhere to
strict, unspecified rules when using plastic bullets.
   In Nablus, the West Bank's largest city, troops closed 22 adult
education programs that taught courses in computer programming,
mathematics, chemistry and English, Palestinian witnesses said.
   The action was part of an ongoing Israeli effort to stifle the
growth of a grass-roots Palestinian leadership in the occupied
lands.
   ``We didn't have any choice but to close them down,'' said an
official of the West Bank military government, speaking on
condition of anonymity. ``These programs are part of an all-out
effort by pro-PLO elements to replace the system run by Israel.''
   Israel has shut down more than 320 trade unions, professional
organizations and local committees in the West Bank and Gaza. In
addition, all schools in the West Bank and middle schools and high
schools in Gaza remain closed on army orders. Israel contends they
are breeding grounds for violent protests.
   Monday's closures prompted widespread protests in Nablus, where
hundreds of Palestinians marched in the city's open-air market
waving outlawed Palestinian flags and chanting anti-Israeli
slogans, Arab witnesses said.
   Dozens of school children flew kites bearing the red, green,
yellow and black colors of the Palestinian flag, the witnesses said.
   Also in Nablus, 200 masked supporters of the militant Islamic
group Hamas, or Zeal, held a separate march during which
protesters, who wore white T-shirts emblazoned with ``Hamas,''
carried Palestinian flags and Islamic banners.
   The American passports were confiscated Sunday in the West Bank
city of Ramallah, an army official said. He said the group
participated in an anti-Israeli protest and was detained. ``They
ran away, leaving the passports,'' said the official.
   But Doares denied the group joined the protest and said they
would refuse a police demand to submit to questioning before having
their passports returned.
   The group of community activists is touring the occupied lands
at the invitation of the San Francisco-based Palestine Solidarity
Committee.
   The U.S. Consulate in Jerusalem asked Israeli officials to look
into the matter, said consulate spokesman David Good. ``Our
position is that American passports are U.S. government property
and should not be taken,'' Good said.
</TEXT>
