<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Dornan-AIDS     09-19 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dornan-AIDS,0620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Wife Reveals Brother Is Dying of AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GARDEN GROVE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of conservative Rep. Robert
K. Dornan apologized to a gay community leader she called a ``fag''
at a meeting and later revealed her brother is a homosexual who is
dying of AIDS.
   Dornan, R-Calif., afterward told reporters he knew his
brother-in-law was a homosexual, but did not know that he has
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``Why didn't you tell me?'' he asked his wife, Sallie, after she
told reporters that one of her four brothers is a homosexual and is
dying of AIDS.
   ``I didn't want to hurt you,'' she said.
   The Dornans declined to be interviewed further on the issue
Monday.
   ``They regard this as a personal matter that they don't want to
continue publicly talking about it ... not out of any shame for
themselves or the family, but for the privacy for the brother,''
said Dornan's chief aide, Brian Bennett.
   Bennett refused to name the brother. He said Dornan's family and
Mrs. Dornan's family had not always gotten along, in attempting to
explain why Dornan did not know about his brother-in-law's illness.
   Dornan is seeking a third two-year term.
   The relevation occurred at a so-called town meeting Sunday held
by Dornan at Pacifica High School to meet with constituents. The
school is in Dornan's district, about 30 miles southeast of
downtown Los Angeles.
   During a heated exchange between her husband and Jeff
LeTourneau, a gay activist, Mrs. Dornan screamed, ``Shut up, fag.''
   Then LeTourneau and about 30 other chanting protesters were
escorted from the auditorium by police at Dornan's request.
LeTourneau was allowed to return and pose the last question, and he
demanded an apology from Mrs. Dornan.
   ``I'm very sorry I did that,'' said Mrs. Dornan, her voice
breaking. ``You were all yelling at my husband, whom I love.
   ``I apologize, but it will not rid the anger in my heart. My
brother is dying and he grows thinner every day and has sores on
his body. ... I want you to understand there's great anger and pain
inside of me.''.
   She said later that gay activists like LeTourneau were trying to
make the AIDS crisis into a civil-rights issue instead of a medical
issue.
   ``A plague doesn't have any civil rights,'' Mrs. Dornan said.
   LeTourneau, an organizer of the Orange County Visibility League,
a gay rights group, accepted Mrs. Dornan's apology and asked Dornan
if he would support federal subsidies to AIDS sufferers to purchase
the drug AZT, or azidothymidine, which was recently approved for
AIDS treatment by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration.
   ``Of course,'' said Dornan. ``It extends the precious thing we
call human life.''
   AZT is not a cure but has been found to prolong the lives of
some victims by strengthening their immune systems. AIDS attacks
the body's immune system, leaving victims susceptible to infections
and cancers.
   Before Dornan's town meeting, LeTourneau had organized a rally
of the gay rights group to protest what they say is Dornan's
anti-homosexual stand.
   In his defense, Dornan, said he contributed part of his $12,400
congressional pay raise to help AIDS hospices and called a news
conference in January 1987 to publicize the enormity of the issue.
   ``I've lost friends and people I know to AIDS,'' Dornan said.
``Terry Dolan was a good friend.''
   Dolan, head of the National Conservative Political Action
Committee, died of complications of AIDS. Dornan said he also was
acquainted with conservative lawyer Roy Cohn and entertainer
Liberace, who attended his church at one time, who also died of
complications from AIDS.
</TEXT>
