<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1928EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Debate-Talks     09-19 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Debate-Talks,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Campaign Proposes Using Anchormen As Moderators</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aides to Democrat Michael Dukakis proposed
Monday that the news anchormen of four commercial television
networks serve as the questioners in upcoming presidential debates,
but sources said the idea was rejected by George Bush's advisers.
   Aides to the Republican presidential hopeful responded with a
list of proposed moderators and questioners from both print and
electronic media. As of late Monday, the Dukakis campaign had not
agreed to the idea, sources said.
   Only six days before the first debate, the campaigns are still
sparring over the arrangments for the televised confrontations
between Bush and Dukakis.
   The first debate, sponsored by the parties' commission on
debates, is scheduled Sunday at Wake Forest University. The second
presidential debate is due Oct. 13 or Oct. 15 in Los Angeles _
sponsored by the League of Women Voters.
   The late round in the pre-debate sniping came as Dukakis
campaign chairman Paul Brontas called James Baker, his counterpart
in the Bush camp, on Monday.
   Sources famiiliar with the talks who spoke only on the condition
they not be identified said Brountas suggested that the anchors
from CBS News, ABC News, NBC News and the Cable News Network be the
moderators and questioners during both presidential debates and the
vice president debate scheduled Oct. 5 in Omaha.
   That would mean CBS's Dan Rather, NBC's Tom Brokaw, ABC's Peter
Jennings and probably CNN's Bernard Shaw would be on stage for all
three events.
   ``This is a television event,'' said one Dukakis aide of the
idea. ``We want to do what we can to make it an event that people
will pay attention to. We think that they anchors would make it a
bigger event...More people would watch it.''
   But a top Bush adviser said the idea was turned down ``as
blatantly unfair to the print media and other television
correspondents.''
   This source said Bush responded later Monday with a list of four
proposed moderators and 10 panelists. The source would not name any
of them, saying only the list was made up of network anchors,
network correspondents and print representatives.
   The Bush source took the occasion to accuse the Dukakis campaign
of violating the agreement not to talk about such matters.
   ``We are operating under a written agreement of understanding
not to discuss the negotiations surrouding'' debate details, said
the aide. ``Obviously that has been violated,'' and thus the source
gave the Bush campaign position on the matters.
   The pre-debate sparring is typical of presidential debate
negotiations. What is different in 1988 is that the campaigns are
negotiating directly, rather than with an involved third party like
the League of Women Voters.
   With the effort by the two political parties to take the
sponsorship of the debates away from the league _ which has done it
for the past three presidential campaigns _ the two campaigns have
squabbled more directly on these matters than in the past.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
