<1ST_LINE>r n AM-Quayle 1stLd-Writethru a0595 09-19 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0595,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede KNOXVILLE, Tenn.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Quayle: Dukakis Caused Economic Manacle, Not Miracle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Casper remarks, picking up 3rd graf pvs,
``Michael Dukakis did not....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CASPER, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle ridiculed Michael Dukakis'
defense posture on Monday and accused the Democrat of causing ``an
economic manacle'' rather than a miracle in his home state of
Massachusetts.
   At rallies in Knoxville, Tenn., and on the start here of a
four-day western swing, the Republican vice presidential candidate
hammered at Dukakis' record on both pocketbook and national
security issues.
   ``The West has a lot of big, open spaces _ just like the Dukakis
defense record,'' Quayle told the crowd of about 250 in Casper. He
laughed at the pose Dukakis struck last week in Michigan when he
donned a helmet and rode in a tank.
   ``In just one week, his defense policy went from general
confustion to Gen. Patton,'' the Indiana senator said.
   Earlier, he faced down persistent hecklers at a noontime rally
at an outdoor shopping mall in downtown Knoxville, in Republican
East Tennessee. Quayle said his aim was to ``burst the bubble'' of
Dukakis' reputation as a competent administrator.
   In Casper, he excoriated ``the man from Massachusetts'' on gun
control, his opposition to the death penalty, and on a
Massachusetts prison furlough program that Quayle said ``let on
average one first-degree murderer out on furlough each day'' since
1983. The furlough program has since modified to exclude murderers.
   Later, Quayle was headed to Boise, Idaho, the 30th state he has
campaigned in.
   In Knoxville, he charged Dukakis with driving citizens away from
Massachusetts with high taxing and spending _ higher spending per
capital than any other state.
   ``Michael Dukakis did not create an economic miracle in
Massachusetts. He created an economic manacle ... that inhibits
private sector expansion at the expense of public sector
expansion,'' Quayle said.
   The Indiana senator told the rally, ``The last thing in the
world he should want this campaign to be about is competence. ...
The record of Michael Dukakis as governor of Massachusetts is not
something of which to be proud.''
   Quayle said Massachusetts ranks 40th out of 50 states in total
employment growth and 45th in manufacturing job growth. The state
actually lost 90,000 manufacturing jobs between June 1984 and
January 1988, he said.
   Several dozen pro-Dukakis demonstrators positioned themselves
near the front of the crowd of 750, waving signs and making
catcalls.
   ``Don't worry about the yellers. You know if you had to support
Dukakis, you'd be yelling too,'' Quayle said in his sole digression
from the speech.
   The Indiana senator charged Dukakis had earned the title ``Mr.
Tax Hike'' and ``Mr. Job Loss,'' not ``Mr. President.''
   Quayle conceded that Massachusetts has a low unemployment rate,
but said that is because ``people are leaving Massachusetts.''
   Quayle said Dukakis ``raised virtually every tax in
Massachusetts _ sales taxes, personal income taxes, business taxes,
taxes on cigarettes, gas, beer and wine.'' The state legislature,
not the governor, deserves credit for taxes that were cut during
Dukakis' three terms, Quayle said.
   Quayle claimed, ``He has presided over horrendous growth in the
debt of Massachusetts and ... has created more debt than all
previous governors of Massachusetts combined.''
   Massachusetts, like most states, is required by its constitution
to operate on a balanced budget. Quayle aides said he was referring
not to its operating budget, but bonded indebtedness.
   David Prosperi, Quayle's press secretary, said, ``He's not the
only one who's doing it, but we're pointing out the fact that he's
issuing debt to come up with a balanced budget _ debt though
bonds.''
   Quayle ate a fast lunch at a Greek restaurant, Peroulas', before
departing Knoxville.
   Quayle flies from Boise to Las Vegas Tuesday, then moves on to
Phoenix and California before heading home.
   The Republican ticket is rated solidly ahead of the Democrats in
the Mountain states and Nevada, while a tight race is forecast in
California for its 47 electoral votes.
</TEXT>
