<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     09-19 0262</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Africa,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Still No Decision by Anti-Apartheid Activists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three anti-apartheid activists taking refuge
in a U.S. consulate in South Africa still have not decided whether
to accept the South African government's offer to leave without
fear of rearrest, a State Department spokesman said Monday.
   The American Embassy in Pretoria, South Africa, said after the
three fled from detention in a hospital to the consulate in
Johannesburg a week ago that the United States would not force them
to leave against their will. It is against U.S. policy, however, to
grant them asylum at a diplomatic mission, the embassy said.
   Thus ``the three men remain in temporary refuge,'' State
Department spokesman Charles Redman told reporters.
   In South Africa, he said, ``We have explained what our policy
is, and what we are doing, and where we stand.''
   The three activists are Murphy Morobe and Mohammed Vallio Moosa,
of the United Democratic Front, and Vusi Khanyile, chairman of the
National Education Crisis committee.
   U.S. civil rights activist Jesse Jackson met for an hour last
Wednesday with South African Ambassador Pieter Koornhof for a talk
that both described as positive.
   Asked whether the U.S. government regards Jackson as an
intermediary in the affair, Redman said, ``There is no U.S.
intermediary role in the sense that you are referring to, and I am
not sure what contact that Mr. Jackson has had with the people in
the consulate.''
   Jackson planned to make some telephone calls to South Africa,
but his office in Chicago said they had not yet been made.
</TEXT>
