<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0625 09-19 0815</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0625,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Accuses Dukakis of Being `Anti-Business,' Dividing Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 10th pvs, The vice...raise taxes,''
to give reaction from Massachusetts businessman, EDITING 11th graf
pvs, In Boston,... economic record.
^By TOM RAUM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BENSALEM, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, warming up for his
debate with Michael Dukakis this weekend, accused his Democratic
rival Monday of being ``anti-business'' and pursuing a
divide-and-conquer campaign strategy aimed at polarizing Americans.
   ``He's begun a calculated strategy of emphasizing differences
between rich and poor, between one region of the country and
another,'' the vice president told the Lower Bucks County Chamber
of Commerce.
   The luncheon speech, in which Bush offered himself as the
champion of small business, was his only public event Monday. He
returned to Washington afterward to prepare for his first
nationally televised debate with Dukakis in Winston-Salem, N.C.,
Sunday night.
   Campaign spokeswoman Sheila Tate said the GOP nominee planned to
spend most of the week getting briefings from policy aides and
taking part in ``mock debates,'' with economic adviser Richard G.
Darman standing in for Dukakis.
   Campaign sources said Bush soon will propose a ``parental
leave'' program that would use tax incentives to encourage business
companies to give parents time off to care for children.
   Until now, Bush has made only vague mention of such a plan,
saying that women should not have to worry about getting their jobs
back after a pregnancy or finding time to care for a sick child.
   The Reagan administration has opposed parental job leaves.
   The vice president used three charts and a flurry of statistics
in his speech here to demonstrate what he claimed was Dukakis' poor
treatment of businesses as governor of Massachusetts.
   ``Frankly, since he's never been in business, I don't think he
understands the full effect of his own anti-business scheme,'' Bush
said.
   The vice president asserted that in the first six months of this
year, the number of business bankruptcies had fallen nationally but
risen in Massachusetts. Moreover, Bush, said, ``he clearly wants to
raise taxes.''
   In Boston, the Dukakis campaign called together eight
Massachusetts business leaders who support the candidate. ``I can't
believe how anyone can say that the Massachusetts economy is not
conducive to business,'' said one of them, Bernard J. O'Keefe,
chairman of an electronics manufacturing firm and recent chairman
of the National Association of Manufacturers.
   ``I've been to every state in the union and I can assure you
that there is not a state in the union that comes anywhere near
close to Massachusetts as an environment for growth and
employment,'' he said.
   And Dukakis campaign manager Susan Estrich said Bush ``went to
lunch today and served up another plate of whoppers'' about the
governor's economic record.
   ``George doesn't know what he's talking about when he calls Mike
Dukakis anti-business,'' she said, citing four private, independent
rankings that applauded a favorable business climate in
Massachusetts.
   On bankruptcies, she said the rate of business failures in
Massachusetts was less than half the the national rate during the
eight years of the Reagan administration, and had fallen by 28
percent since Dukakis became governor in 1983.
   She also said Bush was ``flat wrong'' in charging that Dukakis
had effectively doubled taxes on certain small businesses in
Massachusetts.
   The state gave companies with fewer than 35 shareholders a $15
million tax break in 1985, but when the federal tax overhaul law
took effect, the state's revenue loss nearly tripled.
   As a result, Dukakis and the legislature amended state law to
restrict the tax break to corporations that grossed $6 million or
less annually, thus disqualifying 750 larger companies that had to
pay a higher corporate rate.
   
   
   
   
   Bush said the current economic expansion is ``tough news for my
opponent to swallow,'' so as the campaign heats up, ``he's pursued
a strategy of dividing Americans.''
   Said Bush: ``I understand the motivation. He won't win unless he
convinces the electorate that everything is bad in America.''
   ``I am dismayed by the divide-and-conquer strategy,'' Bush said.
   The vice president expressed support for federal limits on
certain lines of liability lawsuits in an effort to trim business
insurance costs.
   ``In our litigation-happy society, high insurance rates and
outrageous awards threaten to put some companies out of business,''
Bush said.
   He promised to work with Congress to produce legislation aimed
at lowering the cost of product liability insurance.
   The vice president was forced to postpone plans for a meeting
with Roman Catholic Church leaders in Philadelphia on Monday
because fog prevented his plane from landing there.
   A Bush supporter, Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., told reporters he
doesn't agree with Bush when he speaks critically of the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   Bush frequently accuses Dukakis of being ``a card-carrying
member of the ACLU.''
   ``There is nothing wrong with belonging to the ACLU,'' said
Specter, a former prosecutor.
</TEXT>
