<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-SouthAfrica     09-19 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-South Africa,0723</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Chief To Make First Visit in Five Years To South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. Secretary-General will make his first
visit to South Africa in five years on Wednesday for peace talks
with white minority leaders of the nation isolated and condemned by
the world body as racist.
   He then holds peace talks in Angola.
   U.N. officials said Monday that Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar will confer with President P.W. Botha in Pretoria, the
South African capital, from Wednesday to Friday on implementing a
U.N. plan for the independence of Namibia, or South-West Africa.
   The officials declined to discuss his schedule in South Africa
or say whether he will meet with black leaders.
   But South Africa's new U.N. ambassador, Jeremy B. Shearar, told
The Associated Press he doubted the secretary-general would meet
opposition leaders.
   ``I think we could assume he is not going to complicate this
short visit,'' Shearar said in a telephone interview.
   ``We are dealing with a topic which has occupied us and the U.N.
for some 40 years and it would not be sensitive for anybody to try
to deal with other issues ... It (meeting opposition leaders) could
cloud the issues,'' he said.
   Perez de Cuellar ``trusts that his visit will help expedite the
implementation'' of a U.N. independence plan for Namibia, Security
Council Resolution 435 of 1978, a U.N. announcement of the visit
said.
   South Africa has been governing Namibia under a mandate issued
by the now-defunct League of Nations after World War I and rejected
the U.N. resolutions.
   South Africa has said it is willing to grant independence to
Namibia by next June 1 if the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops
supporting the Marxist government in neighboring Angola have left
by that date.
   A U.N. observer team is expected to oversee the transition to
independence, beginning in November.
   Shearar said the visit ``is coming at a very important
juncture'' since the United Nations shortly will be involved in the
peace process. ``It is very important that the process should have
an impulse from the secretary-general himself,'' he said.
   A feeling exists in South Africa, Shearar said, ``that the U.N.
cannot be impartial on these (southern African) issues and we think
it is hopeful that he should be there and demonstrate his
impartiality and that of the Secretariat.
   ``We think both ourselves and the United Nations have a great
deal to gain from the visit.''
   Shearar said he hoped no one would raise ``extraneous issues''
on the independence of Namibia and the withdrawal of Cuban troops
from Angola. ``We are looking forward to reaching an understanding
and a commitment on the part of the Angolans and the Cubans for
their withdrawal. And their presence too close to the border oculd
inhibit free and fair elections,'' he said.
   Shearar said he hoped the peace process in southern Africa
eventually would lead to a restoration of South Africa's voting
rights and participation in the General Assembly. The Pretoria
government was stripped of its voting rights in 1974.
   ``We hope that during the negotiations that go on, people will
see what is happening in South Africa and see a general commitment
to reform,'' Shearar said.
   ``Maybe it's not such a bad idea to have South Africa's voice
back in the corridors of the General Assembly ... They may find it
is sensible to deal with us rather than isolate us because that
will not sort our our internal problems.''
   ``I would greatly look forward to being permanent representative
when we resume our seat in the General Assembly, but there is a lot
of ground to cover before that happens,'' the envoy he said.
   In Angola, Perez de Cuellar will confer with President Eduardo
dos Santos on the situation in the area, U.N. officials said.
   South Africa regularly is denounced by the United Nations and
the Security Council for apartheid, its rule over Namibia, and
reported undermining of neighboring states.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which South Africa's 26 million blacks have no vote in
national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and
maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
