<DOCNO> AP880919-0155 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2036EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-Rebels     09-19 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Rebels,0497</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Impose Transport Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus service came to a virtual
standstill Monday after leftist rebels called for a nationwide
transportation ban and threatened drivers who took to the roads.
   Despite assurances from the military that transportation would
be protected, a vast majority of bus and truck drivers chose to
park their vehicles.
   Only a handful of buses, the main means of mass transit,
circulated in this capital city of 1 million inhabitants. More than
70 percent of the urban bus traffic was halted and inter-city
service was even more severely curtailed, an official of the bus
owners' association told The Associated Press.
   A dispatcher at one of the capital's two terminals said 90
percent of the bus service between provinces was stopped.
   Local radio stations with correspondents in all 14 provinces
also said the ban was about 90-percent effective.
   Workers had to walk to their jobs or pay inflated fares to
pickup truck and van owners, who turn significant profits during
such bans. Dozens of overcrowded small trucks and vans circulated
through downtown.
   There were fewer private cars on the roads, but public
transportation was more severely curtailed.
   The ban on bus and truck traffic was the fifth called this year
by the Marxist-led guerrilla army, which has been waging a nearly
9-year-old war against the U.S.-backed government.
   The government had repeatedly urged on broadcast media that
Monday's ban be ignored, saying the military would protect vehicles.
   The ban is indefinite. Previous bans this year, during which
about 35 vehicles were burned, lasted three days each.
   Col. Mauricio Vargas, the army chief of operations, told YSU
radio that about 13,000 soldiers were providing and protecting
transport.
   ``We refuse to allow a violent minority to impose its will on
us,'' he said.
   Soldiers rode shotgun aboard several state-owned buses
circulating in the capital and some army trucks carried passengers
to and from the city outskirts. Lorgio DeLeon, a 48-year-old father
of six, was stranded at the eastern bus terminal with no way to get
to his tailor's job in Zacatecoluca, 35 miles southeast of San
Salvador.
   ``This hurts the poor worker more than anyone. We don't work
today, we get our pay docked,'' he said. ``The person who has some
capital, he just stays home, where he has everything.''
   Rebels of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front said the
ban was in response to what it termed official repression. The
guerrillas, in announcing the ban, referred to the actions of riot
troops who broke up a Sept. 13 demonstration by leftist university
students.
   The troops used tear gas and clubs and fired shots in the air to
disperse nearly 3,000 students at that protest. About 250
demonstrators were arrested.
   All but 14 were subsequently released, with the remainder
charged with what the government called ``terrorist acts.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2045EDT</FILEID>
