<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TrailofTears     09-19 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trail of Tears,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wagon Train Follows ``Trail Of Tears''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STRAT DOUTHAT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Trail of Tears Commemorative Wagon
Train crossed the Tennessee River on Monday, the third day of its
1,000-mile journey to Oklahoma.
   Eight covered wagons were taken across the quarter-mile expanse
of water on a tug-operated ferry connecting state Route 60 midway
between Georgetown and Madison.
   The crossing went without a hitch, although one wagon had to be
pushed onto the barge when the mule team pulling it was unable to
get any footing on the slick metal approach ramp.
   ``This was our second big hurdle and it went off just fine,''
said Ray Morris of Golconda, Ill., the project coordinator. ``Our
first hurdle was just getting the wagon train on the road Saturday;
that was a miracle considering the short time we had putting this
project together.''
   The wagon train departed Saturday morning from Red Clay State
Historical Park, 15 miles east of Cleveland. After three days of
traveling, the eight covered wagons had covered slightly more than
50 miles.
   Although the project is designed to commemorate the 150th
anniversary of the removal of the Cherokee Indians from the
Southeast in 1838, as of Monday no Cherokees had traveled with the
wagon train.
   ``We did invite the Cherokees in Oklahoma to join us but they're
a poor people and couldn't afford to pay their own expenses for a
76-day trip,'' said Morris, an agricultural adviser for the
University of Illinois.
   Morris said the university was continuing to pay his salary
while he made the trip because the journey is seen as a cultural
contribution to the community. However, he said there were no funds
available to finance Indian participation.
   ``The state of Illinois gave us $1,000 and some of the
communities along the way have promised to provide free services
such as meals and feed for our animals,'' he said. ``Otherwise
we're paying our own way.''
   Meanwhile, Harley Grant of Chattanooga, the interim chairman for
Tennessee's Commission on Indian Affairs, said he was surprised
that the Cherokees had not played a greater role in the project.
   Grant added that the Cherokees had been indirectly invited to
participate in the project several months ago.
   ``But most of us work for a living and were unable to make the
journey from day to day,'' he said.
   Morris said he expected some Cherokees to join the wagon train
as it moved further westward. He also noted that the journey will
end at Tahlequah, Okla., the capital of the Cherokee Nation.
   ``There will be a big observation at the Cherokee Reservation
when we get there, in early December,'' he said. ``And, too, we did
receive a letter of recognition from Wilma Mankiller, the principal
chief of the Cherokees.
   In her letter, Mankiller thanked the participants for
commemorating the Cherokees' terrible ordeal. Grant also said he
thought the wagon train project was a good idea.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
