<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0604 09-19 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Too Many Americans `Treading Water'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with remarks in Texas, INSERT four grafs after 7th
pvs, ``We don't ... the polls, and picking up 8th pvs, Dukakis
offered...energy policy, editing that graf for transition.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Monday that many
Americans are ``treading water'' after eight years of Reaganomics
and still awaiting the economic recovery trumpeted by the
Republicans.
   ``After eight years in power, the Republican party seems to have
exhausted its reservoir of ideas,'' Dukakis said in a speech that
echoed refrains from John and Robert Kennedy's campaigns.
   ``In their hearts they know that four more years of Reaganomics
would be bad for the country and that four more years of
Reaganomics without Reagan would be a disaster.''
   ``We can do better than that,'' Dukakis said as he set out on a
two-day Southern swing.
   He said Republican prosperity means young families having to
postpone having children, kids going home to an empty house at the
end of the day because their mothers must work and can't afford
child care, and 40 million Americans without health insurance.
   ``Mr. Bush doesn't seem to understand that. I do,'' he said as
he set out on an abbreviated week of campaigning to allow him ample
time to prepare for next Sunday's campaign debate.
   ``We don't need a warmed over call to selfishness; we need a new
call to greatness,'' said the Massachusetts governor, who is
struggling to reverse Bush's recent gains in the polls.
   From Arkansas, Dukakis flew to Texas for a joint appearance with
vice presidential running mate Lloyd Bentsen.
   In a speech about energy policy, Dukakis said he would convene a
bipartisan energy summit with congressional leaders shortly after
taking office. The summit would be chaired by Bentsen, a Texas
senator.
   Dukakis accused Bush of tailoring his position to the region of
the country he's campaigning in, saying in Texas he was in favor of
offshore drilling but saying in California he was against it.
   ``George Bush is like a coin: they just flip him and sometimes
he lands on his head, and sometimes he lands on his tail,'' Dukakis
said to the laughter of his audience of 1,000 people.
   Dukakis offered no new proposals in his Little Rock speech,
although aides said he would be making some recommendations over
the next few days in speeches devoted to health insurance and
energy policy.
   Advisers said the first appearance of the campaign swing was
designed to show Dukakis is attuned to the concerns of average
people, and the Democratic presidential nominee was warmly
applauded when he vowed to ``stand up and fight for the average
American family.''
   It contained plenty of robust rhetoric, as well, including the
declaration that the new president ``will inherit a sea of
Republican red ink that not even Moses could part.'' Dukakis did
not say how he would tackle the deficit.
   Dukakis has scaled back his campaign time this week to prepare
for Sunday's televised debate in Winston-Salem, N.C., the first of
two debates.
   Shortly after his plane departed Boston, aides distributed a
written statement reporting that a doctor's examination earlier
this month showed Dukakis to be in ``excellent health.''
   The statement noted that Dukakis suffers from back pain that is
aggravated by long stretches of sitting in airplane seats, and his
doctor has prescribed anti-inflammation medication.
   In his speech in Little Rock, Dukakis depicted an America
``ready to take charge of its future again,'' and said in areas
such as health insurance, education and the environment he would
use the power of government for change.
   Beyond that, he said in a Kennedyesque passage that he would ask
all Americans to bear a ``fair share of the burden of leading
America into a new decade and a new century.''
   Dukakis has been struggling to regain his footing in the race
for the White House after a long period of decline in the polls,
and his traveling group of advisers was expanded for the trip by
several veterans of past Democratic campaigns. Those on board
included Ted Sorenson, a senior adviser to President Kennedy, and
Peter Edelman, who advised Robert Kennedy.
   Whether it was coincidental or not, Dukakis' speech was
delivered to a crowd in the Camelot Hotel and contained echoes of
rhetoric from the two Kennedys.
   He spoke of the need to ``get America moving again,'' foresaw
``new frontiers to conquer,'' and after an attack on ``voodoo
economics,'' he said, ``We can do better than that.''
   Dukakis renewed his criticism of Bush's call for a cut in the
capital gains tax as a ``giveaway'' that would benefit mostly the
wealthy.
   He said that while Bush may be satisfied with the status quo,
``most Americans aren't satified and neither am I.''
   He said prosperity is fragile for ``too many who are treading
water in the rust belt and the farm belt and the oil patch, in our
inner cities and small towns and rural counties.''
   ``Too many Americans, even those with good jobs and with
paychecks that once would have seemed enough, are fearful that they
could be wiped out by one big wave'' such as a long-term illness in
the family or the cost of college education, he said.
</TEXT>
