<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2101EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hurricane-Cancun     09-19 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane-Cancun,0905</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Caribbean Resort Won't Be Functional Until December</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hurricane-Monterrey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANCUN, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It will be December before this Caribbean
luxury resort returns to normalcy after weathering the strongest
hurricane of the century, hotel executives say.
   But Cancun, which alone represents 20 percent of Mexico's
tourist income, will recover and continue to grow, they said.
   An estimated $40 million in lost hotel room revenue for the
coming weeks is the least of the damage caused by Hurricane Gilbert
as it roared through Mexico's choice resorts on the Yucatan
Peninsula last week.
   Industry officials said they will rush repairs in Cancun to be
ready for the beginning of the high season in December. Other
affected areas include the neighboring islands of Cozumel and Isla
Mujeres.
   Workers were putting ceilings back in the lobby at the Sheraton
and unloading new plants to replace those wiped out by the storm as
still-stranded guests continued to try to find seats on jammed
flights.
   At the 14-story Hyatt Regency, the tallest building on the
strip, architects and engineers huddled with hotel officials in the
lobby to replan remodeling that already had been scheduled.
   About 6,000 tourists were evacuated in the hours just before the
storm last Wednesday and no tourists were among the 31 people
confirmed killed on the Yucatan Peninsula.
   Government officials and hotel people said they were still
gauging physical damage from the storm and the loss of business it
will suffer while repairs are made and the city is cleaned up. No
official estimate was made, but Carlos Constandse, a leading local
hotel owner, said he believed repairs would cost about $100 million.
   ``We have to close in the short term 100 percent,'' Tourism
Secretary Antonio Enriquez Savignac said during a weekend visit
here with President Miguel de la Madrid. ``I believe in two weeks
we will be in a position to begin slowly reopening the hotels. By
the end of November it will be totally repaired.''
   Hotel managers said they were aiming for the Dec. 15 start of
the high season.
   Tourism accounts for 10 percent of foreign exchange and has
helped Mexico survive economic crisis and falling oil prices.
Cancun itself draws 1 million tourists annually and brings in $500
million a year, or 20 percent of tourism income, Enriquez Savignac
said.
   About 90 percent of the tourists are foreigners. The $100 a
night off-season and $160 in-season rates are beyond the means of
all but wealthy Mexicans.
   ``Obviously there's going to be a `down.' The very commercial
restaurants (ones that cater only to tourists) are going to suffer
and give their employees vacations,'' said Paolo Ceravolo, who owns
an Italian restaurant popular with local hotel and construction
executives. ``But by December there will be people.''
   ``There is too much invested (in Cancun) for them (private
investors) to let it fall,'' he said.
   ``We're going to have to lower rates and the people will come,''
said Miguel Loyo, controller of the 1,200-room Hotel Presidente. He
stood in the lobby, its ceiling gone and glittering glass decor
stripped to bare concrete.
   Cancun was a hamlet of fishermen and farmers until 1969, when
the government, using computer analyses of its climate, proximity
to Mayan ruins and other factors, targeted it for development.
Since then, it has boomed to a population of about 200,000. Nearly
all its 45,000 jobs depend on tourism.
   More than 50 of its 111 hotels are strung along a 12-mile ribbon
of powdery white sand dunes, now known as the ``hotel zone,'' that
faces the Caribbean on one side. On the other, lagoons separate it
from the mainland.
   All the hotels on the strip ``were damaged in one way or
another,'' Constandse said. Of 11,000 rooms that were operating at
the time, 30 percent were damaged, he said.
   Gilbert uprooted trees, jerked street lights out from their
concrete bases and bent communications antennae like hairpins.
Windows and glass walls blew out all along the hotel strip _ in
some buildings, virtually all of the windows.
   Wendy Kidd, who was staying in a suite at the Sheraton, said the
wind whipped through the bedroom, going ``in one way and out the
other and took everything with it.''
   ``It took beds, chesterfields. It was completely gutted. It
could have been a fire but nothing was blackened.''
   She said the other rooms in the suite were hardly touched.
   The storm scoured away beaches in some places and built them up
in others. Hotel managers said they understood the shore would
return to its old lines, but were calling in specialists.
   Some of the most severe damage was at the Flamingo Hotel, where
a four-story, eight-room section ripped away and came to rest at a
steep angle at the edge of the sea. A crumbled swimming pool lay at
the ocean's edge and sand was washed from under the main floor of
another section.
   Down the beach, a 118-foot Cuban fishing boat crashed into the
corner of a three-story hotel unit.
   Despite the storm's force, hotel managers said there was little
structural damage and the biggest losses were in the windows and in
decorations.
   Construction under way is expected to add 2,500 rooms by
December and the total is to reach 21,000 in 1989.
</TEXT>
