<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Haiti-Manigat     09-19 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Haiti-Manigat,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President Describes Avril As `Political Brain'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril, the new leader of Haiti, is
``a political brain'' who has had a role in overthrowing the
nation's last three leaders, said former Haitian President Leslie
Manigat.
   ``Everyone in the army considers him a political brain,''
Manigat said Sunday in an interview here. ``He has been clever
enough to further his military career and emerge as No. 1.''
   Manigat, who fled Haiti after he was ousted from power in a coup
last June, believes Avril played a role in his removal and that of
exiled former President Jean-Claude Duvalier.
   ``He has been a man acting behind the scenes and has now moved
into a new role,'' Manigat said of Avril, who served as chief
counsel to the junta that assumed power after Duvalier fled in
February 1986.
   Manigat, a political science professor elected president in a
widely boycotted election last February, said he was not surprised
that the junta headed by his successor, Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy,
lasted only a few months because of military infighting.
   ``They were too divided among themselves for that to last,''
said Manigat, who lives in Baltimore.
