<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuardianAngelAssault     09-19 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guardian Angel Assault,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guardian Angels Leader Says He Was Assaulted In Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guardian Angels founder Curtis Sliwa, who went
to England last week to set up chapters of the group, said Monday
he was stabbed in the face with a handful of darts by a local
``football hooligan'' during his stay.
   Sliwa, speaking an hour after his return to the United States,
said he required 28 stitches in his face after the assault last
Wednesday. Another Guardian Angel, Collins Pompey, also was stabbed
and took six stitches, Sliwa said.
   In London, Scotland Yard said Monday the Guardian Angels leader
was assaulted at a youth club but released no details.
   According to Sliwa, the incident occurred in the Lansdown Green
Community Center in Brixton, where he went to meet with local
residents about forming a chapter of the civilian anti-crime group.
   The meeting was interrupted by ``a group of football hooligans
who didn't take kindly to my presence,'' Sliwa said.
   ``The leader of the group came up to me and stabbed me in the
face with darts, which is a very popular game over there,'' said
Sliwa. Pompey was also attacked by the group, he said.
   No suspects have been arrested in the attack on Sliwa, 34,
Scotland Yard said. Sliwa said he plans to return to England the
week of Oct. 17 to go ahead with his plans to set up Guardian
Angels patrols there.
   Teams of unarmed Guardian Angels sporting red berets and crested
T-shirts patrol dangerous areas of many U.S. cities. They are
trained in martial arts and attempt to make citizens' arrests of
crime suspects, a tactic that authorities say sometimes interferes
with police work and violates the rights of those detained.
</TEXT>
