<DOCNO> AP880919-0165 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2204EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-GeneralAssembly     09-19 0728</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-General Assembly,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>43rd General Assembly Convenes Tuesday; UN Chief Praises
Peacemaking Role</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0682 to restore logo</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. secretary-general delivered a
positive annual report Monday on the eve of the 43rd General
Assembly, praising the world body for peacemaking but warning that
the peacebroker was going broke.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar cited U.N. peacemaking
efforts in Afghanistan, the Iran-Iraq war, Cyprus, Southeast Asia,
South-West Africa and Western Sahara in giving his most optimistic
assessment in years of the 159-nation organization.
   The session opens Tuesday afternoon for election of a president
by secret ballot. A behind-the-scenes fight has been under way.
Foreign Minister Dante Caputo of Argentina and Barbados'
Ambassador, Dame Ruth Nita Barrow, are in close contention.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
race was too close to call and several ballots could be held before
one candidate gets a simple majority.
   For the second consecutive year, Perez de Cuellar will not be
there for the opening. He will be bound for South Africa for his
first talks in five years with President P.W. Botha on a regional
peace settlement.
   From there he goes to Angola for more peace talks.
   A fight is expected over the Korean issue during the three-month
General Assembly. The United States and other nations have
sponsored a resolution inviting South Korea to address the assembly
on the 40th anniversary of its founding.
   Both South Korea and communist North Korea have non-voting
observer status and are not permitted to speak during the general
debate, when national leaders address the assembly.
   But the Soviet Union and its socialist friends oppose letting
South Korea speak and on Monday they sponsored a resolution
inviting North Korea to deliver an address.
   Both North and South Korea formed their governments in late
summer of 1948.
   China has not sponsored either resolution but opposes a South
Korean speech.
   The three-week general debate begins Sept. 26 when President
Reagan will deliver his final speech to the world body. His
administration has criticized the United Nations over the years for
bureaucracy, waste and anti-Western bias.
   The session will hear 13 heads of state, six prime ministers and
numerous foreign ministers.
   Among the issues the assembly will discuss is the perennial
problem of the Middle East and the Palestinians. The Palestinian
uprising in the occupied territories that began last Dec. 8 is
expected to produce harsh denunciations of Israel.
   Another anticipated topic is Iraq's refusal to receive a U.N.
chemical experts team to investigate allegations that Iraq violated
international law by using poison gas against its rebellious
Kurdish minority.
   In his annual 21-page work report, released Monday, Perez de
Cuellar likened the United Nations to ``a small boat in which all
the people of the Earth were gathered.'' He said the sails had
caught ``a light, but favorable wind'' and the shore was in sight.
   He cited the U.N.-mediated Afghanistan accords last April; a
U.N.-supervised cease-fire Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old Iran-Iraq war;
Iran-Iraq peace talks; a U.N. meeting between Greek and Turkish
Cypriot leaders of the divided Mediterranean island nation of
Cyprus; approaching settlements in Western Sahara; South-West
Africa, or Namibia, and southern Africa, and positive signs in
Southeast Asia.
   But he also pointed to continuing problems in the Middle East,
Central America, southern Africa and the Korean Peninsula. The
issues of disarmament, global economic disparties, human rights
violations and the environment are urgent problems, he said.
   Perez de Cuellar said the United Nations still faces a financial
crisis, despite a U.S. promise to pay $144 million in arrears.
   The U.N. chief said, ``The financial health of the organization
needs to be immediately restored. The United Nations cannot
function without money.''
   He said the U.N. faces both an immediate shortage of cash
``which threatens insolvency in the next few months, and the
virtual depletion of reserves.'' He said this means the U.N. will
not be able to carry out new peacekeeping operations.
   He said he would ask the General Assembly urgently to consider
new ways of raising money, such as voluntary contributions,
interest-free loans and changes in the scale of assessments.
   ``It would be paradoxical and discordant,'' Perez de Cuellar
said, ``if the organization should face financial difficulties
precisely when it has to meet the demands of a more constructive
phase of international affairs.''
</TEXT>
