<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NewspaperHostages 2ndLd-Writethru a0666 09-19 0722</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Newspaper Hostages, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0666,0738</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marshals Arrest Fugitive Wanted in Newspaper Office Siege</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS one graf after 11th graf ``Hatcher was...' to UPDATE
with quotes from fugitive, saying, ``It's time to overthrow the
government.''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. marshals arrested a fugitive wanted in
a hostage-taking at a newspaper office as he arrived Monday on a
flight from Newark, N.J., with an attorney.
   Marshals grabbed Eddie Hatcher and frisked him in the covered
passageway connecting an arriving Piedmont Airlines plane to a
terminal at Raleigh-Durham Airport. A security officer guarded the
door to the terminal while marshals arrested Hatcher, handcuffed
him and led him to a car waiting on the tarmac.
   Hatcher, whose hair had been cut shorter since his disappearance
last month, wore a bright red shirt, blue jeans, long breech cloth
and Indian-style boots.
   He is charged with violating federal weapons laws and holding up
to 20 people hostage at The Robesonian newspaper in Lumberton on
Feb. 1. Hatcher, who is American Indian, and a second man charged
in the incident said they were protesting alleged corruption and
discrimination against minorities by Robeson County law enforcement
officials.
   Hatcher's arraignment had been scheduled for Monday, and his
brother and sister, Aaron and Ginger Clark, were waiting at the
airport with a limousine. They said they had planned to take their
brother to the federal courthouse in downtown Raleigh for the
hearing.
   However, authorities were watching the flights coming into
Raleigh-Durham and spotted Hatcher first, said U.S. Marshal Bill
Berryhill.
   ``We felt like with his arraignment today he might come in,''
said Berryhill.
   The marshal said he was ``willing to give Hatcher the benefit of
the doubt,'' and believed he was on his way to surrender when he
stepped off the plane at the airport.
   New York attorney Ron Kuby had accompanied Hatcher on the flight
from Newark. Kuby is an associate of lawyer William Kunstler,
well-known for his defense of left-wing activists.
   Ms. Clark watched through a window as officials led her brother
out of the plane and down a stairway to the waiting car. She
sobbed, pounded on the window and waved in an attempt to get her
brother's attention. Hatcher looked up and smiled at her.
   Hatcher was taken to the Cumberland County Jail in Fayetteville,
one county over from Robeson in southeastern North Carolina,
Berryhill said.
   Upon his arrival in Fayetteville, Hatcher was asked where he had
been. He replied: ``Over the rainbow. I had a vacation. I feel real
good. It's time to overthrow the government.''
   While Hatcher was being taken into custody, his case was called
by U.S. District Judge Terrence Boyle. The judge entered an
innocent plea on Hatcher's behalf and set trial for Sept. 26.
   Hatcher, 30, disappeared Aug. 31 after the 4th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals revoked his bond. He was declared a fugitive after
failing to surrender to U.S. marshals in Raleigh.
   Asked where Hatcher had been hiding or if he had been in contact
with his lawyers while a fugitive, Barry Nakell, a Chapel Hill
attorney who's helping represent Hatcher, said, ``I can't say.''
   Berryhill said investigators would pursue information on where
Hatcher has been during the past 20 days ``even though it's rather
academic at this point.''
   ``We'll be talking with Mr. Hatcher right away,'' the marshal
said. ``And we'll be getting with the airlines to determine point
of departure, who bought the plane tickets and so on.''
   U.S. Attorney Margaret Currin and Assistant U.S. Attorney John
Bruce would not comment on possible additional charges against
Hatcher or others who may have helped him.
   Timothy Jacobs, 20, who also is charged in the hostage-taking
incident, surrendered to U.S. marshals in Asheville on Aug. 31.
Jacobs was later transferred to the Wilson County Jail.
   Bruce said Hatcher and Jacobs would be tried together since they
were indicted together and the cases had not been separated by a
judge.
   Hatcher and Jacobs had been released on $100,000 unsecured bond
July 5 after a three-judge panel of the appeals court ruled they
had not been given a bond hearing within five days of their arrest,
as required by law. But the full court voided that decision and set
an Oct. 4 hearing on a prosecution motion challenging bond for the
two men.
</TEXT>
