<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Diplomats     09-19 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Diplomats,0506</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain Tells Diplomats To Obey Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Office plans to tell 10 ambassadors
that their envoys must obey the law following a flurry of crimes by
visiting diplomats, officials said Monday.
   The Foreign Office said the ambassadors were being selected as
representatives of geographic regions, rather than as suspected
offenders. The envoys were not immediately identified.
   ``We're asking a number of senior ambassadors to call to enlist
their help and cooperation in putting across to their colleagues
the government's concern at any possible abuse of diplomatic
privilege,'' said a Foreign Office statement.
   The meeting is to be held this week, but no final date was set.
   The carea gun at demonstrators
outside his embassy, and a Tunisian who refused to pay parking
fines.
   The 10 ambassadors will meet with Foreign Office Minister
Timothy Eggar, who expelled both the Cuban diplomat and the Cuban
ambassador, Oscar Fernandez-Mell.
   ``Obey our laws or go home,'' Eggar warned in a column this week
in a London weekly, The Mail on Sunday.
   Eggar revealed that Britain tried unsuccessfully in 1984 to get
an international agreement to modify the 1961 Vienna Convention,
which gives diplomats blanket immunity from prosecution.
   Britain has been particularly touchy about diplomatic crime
since a man firing from the Libyan Embassy at demonstrators killed
a London policewoman in 1984. Libya refused to waive immunity and
Britain severed relations.
   It is widely suspected that violations are occurring of the
Foreign Office ban on diplomats carrying guns and stockpiling arms,
officials say privately.
   London's Sunday Telegraph said this week that the intelligence
service, MI5, ``quietly screens'' diplomatic consignments if arms
are suspected, although this is forbidden under the Vienna
Convention.
   The newspaper said intelligence agents arranged for a recent
shipment of automatic rifles destined for an Arab embassy, which it
did not identify, to be dropped while being unloaded from a
freighter. The ambassador was told to send the rifles home, the
newspaper said.
   Most crimes by the 18,000-strong diplomatic community are
unpublicized and the envoy involved is quietly expelled, with 18
such cases last year and 17 in 1986, the Foreign Office says.
   Recent publicized cases include a Jordanian Embassy waiter
suspected of sex crimes, a Mexican envoy questioned about the
murder of two prostitutes and an Iranian consul expelled on
shoplifting allegations.
   Britain lists the worst offenders for non-payment of parking
fines.
   Egypt headed the 1987 list with 799 unpaid tickets, followed by
the Soviet Union, 622, China, 551 and France with 513.
   Asked to comment, an Egyptian Embassy spokesman did not return
the call.
   Tunisian diplomat Sadok Kassous was expelled because he refused
to pay hundreds of dollars in fines, protesting that insufficient
parking spaces were provided outside the embassy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
