<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolClothes     09-19 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Clothes,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subdued Dress Code Aims at Ending Thefts, Rivalry</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school principal says he's encouraged by
the success of a dress code aimed at stopping thefts, violence, and
expensive rivalry some students can't afford.
   There are no gold chains and bracelets or designer sunglasses
allowed at the 2,500-student Mumford High School, which gained
notice through T-shirts worn by Eddie Murphy in the film ``Beverly
Hills Cop.''
   Pupils also are minus their tank tops, jogging suits,
snakeskin-adorned gym shoes and like finery.
   ``I'm a pro-active administrator, not a reactive one,''
Principal Robin E. Oden said. ``I see and hear about the youngsters
being shot over gold chains as they walk to and from school.
   ``My kids (students) have been harassed. Recognizing that, I
want to make sure that it doesn't spill over into the school.''
   Two 17-year-old boys were wounded by gunfire last year in
Detroit after one was robbed of a blue sheepskin jacket. Three
years ago, a 13-year-old was shot in the chest after giving his
popular gym shoes to five youths who demanded them.
   Oden said the policy has been successfully enforced this school
year without any suspensions.
   ``About 98 percent of my students adhere to the dress code to
the letter,'' he said.
   Some students were spotted near the school recently wearing gold
or other expensive jewelry and other banned items. They said they
stashed it during the day and then wore it home.
   Oden said such a tactic resulted in a recent robbery of a
14-year-old student.
</TEXT>
