<HEAD>Namphy Keeps to Self in Luxurious Dominican Suite</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One graf SUBS for 8th graf pvs, Namphy and ... CORRECTING
that Manigat exiled in June, not July. Picks up 9th graf pvs,
Namphy received ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Haiti-Analysis, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Haiti's deposed
president, Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy, kept to himself Monday in a
guarded hotel suite on his second day in forced exile.
   ``The general has repeated his decision not to speak to
reporters. He has said he has nothing to say,'' one guard told a
reporter.
   Guards maintained tight security outside the sixth-floor suite
in the Dominican Concorde Hotel where Namphy, his wife, Gabrielle,
and his daughter, Melissa, were staying.
   A hotel employee said Namphy and his family have eaten all meals
in their rooms and have refused to accept phone calls.
   Security agents have prohibited reporters, photographers and
cameramen from visiting the sixth floor of the hotel.
   Security was even tighter at the Haitian Embassy, where
anti-riot police armed with automatic weapons stood guard to
prevent demonstrations.
   Namphy arrived Sunday from Haiti, which shares the island of
Hispaniola with the Dominican Republic, after being deposed by
non-commissioned officers and soldiers of his own Presidential
Guard, a 1,000-man unit that has been instrumental in Haiti's last
two coups.
   Namphy and others had sought political asylum at the Dominican
Republic Embassy in the Haitian capital of Port-au-Prince. Haiti's
last exiled president, the civilian Leslie Manigat, also stayed in
the Dominican Concorde when he was overthrown and sent into exile
in June by Namphy.
   Namphy received his first visitor Monday, the Dominican deputy
foreign minister, Fabio Herrera Cabral, who met with the deposed
general for about 30 minutes in his hotel suite.
   Herrera Cabral later told reporters Namphy's visa was good for
only two months. He said it was a ``courtesy'' document issued to
visitors.
   Local newspapers speculated that Namphy was making arrangements
to fly to France, as did Manigat after his ouster from the
presidency by the now-deposed general. The reports could not be
confirmed.
   Santo Domingo's La Noticia newspaper reported Monday that Namphy
was seen limping when he arrived at the hotel Sunday and that he
complained of pain in his right leg. It also quoted an unidentified
hotel employee as saying that the lights in Namphy's suite were
turned on several times during the night and that Namphy asked an
orderly to bring him aspirin.
   Rafael Bello Andino, an aide to President Joaquin Balaguer, said
Monday that the Dominican Republic will continue monitoring events
in Haiti.
   A source at the Foreign Ministry said discussions are continuing
to decide the fate of 12 people granted asylum in the embassy.
   Although the identities of the 12 have not been confirmed,
Port-au-Prince Mayor Franck Romain is believed among them.
</TEXT>
