<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The long-awaited autumn weather and snow is helping cool a
record fire season in the northern Rockies, but officials say the
worst is yet to come in hotter areas such as California.
   Wildfires have burned over 4.1 million acres of forest and brush
this summer in the West and Alaska, the worst fire season in 30
years, according to the Boise Interagency Fire Center, which
coordinates the firefighting.
   If hot, dry weather persists in California and southern Oregon,
where the peak fire season is just starting, more than 5 million
acres may burn this year, a survey of firefighting officials shows.
</TEXT>
