<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Soldiers'Diaries adv27   09-19 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldiers' Diaries, adv27,0669</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv27</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Sept. 27 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Diaries of Two Israeli Soldiers Differ on Army's Occupation</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting to fix release date to Tues sted Wed PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The diaries of two Israeli soldiers offer
sharply conflicting accounts of how the Israeli army deals with the
nine-month-old Palestinian uprising on the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   But at the same time, the diairies published in the Jerusalem
Post mirror the broad differences in Israeli society itself on how
to quell the rebellion.
   One soldier, a reservist, wrote that troops were taught to beat
Arabs with ``dry blows'' that cause pain but draw no blood.
   The other said his reserve duty in the Gaza Strip's Jabaliya
refugee camp convinced him that despite occasional abberations,
soldiers were ``restrained and noble men.''
   ``The Israeli army remains one of the most decent in the
world,'' the second soldier, American-born free-lance writer Louis
Rapoport, wrote of his 30 days of duty in the crowded camp of
70,000 refugees in June.
   But the other, British-born educator Jonathan Kestenbaum,
described a ``tremendous callousness'' among many of the soldiers
he served with in the West Bank village of Qabatiyeh in August.
   ``Among the soldiers, there is a depressing routine of almost
wild abandon. Everybody here makes up their own rules,'' Kestenbaum
wrote in his diary.
   Kestenbaum, 29, described an encounter with an Israeli guard at
a detention center in Jenin, north of Jerusalem.
   ``How many dogs have you brought?'' Kestenbaum quoted the guard
as asking him when he arrived with a group of teen-age Palestinian
detainees.
   He added: ``Once the man opposite you is a dog, anything goes.''
   Rapoport conceded troops were sometimes responsible for
``accidents or misjudgments,'' including a case where an Israeli
soldier made a firebomb and intended to hurl it at Arab
demonstrators. His officers confiscated it.
   But, he wrote, many soldiers were frustrated because they felt
the Palestinians had a propaganda edge by sending boys as young as
9 years old to the front lines of stone-throwing riots to take on
armed troops.
   ``The scores of men in the reserve company I served with ... are
portrayed in the world media as part of a Goliath machine versus
little David with his puny stones,'' Rapoport wrote.
   Addressing the same issue, Kestenbaum wrote of a 15-year-old
Palestinian killed by a member of his unit: ``Why are we using live
bullets on teen-agers throwing stones?''
   Kestenbaum told of chasing a 9-year-old boy who broke a 30-day
curfew to try to retrieve bread from a gutter and of rounding up a
group of elderly Palestinians who slipped into a field at night to
pick a bucket of tomatoes rotting in the fields.
   ``Our jeep springs into action, chasing this family as if the
very future of our country depended on it. We corner them,''
Kestenbaum wrote. ``At which point the old woman, 90 years old,
falls to her knees, kisses my hand and begs me not to (detain) her:
`We really needed tomatoes,' she says.''
   ``These are vulgar, unnecessary situations which humiliate them
and degrade us,'' Kestenbaum added.
   Both Kestenbaum and Rapoport described the shooting deaths of
Palestinians during their tours but had markedly different
reactions to the killings. Since the uprising began, 266
Palestinians and six Israelis have died.
   ``I doubt whether any other army in the world ... would act with
more restraint,'' Rapoport said, adding that he considered the Arab
fatalities in the uprising to be ``remarkably low given the scale
of the revolt.''
   Kestenbaum offered this observation about a soldier in his unit
who killed a Palestinian teen-ager: ``The guy who fired the shots
was the same guy who spent three days at our training base talking
of beating up Arabs. (The death) didn't really affect him one way
or the other.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Sept. 27</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1003EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-SouthAfrica-Vote ADV28   09-19 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa-Vote, ADV28,0760</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv28</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Sept. 28 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>South African Government Facing Stormy Local Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Punctuated by violence and
black defiance, the campaign for local elections in South Africa is
developing into a high-stakes showdown between the government and
its adversaries.
   Two powerful challenges, from opposite directions, threaten to
foil the government's hopes for political and public-relations
triumphs Oct. 26, when for the first time, voters of all races go
to the polls on the same day.
   Black anti-apartheid clergymen are defying emergency regulations
by urging a boycott of the elections, which they view as an
entrenchment of segregated, white-controlled political structures.
   Among whites, the far-right Conservative Party, which depicts
even minimal reforms by the government as surrender to the black
majority, is campaigning vigorously for an intensification of
apartheid. It is favored to win control of most white municipal
councils in two of the four provinces, including Transvaal, the
most populous.
   President P.W. Botha's National Party, which rejects black
participation in national elections, says in its campaign leaflets
that the local elections prove ``democratic participation for all
has become a reality.''
   Information Minister Stoffel van der Merwe suggests that the
turnout among registered black voters could reach 40 percent, in
contrast to about 20 percent in the previous black local elections
in 1983.
   To maximize the turnout, the government is spending hundreds of
thousands of dollars on advertising. In a series of print and
television ads, a pair of squirrels discuss the virtues of voting;
billboards in white and black communities bear the slogan: ``You
Can Make It Happen. Vote Oct. 26.''
   A black newspaper columnist, Joe Latakgomo, wrote of the slogan:
``Nobody has got around to telling me what it is I can make
happen.''
   Predicting that militants will try to intimidate would-be black
voters, the government will allow ballots to be cast in advance by
virtually anyone who asks to do so. Critics claim this ``prior
vote'' system could be easily abused to produce fraudulent turnout
statistics in townships where few voters show up on election day.
   Roughly half the 26 million blacks are not allowed to vote
because they are considered citizens of semi-autonomous or
nominally independent homelands. Hundreds of thousands of other
blacks are ineligible for other reasons. These include residents of
illegal squatter camps and servants who live at their employers'
homes in white areas.
   In some black townships, the nomination deadline expired with no
candidates entering the election. In many other townships, most
candidates are running unopposed and will take office for five-year
terms no matter how low the turnout. Nowhere are prominent black
anti-apartheid activists seeking office.
   Several major black opposition groups have been banned from
functioning since February, and dozens of activists have been
detained.
   In June, the government outlawed calls for election boycotts;
those who do can be sentenced to prison terms as long as 10 years.
   A leading black newspaper, The Sowetan, has responded by
rejecting ads promoting the election.
   Archbishop Desmond Tutu of the Anglican Church has risked
prosecution by telling blacks that the election is ludicrous and
will ``perpetuate your oppression.''
   Unsigned pamphlets distributed in townships denounce blacks
running for office as ``a bunch of crooks, murderers and highly
paid apartheid agents ... who should be met with the people's
anger.''
   One black candidate, David Nkomo, was assassinated in Soweto in
August by two unidentified gunmen. Earlier, assailants threw hand
grenades at a rally organized by Nkomo's Sofasonke Party, and
candidates' homes were set afire in the Cape Province township of
Bhongolethu.
   A Johannesburg security company is conducting one-day workshops
in major cities, costing the equivalent of nearly $200 per
participant. Civil defense and bomb-disposal experts provide advice
on countering ``the possible increase in terrorist activities''
before the election.
   For most of the 5 million whites, the drama surrounding the
black elections is overshadowed by the Conservative Party's assault
on the National Party, which has held power for 40 years.
   The Conservatives, who won 26 percent of the vote in 1987
general elections, believe whites are confused by Botha's reform
program and prefer the clarity of an unabashed pro-segregation
policy.
   Many analysts predict the Conservatives will take control in
every white municipality in Transvaal except Johannesburg and a few
suburbs. Even Pretoria, the national capital, is expected to be
lost by the National Party.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Sept. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
