<2ND_LINE>BC-History, Adv 26,0543</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Monday, Sept. 26</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Sept. 26, the 270th day of 1988. There are 96
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1888, poet, dramatist and critic T.S. Eliot was born in St.
Louis. Eliot would become one of the most distinguished literary
figures of the 20th century, writing such famous poems as ``The
Waste Land'' and ``The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock,'' and
winning the Nobel Prize for literature in 1948. Eliot, who became a
British subject in 1927, died in 1965.
   On this date:
   In 1777, British troops occupied Philadelphia in the American
Revolution.
   In 1789, Thomas Jefferson was appointed America's first
secretary of state; John Jay was named the first chief justice of
the U.S. Supreme Court; Samuel Osgood began service as the first
postmaster general; and Edmund Jennings Randolph was named the
first attorney general.
   In 1820, pioneer Daniel Boone died in Missouri at 85.
   In 1892, John Philip Sousa and his band performed in public for
the first time, in Plainfield, N.J.
   In 1898, composer George Gershwin was born in New York.
   In 1914, the Federal Trade Commission was established.
   In 1918, the Meuse-Argonne offensive against the Germans began
during World War I.
   In 1950, U.N. troops in the Korean War recaptured the South
Korean capital of Seoul from the North Koreans.
   In 1955, following word that President Dwight D. Eisenhower had
suffered a heart attack, the New York Stock Exchange saw its worst
price decline since 1929.
   In 1957, the musical ``West Side Story'' opened on Broadway.
   In 1960, the first of four televised debates between
presidential candidates Richard M. Nixon and John F. Kennedy took
place in Chicago.
   In 1962, ``The Beverly Hillbillies'' premiered on CBS-TV.
   In 1968, ``Hawaii Five-O'' made its debut as an hourly program
on CBS, having premiered as a two-hour movie the week before.
   In 1977, Sir Freddie Laker began his cut-rate Skytrain service
from London to New York. The carrier went out of business in 1982.
   Ten years ago: Railroad clerks went on strike, halting more than
two-thirds of the nation's rail service for four days until the
union representing the clerks complied with a federal court order
for a cooling-off period.
   Five years ago: In an address to the United Nations, President
Reagan said ``the door to an agreement is open'' concerning
intermediate-range nuclear missiles in Europe. Australia II became
the first challenger to win the America's Cup as a team led by John
Bertrand defeated the Liberty, skippered by Dennis Conner, in the
seventh and deciding race on Rhode Island Sound.
   One year ago: In his weekly radio address, President Reagan said
he was reluctantly signing legislation restoring the automatic
deficit-reducing provisions of the Gramm-Rudman Act.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Julie London is 62. Actor Patrick
O'Neal is 61. Actor Kent McCord is 46. Singer Lynn Anderson is 41.
Singer Olivia Newton-John is 40. Actress Melissa Sue Anderson is 26.
   Thought for today: ``This is the way the world ends@ Not with a
bang but a whimper.'' _ T.S. Eliot.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
