<NOTE>For release Tuesday, Sept. 27</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, Sept. 27, the 271st day of 1988. There are 95
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1964, the Warren Commission issued a report concluding that
Lee Harvey Oswald had acted alone in assassinating President John
F. Kennedy.
   On this date:
   In 1779, John Adams was named to negotiate Revolutionary War
peace terms with Britain.
   In 1825, the first locomotive to haul a passenger train was
operated by George Stephenson in England.
   In 1854, the first great disaster involving an Atlantic Ocean
liner occurred when the steamship Arctic sank with 300 people
aboard.
   In 1928, the United States said it was recognizing the
Nationalist Chinese government.
   In 1938, the ocean liner Queen Elizabeth was christened at
Clydebank, Scotland, by the British queen consort for whom the ship
was named.
   In 1939, Warsaw, Poland, surrendered to the Germans after 19
days of resistance during World War II.
   In 1954, ``Tonight!'' with host Steve Allen, made its debut on
NBC television.
   In 1959, a typhoon battered the main Japanese island of Honshu,
killing nearly 5,000 people.
   In 1959, Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev concluded his visit to
the United States.
   In 1979, Congress gave final approval to creating the Department
of Education.
   In 1986, the Senate joined the House of Representatives in
approving the most sweeping changes in the federal tax code since
World War II.
   Ten years ago: The Israeli Knesset, or parliament, opened debate
on the Camp David accords with Egypt, during which Prime Minister
Menachem Begin found himself being accused of betraying his country
by members of his own Likud coalition. Early the next day, the
parliament voted to endorse the agreement.
   Five years ago: Members of Congress received written assurances
from President Reagan that he would seek their approval before
deciding to keep 1,600 U.S. Marines in Lebanon longer than 18
months.
   One year ago: Football fans suffered through their first Sunday
without football because of the NFL players' strike. However, NFL
owners organized games with replacement and non-striking players,
and the strike was called off in mid-October.
   Today's birthdays: Former Illinois Sen. Charles Percy is 69.
Actor William Conrad is 68. Movie director Arthur Penn is 66.
Actress Sada Thompson is 59. Actress Kathleen Nolan is 55. Author
Barbara Howar is 54. Sportscaster Dick Schaap is 54. Actor Greg
Morris is 54. Singer Meat Loaf is 41. Baseball player Mike Schmidt
is 39. Singer Shaun Cassidy is 30.
   Thought for today: ``Hypothetical questions get hypothetical
answers.'' _ Joan Baez, American folk singer and activist.
</TEXT>
