<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Thursday, Sept. 29, the 273rd day of 1988. There are 93
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1978, Pope John Paul I was found dead in his Vatican
apartment by his personal secretary. He had served little more than
a month as head of the Roman Catholic Church.
   On this date:
   In 1789, the U.S. War Department established a regular army with
a strength of several hundred men.
   In 1829, London's reorganized police force, which became known
as Scotland Yard, went on duty.
   In 1902, impresario David Belasco opened his first Broadway
theater.
   In 1918, Allied forces scored a decisive breakthrough of the
Hindenburg Line in Germany in World War I.
   In 1943, Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower and Italian Marshal Pietro
Badoglio signed an armistice aboard a British ship off Malta.
   In 1956, Nicaraguan leader Anastasio Somoza Garcia died, eight
days after he was shot.
   In 1963, the second session of the ecumenical council, ``Vatican
II,'' opened in Rome.
   In 1975, baseball manager Casey Stengel died at a hospital in
Glendale, Calif., at 85.
   In 1977, Muhammad Ali won a unanimous, 15-round decision over
Earnie Shavers at Madison Square Garden in New York to retain his
world heavyweight boxing championship.
   In 1982, seven people in the Chicago area died after unwittingly
taking Extra-Strength Tylenol capsules that had been laced with
cyanide. The crime remains unsolved.
   In 1986, the Soviet Union released Nicholas Daniloff, an
American journalist who had been confined to Moscow on spying
charges.
   Five years ago: Congress authorized President Reagan to keep
1,600 U.S. Marines in Lebanon for up to 18 months longer. It was
the first time Congress had invoked the War Powers Act, passed in
1973 to give lawmakers more say in how the president deploys troops
overseas.
   One year ago: Henry Ford II, who in 1945 took over the ailing
automobile company founded by his grandfather and restored it as a
leading industrial giant, died in Detroit at 70.
   Today's birthdays: Former singing cowboy and baseball magnate
Gene Autry is 81. Actress Greer Garson is 80. Movie director
Michelangelo Antonioni is 76. Movie producer Stanley Kramer is 75.
Retired football coach Bum Phillips is 65. Former U.S. Sen. John
Tower is 63. Actress Anita Ekberg is 57. Singer Jerry Lee Lewis is
53. Actor Larry Linville is 49. Actress Madeline Kahn is 46.
``Today'' host Bryant Gumbel is 40.
   Thought for today: ``Understanding is the reward of faith.
Therefore seek not to understand that thou mayest believe, but
believe that thou mayest understand.'' _ St. Augustine.
</TEXT>
