<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, Sept. 30, the 274th day of 1988. There are 92
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   In 1938, British, French, German and Italian leaders ended the
Munich Conference with a decision to appease Adolf Hitler by
allowing Nazi annexation of Czechoslovakia's Sudetenland.
   On this date:
   In 1630, the first execution in America took place as a John
Billington was hanged in Plymouth, Mass., for fatally shooting John
Newcomin.
   In 1777, the U.S. Congress, forced to flee in the face of
advancing British forces, moved to York, Pa.
   In 1791, Mozart's opera ``The Magic Flute'' premiered in Vienna.
   In 1846, Dr. William Morton used an experimental anesthetic,
ether, for the first time on one of his patients.
   In 1927, Babe Ruth hit his 60th homer of the season to break his
own major league record. The blow came off Washington's Tom Zachary
in Yankee Stadium.
   In 1946, an international military tribunal in Nuremberg,
Germany, found 22 top Nazi leaders guilty of war crimes.
   In 1954, the first atomic-powered vessel, the submarine
Nautilus, was commissioned by the Navy at Groton, Conn.
   In 1955, actor James Dean, 24, was killed in the collision of
his sports car with another automobile near Cholame, Calif.
   In 1962, James Meredith succeeded on his fourth try in
registering for classes at the University of Mississippi.
   In 1980, Iran's spiritual leader, Ayatollah Khomeini, rejected a
truce call from Iraqi President Saddam Hussein, saying war between
the two countries would continue ``to the end.''
   Ten years ago: American and Soviet negotiators reported progress
during White House talks for a new treaty to limit strategic
bombers and interncontinental ballistic missiles. The two sides
agreed to meet again the next day at the State Department.
   Five years ago: President Reagan met at the White House with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak; among the topics they discussed
was Lebanon. Congress approved a 40-day stopgap spending bill
needed to keep the federal government funded past midnight.
   One year ago: Two top campaign aides to Massachusetts Gov.
Michael S. Dukakis resigned after one of them, campaign manager
John Sasso, admitted leaking an ``attack'' videotape that helped
bring down the candidacy of Delaware Senator Joseph Biden. Sasso
returned to the campaign this month.
   Today's birthdays: Former Georgia Gov. Lester Maddox is 73.
Actress Deborah Kerr is 67. Actress Angie Dickinson is 56. Singer
Johnny Mathis is 53. Sen. Jim Sasser, D-Tenn., is 52. Singer
Marilyn McCoo is 45. Former White House press secretary Jody Powell
is 45. Actress Rula Lenska is 41.
   Thought for today: ``Diplomacy is a game of chess in which the
nations are checkmated.'' _ Karl Kraus, Austrian essayist and poet.
</TEXT>
