<2ND_LINE>AM-News to Use, ADV 21,0570</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv21</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed AMs, Sept. 21, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>When Buying a Country Home, Water Is Vital Consideration</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In this year of the drought millions of
Americans have discovered the fickleness of water supplies. It's a
concern that needs to be kept in mind by anyone considering a rural
residence, whether farmer or commuter.
   In the last decade or so many long-time city dwellers have moved
into the sometime greener pastures of rural America.
   These relocations can offer many benefits, but they also pose
problems the urbanite may not have thought of, with water supplies
and sewage disposal atop the list.
   ``Prospective homeowners need to know about the terrain, the
proximity of the house to other structures, and the condition of
the well and septic system,'' says Roger M. Waller, a hydrologist
with the U.S. Geological Survey.
   ``If building in an unpopulated area, drill a well first,'' he
advises, ``or if buying an old house, find out if the water supply
is adequate.''
   Rural homeowners sometimes find out too late that the well
drilled on their land doesn't provide enough water or that what is
available is of poor quality.
   Waller is the author of a new booklet, ``Ground Water and the
Rural Homeowner,'' designed to explain the fundamentals of
undergound water supplies. It discusses how water moves through the
ground, the most common types of wells, and methods to solve or
prevent common well and septic-system problems.
   Single copies of the 37-page booklet are available at no charge
by writing to the U.S. Geological Survey, Books and Open-File
Reports Section, Box 25425, Denver, CO, 80225.
   When considering buying rural property, get to know the area
well and, if possible, in all weather conditions, Waller cautions.
   ``Try to visit the site under adverse conditions, such as during
heavy rain or meltwater runoff, to observe the drainage
characteristics, particularly the condition of the basement,'' he
says.
   It is also important to learn what types of business or other
activities may have been in the area in the past.
   For example, Waller notes that while orchards are picturesque,
they are often treated with chemicals to prevent disease and insect
infestation. These chemicals eventually settle into the soil and
can enter the ground water. The same type of problems can occur in
areas previously used for vegetable farms.
   In northern areas, salt and other chemicals spread on highways
in the winter can enter the water supply, and other potential
hazards include oil spills, natural gas in wells, bacteria from
septic tanks and barnyard runoff and fertilizers.
   Some mortgage lenders require a negative bacteria test of well
water before making a loan, but even if that isn't required it is
important to have the test done, Waller stresses.
   Also important to the buyer is a well record or log, which
describes the well's characteristics, including yield and the type
of materials that the driller encountered. This should include such
information as well depth, water level, type of pump, pump-intake
setting and yield.
   ``Although potential water problems for the rural homeowner can
sometimes be expensive, pose a health hazard, or possibly affect
real estate values, these problems can be avoided by the observant,
informed buyer or owner,'' concluded Waller.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed AMs, Sept 21</NOTE>
</DOC>
