<1ST_LINE>s a BC-APN--JuliusLester ADV02-1stAdd   09-19 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-APN--Julius Lester, ADV 02-1st Add,0706</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv02</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, Oct. 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>AMHERST: songs did.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   He eventually joined the increasingly militant Student
Non-violent Coordinating Committee and in 1968 drew attention
through publication of ``Look Out, Whitey,'' an exposition of the
black power principles. Lester now says he's embarrassed by the
book.
   ``In my soul I had very serious questions about black power. I
left all of that out because I felt it had to speak for the
movement. The book is honest as far as it goes, but is a betrayal
of my soul,'' he says.
   ``My problems with black power had to do with wondering whether
it would be different from white power. ... It seemed to me we were
in danger of becoming more like white people while we were thinking
we were being different.''
   On a talk show he led for several years on WBAI-FM in New York,
he broadcast an anti-Semitic poem, he said, to focus on strong
feelings aroused in some blacks by a struggle with Jews over the
control of schools in Brooklyn.
   The reading unleashed even stronger feelings. It brought death
threats, demonstrations and calls from the Jewish Defense League
for his ouster from the station.
   So it was with shock that Lester's friends and foes read in
1979, 11 years later, his article beginning: ``And so, Jews are
being used as scapegoats again.''
   The article criticized black leaders who accused Jews of
pressuring Andrew Young into resigning as U.S. ambassador to the
United Nations after he met secretly with the Palestine Liberation
Organization's representative to the United Nations, against U.S.
policy.
   Those leaders, Lester wrote, ``merely show that blacks, too, can
be Germans.''
   Lester, who by then had been teaching at the University of
Massachusetts for nine years, nearly ended up in a fistfight with a
professor over the article. He stopped attending department
meetings.
   The Young episode was followed in 1985 by an article criticizing
Jesse Jackson for his ``race for power'' and whites for overlooking
his ``Hymietown'' gaffe.
   ``An unfortunate legacy of the '60s has been an almost total,
moral abdication on the part of whites where anything black is
concerned,'' he wrote.
   The final straw for his departmental colleagues came in
``Lovesong,'' with Lester's account of Baldwin and the Jews. Lester
wrote that Baldwin somehow held Jews responsible for the outcry
over the ``Hymietown'' remark. Later he conceded that might have
been a misinterpretation.
   He had also written that he knew that Baldwin was not an
anti-Semite, ``but his remarks in class were anti-Semitic and he
does not realize it.''
   A month after the book's publication, a department meeting was
called to talk about the charge. Soon the letter suggesting
Lester's transfer was on its way to the dean of humanities.
   ``We have nothing against his Judaism,'' department Chairman
Chester Davis told the Amherst Bulletin. ``But when one develops a
vicious attitude toward blacks and black organizations, Jackson,
Baldwin and civil rights, there is some question as to the
appropriateness'' of remaining.
   Chancellor Joseph Duffey termed the meeting ``an inquisition''
and said it raised questions about Lester's academic freedom.
Professor Thelwell said the book raised questions about his
professional standards.
   ``There is no issue of academic freedom,'' Thelwell said in a
prepared statement. ``Elements of the media and the academy created
one in order to vent an ugly racist bias: `See, we've always known
that these black academics are culturally and intellectually
deficient, crude nationalist ideologues with no tolerance for or
understanding of the nuances of civilized discourse and the
protocols of free inquiry. Without the lowered intellectual
standards caused by affirmative action, they would not even be in a
university.'''
   A faculty committee that investigated found no evidence Lester's
academic freedom had been violated by his transfer to the Judaic
studies department, which both parties agreed to.
   The appointment is for one year. Chairman Shmuel Bolozky says
making Lester a permanent member of the department would be
``tantamount to putting him in a straitjacket. Lester himself, a
man not fond of artificial boundaries, would rather be free to
teach without departmental confinement.
</TEXT>
