<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-Roseanne Adv24-25   09-19 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Roseanne, Adv 24-25,0429</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Roseanne' Looks Like a Hit for ABC</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Roseanne'' gets a primo time period amid ABC's
hit Tuesday night lineup, but even without the VIP treatment, it
deserves to be a hit.
   ``Roseanne'' is from the same people who created ``The Cosby
Show,'' although Roseanne and her brood are certainly no Cosby
family. ``This is why some animals eat their young,'' cracks
Roseanne Barr, after breaking up yet another squabble among her
boisterous offspring.
   Barr, a standup comic who does housewife humor cut with feminist
and blue-collar politics, plays Roseanne Parker, the tough-talking
mama of two pre-pubescent daughters and a son. She works in a
plastics factory with a crew of lovable misfits, including her
sister, a sucker always signing up for the latest get-rich-quick
seminar. ``What's this one, `Dare to be a Millionaire?'' Roseanne
inquires when her sister pitches the latest one.
   John Goodman (``Raising Arizona,'' ``True Stories'') is perfect
as Roseanne's husband, Dan. A huggable bear of a guy, he quickly
proves he can hold his own against his funny, snide, gum-popping
co-star.
   ``Is there coffee?'' he asks when he makes his entrance at
breakfast.
   Roseanne regards him with disbelief. ``Isn't there always
coffee?''
   He pauses, suspiciously cautious. ``Yeeessss.''
   ``In the 15 years that we been married have you ever come down
in the morning and there wasn't any coffee?''
   He's still careful. ``Noooo.''
   ``Then why do you always ask, `Is there coffee?'''
   Pause. ``Is there toast?''
   Lecy Goranson plays Becky, the boy-crazy daughter. Sara Gilbert
is Darlene, the tomboy. Laurie Metcalf is Roseanne's sister,
Jackie. Natalie West is gullible co-worker Crystal. George Clooney
plays the handsome plant foreman, Booker.
   In the premiere episode, Roseanne gets stuck with all the kids'
errands after working her full-time job because Dan, an independent
contractor, says he'll be busy putting in a bid on a job. When it
turns out he ended up at a friend's house goofing off, Roseanne
goes on a rampage about shared responsibilities. Just like in real
life, the conflict isn't resolved.
   ``Roseanne'' is not ``Married ... With Children,'' the Fox show
about sniping, unhappy marrieds and their ungrateful children.
Though they're never sentimental, Roseanne and her husband love
each other, and the show, besides being a very entertaining comedy,
also pays tribute to the unheralded working class and the brave
struggle to raise a family.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-Knightwatch Adv24-25   09-19 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Knightwatch, Adv 24-25,0345</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Knightwatch' _ Murky Film Noir About Youthful Vigilantes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In ABC's new drama ``Knightwatch,'' it's hard to
tell who the good guys are.
   That seems to be the point of the premiere of this murky film
noir about a Guardian Angels-type group whose members aspire to
defend citizens on the mean streets of New York, but who
occasionally go over the bounds of accepted law enforcement
practices _ as when one of them throws a suspect off a building.
   Eventually it becomes apparent that the Knights are indeed the
good guys, even if they are struggling a bit in their search for a
meaningful value system amid the squalor of their ghetto
neighborhood.
   In the premiere episode, a hero emerges: handsome Calvin (Dan
Franklin), a good-as-gold, blue-collar kid who wants to follow in
his late father's public-service footsteps.
   Calvin becomes the focal point of the group's moral dilemma when
he cops to the cops that his partner, John, threw a would-be rapist
off a roof. The rest of the Knights shun him, and after wrestling
with his conscience, he discards his Knights jacket.
   To deal with his angst, Calvin rides his motorcycle to a
soundtrack of rock music.
   Meanwhile, the group's leader, Tony (Benjamin Bratt),
alternately charms and menaces a female TV news reporter doing a
story he hopes will raise some money for the Knights. She has
questionable ethics of her own when she suggests he might want to
dress down for the interview in order to look more needy.
   Tom Bower plays Father Jim, the overburdened priest who shelters
the Knights in his church basement.
   The young cast is talented, but ``Knightwatch's'' sophisticated
intent is bogged down by ragged execution. Opposite ``The Cosby
Show,'' it'll offer an alternative to kids who don't want to be
cheered up. But it's unlikely that very many will want to watch
``Knightwatch.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2054EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-AlmostGrown Adv24-25   09-19 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Almost Grown, Adv 24-25,0493</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>CBS' `Almost Grown': It's NOT `thirtysomething'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the concluding scene in the pilot of CBS'
``Almost Grown,'' Norm and Suzie sit in a car listening to a rock
station on the radio. They have changed in the 20-odd years since
they met, but the music has not.
   ``Those same three chords,'' Norm says. ``It's good to know
there's something you can count on.''
   ``Almost Grown'' is an ambitious history of a marriage, set
against that nebulous force that formed a generation who came of
age in the '60s and '70s _ rock 'n' roll.
   The show inevitably will be compared to ABC's
``thirtysomething,'' since it deals with a couple in their 30s and
the foibles of the New Age 1980s and is designed to appeal to baby
boomers.
   But it's a unique, engaging show that deserves a look on its own
merit. Timothy Daly and Eve Gordon star as Norman and Suzie. Each
episode intends to flash back from the present to the pre-Beatles
1960s, when Norm and Suzie were in high school, and-or 1971-ish,
when they were college revolutionaries.
   All three phases are equally evocative, and Daly and Gordon
manage to play the couple convincingly from high school to
impending middle age.
   The two-hour pilot, premiering Nov. 27, begins with Norm finding
Suzie in a store's shoe department, wearing a white wedding gown.
It flashes back to their meeting in high school, when Norm was the
goody-goody best friend of Suzie's brother Joey (Albert Macklin)
and Suzie was a wild child, hanging out with Angelo, the hood. She
develops a crush on Norm and hears ``Today I Met the Boy I'm Gonna
Marry'' on the radio.
   By 1971, they are living together at college. He's a disc jockey
on the university radio station, she's an aspiring documentary
filmmaker out to change the world. They spout free love, but become
jealous. Suzie walks out after getting the message via The Chambers
Brothers' ``Time Has Come Today.''
   Cut to the '80s. Two children later, she is a technical
filmmaker working in a medical lab. He is a program director at a
radio station. They are divorced, and Suzie is about to get married
again, to a saintly, globe-trotting doctor who performs cosmetic
surgery on victims of disasters.
   By the end of the pilot, we come full circle and learn why Suzie
was trying on shoes in a wedding dress.
   The writing could be punched up, but with its realistic
references, like a 1971 remark about the hallucinogen psilocybin,
and offbeat touches, such as a Satanist butler in 1988, ``Almost
Grown'' could develop a following.
   Daly, brother of Tyne Daly of ``Cagney & Lacey, takes up sis'
old time period, Monday nights at 10 p.m. ET.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-MaryTylerMoore Adv24-25   09-19 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Mary Tyler Moore, Adv 24-25,0498</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Married Mary Needs Help in MTM's Newest Try</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   She's a single gal, a spunky single gal, living
in a pastel New York. Mom hovers nearby, fussing and worried but
basically supportive. There's only one camera and no laugh track.
   Based on the premiere episode, it might seem that CBS has booked
``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd'' instead of Mary Tyler Moore's
as yet untitled show for its Wednesday night schedule.
   There's even a cute Molly Dodd-style misunderstanding when Mary,
who works for the city government, tries to straighten out a
licensing problem for a hulking, dirty hot dog vendor who speaks
six words of English. Mom mistakes the hulk for the sensitive,
good-looking beau Mary has been bragging about.
   This might have worked with the neurotic Molly, who was just
desperate enough to fall for the hot-dog man. But Mary, our Mary,
would never ever be so needy, and the bit falls flat. She goes from
a cute meeting to a marriage proposal in one easy episode.
   It's been 11 years, and two failed shows, since Mary Tyler Moore
left the newsroom in Minneapolis. As Lucille Ball found in her
brief, disastrous return to series television two years ago, you
can ride about one week on good will. Next week you need a good
script.
   The first half-hour is a lukewarm start at best, with Mary given
awful lines such as this about her ex-husband: ``I married a man
with principles but no property, but I left a man with property but
no principles.''
   The show will be about a married Mary, and the first episode
lays out the possibilities for conflict. She is a former Peace
Corps member, he's an ex-Marine. She engages her son in dialogue,
he gives his kids orders. Her Mom is an old leftist who spouts
slogans about ``the masses,'' his Dad is so far right that he takes
his vacations at West Point.
   A key to the show's success will be the development of co-star
Edward J. Moore, who is handsome and sensitive _ yeah, another way
of saying dull _ in the first episode. He has to do better.
   Mary does have strong support in Mom, Eileen Heckart, a 1972
Oscar winner for her supporting role in ``Butterflies are Free'';
and John Randolph, a Tony Award winner for his featured role in
``Broadway Bound'' in 1987, who plays her new father-in-law.
   Mary's fate on Tuesday night, opposite ABC's ``Head of the
Class'' and NBC's ``Unsolved Mysteries,'' partly depends on the
success of former co-star Dick Van Dyke, who is also returning to
series television.
   The Van Dyke show was not available for review, which is not a
good omen for the former Mr. and Mrs. Rob Petrie.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2055EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-TV101 Adv24-25   09-19 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-TV 101, Adv 24-25,0380</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`TV 101': Not for Advanced Viewers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Credit ``TV 101'' with truth in titling _ it's
not for advanced viewers. However, this production from Grant
Tinker's new GTG Entertainment for CBS figures to be one of the
season's better offerings for the teen audience.
   ``TV 101'' may confront teens with some of the hard issues that
television rarely even puts before adults.
   It's also a rare instance of television looking at itself, with
the cameras following a high school class learning to use
television instead of publishing the usual newspaper. Jumpy amateur
camera work mixed with the professional work keeps the pace lively,
although looking through the viewfinder quickly gets old.
   Sam Robards stars as Kevin Keegan, a 29-year-old video producer
who is lured into a teaching job by his old high school journalism
teacher, Emily Walker (Brynn Thayer), who's not so much older.
Let's issue a preliminary ``Mrs. Robinson'' alert here, and see
what develops.
   Keegan may be pathetic when he's in his dirty living room,
mooning over his broken marriage and his distant daughter, but back
at FDR High he has all the swagger that made him such a terror as a
teen-age Horace Greeley. Maybe his old nemesis, the dim-witted
reactionary principal Edward Steadman (Leon Russam), gets his
juices flowing.
   The journalism class is a most appealing collection of young
talent. The focus in the first episode is on Andrew White, who
plays bright underachiever Vance Checker.
   Checker is first spied smoking dope in the parking lot, but
don't worry about the show being soft on drugs. Drugs lead to
death. Fortuitously, the death also makes for some compelling video
that helps the student station overcome the opposition of the
principal.
   Yes, ``TV 101'' tends to slam its messages home and events
unfold in predictable fashion, but the lessons are skillfully
sugar-coated. With its high school setting, ``TV 101'' is
positioned to explore any and all issues of interest to teens.
   It deserves a look, though it faces hard competition on Tuesday
night from ABC's ``Who's the Boss'' and NBC's ``Matlock.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-MurphyBrown Adv24-25   09-19 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Murphy Brown, Adv 24-25,0395</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Murphy Brown' Struggling to Be a Hit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most of the people involved in ``Murphy Brown''
need to be slapped _ hard _ for their own good. They're messing up
what could have been one of the bright shows of the new season.
   Candice Bergen is terrific in the lead role of a driven network
star, sort of a tall Barbara Walters, who plunges back into the
stresses of the job after a month drying out at the Betty Ford
Clinic.
   Bergen is elegant, understated and believable. However, her
supporting cast adopts a buffoonish style better suited to the Moe,
Larry and Shemp production of ``Marat-Sade.''
   The worst offender is Grant Shaud, who plays young executive
producer Miles Silverberg. It's a funny idea that Murphy's boss is
a short, nerdy Harvard MBA, but Shaud isn't allowed to stop there.
He acts like a disturbed adolescent, reduced to hugging a desk and
all but drooling after the climax of the episode.
   In the premiere, Murphy gets an exclusive interview with a man
who has been romantically linked with a candidate for vice
president, who already has a husband. The interview is offered on
condition that Murphy not ask the big question _ did he sleep with
the candidate? Murphy asks anyway.
   Incredibly, we don't see his reaction to this double-cross.
There isn't a clue why Miles is gibbering at the end of the
interview, which should have been ambush journalism at its best.
   The script of the first episode also suffers from toilet humor,
including the possibility of mispronouncing ``Shiite'' and milking
a cheap laugh about tampons.
   However, there are glimmers of a great show struggling for air _
particularly in Murphy's first meeting with the male bimbo. ``I'll
bet that sheepish grin of yours got you pretty far,'' the
suspicious Murphy tells him.
   How far will Murphy go? CBS has given the show a sporting chance
with a 9 p.m. Monday slot leading into ``Designing Women,''
competing with ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' and NBC's Monday
movie.
   ``Murphy Brown'' could be smart and stylish, this season's
``L.A. Law.'' It needs to get off Gilligan's Island, and fast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-DearJohn Adv24-25   09-19 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Dear John, Adv 24-25,0363</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Judd Hirsch Returns to Television in Promising Sitcom</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: In penultimate graf, ``The show ...,'' the period after Ed.
Weinberger is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Judd Hirsch is back on television, once again
the sad sack in a crew as strange as the bunch on ``Taxi.''
   Hirsch plays the newly divorced John Lacey, who returns to New
York City after being booted out of his suburban home by an
unfaithful wife. This is not glittering Manhattan, either, but
frumpy, funky Rego Park in Queens where John hopes to start over.
   To that end, he tries to join a singles club. When he mistakenly
wanders into an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting and explains that
there weren't any signs, the group leader demands, ``Well, what did
you expect? `Emotionally Shattered This Way,' `Lushes to Your
Left?'''
   No one needs to paint a ``losers'' sign to explain the ``One to
One Club'' or its leader, Louise Mercer (Jane Carr). Louise isn't
very interested in the members as people, but she is insatiably
curious about any sexual problems that might have broken up their
marriages.
   Jere Burns has the delicious role of Kirk, the self-made lounge
lizard who acts and talks alarmingly like Dan Aykroyd in the old
``two wild and crazy guys'' sketches with Steve Martin on
``Saturday Night Live.''
   ``Stick with me, you're gonna make out like a bandit,'' Kirk
tell John. Eyeing the room, Kirk adds, ``We could really get our
turkeys tetrazzinied in this place.''
   Barry Groener is Ralph, whose Bulgarian wife left him five hours
after the wedding ceremony, and Isabella Hofmann plays a normal
woman _ at least in the first episode _ who seems destined for a
larger role in John's life.
   The show reunites Hirsch with Ed. Weinberger, one of the
executive producers of ``Taxi'' and a veteran of ``The Mary Tyler
Moore Show.''
   Given its strong cast, good writing and Thursday night timeslot
after ``Cheers'' on NBC, ``Dear John'' figures to be around a while.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
