<DOCNO> AP880919-0210 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2056EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-FallTV-MidnightCaller Adv24-25   09-19 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Midnight Caller, Adv 24-25,0432</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Midnight Caller:' Don't Call Us</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Right off, you know this is no ordinary show:
   ``Call me Angel,'' says the disembodied voice at the bottom of
the grave, our vantage point as we see Jack Killian (Gary Cole)
standing above. ``That's Jack Killian. He put me here, but I don't
blame him.''
   The alert viewer will immediately realize the two possibilities
for NBC's ``Midnight Caller.'' It is either a delicious semi-satire
on film noir detective movies, or a mindless, self-important crime
drama that a network mistook for daring television.
   Oh, just take a wild guess.
   Angel, we learn, is a murderess _ in a wedding dress, no less _
put to rest by Killian, a former San Francisco cop turned
late-night radio talk-show host who occasionally steps out of the
booth to blow away bad guys, or gals as the case may be.
   We know Killian's a sharp talker because in a flashback he
regales his partner with oh-so-funny tall tales about meeting
Elvis. But the laughs end when the two cops get tripped up by drug
dealers and Killian accidentally blows his partner away.
   Killian is sitting around wallowing in self-pity and presumably
wasting good one-liners, so enter Devon King _ who makes up these
names? _ played by Wendy Kilbourne, who owns a radio station and
needs a late-night talk guy. She hires Killian to dispense crime
prevention advice and otherwise entertain people who are up in the
middle of the night telephoning radio stations.
   In between Killian's witty radio repartee _ ``That's my name,
don't wear it out'' for pete's sake _ he inadvertently elicits
call-ins from killers.
   Such is Angel, a hooker who demands that her customers love her,
or else. Turns out her boyfriend threw her over and married another
gal. That'll turn 'em into serial killers every time.
   Cole is a smoldering presence, and ``Midnight Caller'' is quite
stylish, owing no doubt to co-executive producer Robert Butler, who
directed the pilots of ``Hill Street Blues'' and ``Moonlighting.''
   But a show about clever talk needs some clever writing, and
``Midnight Caller'' doesn't have it.
   Artistic justice being what it is on network television, that
probably won't matter, because ``Midnight Caller'' will undoubtedly
appeal to the all-important male 18-34 demographic, and NBC has put
it up against Tuesday night's female-appeal ``thirtysomething'' on
ABC and a historically low-rated movie on CBS.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0211 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-Murphy'sLaw Adv24-25   09-19 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Murphy's Law, Adv 24-25,0416</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>George Segal Wreaks Revenge on Television</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hardly anyone felt bad, or even noticed, when
``Kooper with a `K,''' starring George Segal, suffered sudden death
on CBS last season. It's real cause for regret now, however,
because Segal was freed to do his worst in ``Murphy's Law'' for ABC.
   In truth, the title should be ``Sam Spade Meets the Avengers and
Impersonates Columbo.''
   Murphy is a down-at-the-heels dick in San Francisco who adores
Yeats and Keats, wears an old raincoat and lusts after a Eurasian
model who has fabulous gams and shares his amazingly colorful
residence.
   ``Am I not fey?'' his character seems to say. ``Is my battered
fedora not angled rakishly? Does my rumpled raincoat not evoke pity
and amusement?''
   Maggie Han, who plays girlfriend Kamiko Fannuchi, is the only
excuse to watch the show, though even her smart, sassy character
loses luster once she succumbs to Murphy's labored attempts at
charm.
   The ``Avengers'' connection appears in the comic-book villain,
an Oriental guru who is suspected of murdering a wealthy disciple.
Murphy finds the guru in a lotus position before a complex model
train layout of the New York City subway system. There are even
tiny plastic muggers on one platform.
   John Steed would have raised an eyebrow about one-eighth of an
inch; Segal registers shock, horror and indignation _ a face-warp
that is his standard reaction to most any development.
   The audience, meanwhile, registers revulsion as Segal pulls out
the vox humana stop and revs up the tremolo as he fights for
visitation rights with his 10-year-old daughter. He's never
actually met the girl, what with being colorful and dissolute and
drunk, but judge, can't you see he has a heart o' gold?
   The mother, who has fabulous gams, interrupts her chain-smoking
just long enough to hurl abuse at Murphy. However, when Murphy is
gone, she tells her attorney, ``I wouldn't gloat, Charles. He's
still twice the man you'll ever be.''
   Gee whiskers, they just don't write dialogue like that anymore.
For this, ABC canceled ``Spenser: For Hire''?
   ``Murphy'' gets a break that ABC's programmers seldom gave
``Spenser.'' This show isn't up against NBC's popular ``Hunter,''
but comes on at 8 p.m. EST on Saturday, where it is unlikely to
beat either ``227'' or ``Amen'' on NBC.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-Tattinger's Adv24-25   09-19 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Tattinger's, Adv 24-25,0515</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Tattinger's' _ A Bunch of Characters in Search of a Premise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As if the fact that it comes from the same
producers weren't enough, NBC is even giving ``Tattinger's'' the
old ``St. Elsewhere'' time slot.
   If that wonderful and late-lamented show was a square peg in a
round hole, ``Tattinger's'' is a trapezoid. It seems that NBC's
Wednesday 10 p.m. slot is set aside for television that defies
categories, the network's lost-and-found.
   ``Tattinger's'' seems to be aiming for classy-though-absurd, but
it tries too hard to be wacky, a quality that came naturally to
``St. Elsewhere.''
   While ``Tattinger's'' looks for an identity, the search party is
pretty intriguing.
   First there's Nick Tattinger, played with aplomb by the
underrated Stephen Collins. He's a street-fighter who has turned
business sense and personal charm into a successful Manhattan
restaurant that serves the swells and acts as the backdrop to drama
of both the crime and family variety.
   Nick's ex-wife Hillary, played by Blythe Danner as a good-sport
socialite, is trying to raise two teen-age daughters and establish
a meaningful relationship with the quintessential good man, Norman
(Simon Jones).
   Mary Beth Hurt doesn't appear in the pilot but will play the
chef. Jerry Stiller is Sid, the restaurant manager and Nick's loyal
friend. British actor-director Roderick Cook is a snotty
headwaiter. Patrice Colihan and Chay Lentin play the Tattinger
daughters, Nina and Winnifred. Why would a guy like Nick let his
kid be named Winnifred?
   In the premiere episode, airing Oct. 26, Nick has returned from
Paris where he fled after a deranged drug dealer took a potshot at
him. Zach Grenier, who somehow manages to make his eyes roll in
different directions, will apparently be a regular as gun-happy
degenerate Sonny Franks.
   Nick had sold the restaurant, but when an evil real estate
developer tries to muscle the residents of the ``Tattinger's''
block _ Jack Gilford has a cameo as Shlomo, the newsstand operator
_ the juices start flowing, and Nick just can't resist a good fight.
   By the end of the episode, he has reclaimed the restaurant and
set up a line of sexual tension with his ex-wife, who has delivered
the ultimatum that he is to be a good father or good-bye.
   So he'll try to be both a junkyard dog and a debutante's dad.
When he shows up disheveled at Nina's coming out party, she
complains, ``Why you be like the other fathers? They never get shot
at.''
   The Gershwin-like theme music heralds the co-star of the show,
New York City, where ``Tattinger's'' is filmed. The creators'
combination of affection and fear for their locale is tangible.
   Although the pilot is not terribly impressive, there's too much
talent behind ``Tattinger's'' to write it off. It's a character
piece that will take time to evolve. Perhaps as it did with ``St.
Elsewhere,'' NBC will give it some.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
