<DOCNO> AP880919-0213 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-EmptyNest Adv24-25   09-19 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Empty Nest, Adv 24-25,0296</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<HEAD>`Empty Nest' Is Saturday Night Dog</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Empty Nest,'' an addition to NBC's Saturday
night schedule, has one outstanding performer, an actor who can
convincingly convey love or impatience or gratitude with the twitch
of an eyebrow.
   Unfortunately, Bear is confined in a small supporting role as
Dreyfuss, dog and confidant to Dr. Harry Weston (Richard Mulligan).
   Harry, who has been widowed 18 months, fusses over three
daughters: Carol (Dinah Manoff), whose husband recently left her;
Barbara (Kristy McNichol), who is a cop; and Emily, who phones
frequently from college.
   Next-door neighbor Charley (David Leisure, the lying salesman
from the Isuzu ads) drops in frequently, while Harry's office is
supervised by nurse Laverne (Park Overall).
   One hoped-for episode of ``Empty Nest'' would send Charley and
Laverne on a cruise to the Bermuda triangle. Laverne is especially
annoying, doing jokes in which the punchline is some variation on
``I'm from Arkansas'' (therefore I am a hopeless hick). The state
should sue.
   ``Empty Nest,'' by the producers of ``Golden Girls,''
exemplifies this year's ``more of the same'' programming philosophy
at NBC. It follows right after ``Golden Girls'' on the Saturday
night schedule and is set in the same Miami neighborhood.
   If that philosophy worked for Lisa Bonet in the ``Different
World'' spinoff from ``The Cosby Show,'' why not for a Saint
Bernard-German shepherd-golden retriever mix?
   There's nothing really wrong with ``Empty Nest'' and nothing to
particularly recommend it. The show runs half an hour and has
commercial breaks, which fills the time for NBC. Maybe it will do
the same for others.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
