<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 2058EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-FallTV-Paradise Adv24-25   09-19 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Fall TV-Paradise, Adv 24-25,0350</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv24-25</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 24-25, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Paradise' Is Rare Western Series</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Fall TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the never-ending struggle to find something
to run against NBC's hit comedy lineup on Thursdays, CBS is trying
another genre _ the Western.
   Lee Horsley (``Matt Houston'') returns to prime-time television
as Ethan Allen Cord (no relation to the furniture folks), a
mysterious gunslinger who inherits a passel of young 'uns when his
sister dies back East.
   It seems since he sent her a picture of himself standing in
front of the town's dry goods store, his dying sister mistook him
for a successful businessman who would make a perfect dad for her
kids. Instead, he's a down-at-the-heels gunfighter who's running
from a slew of bad guys and is temporarily holed up in the
depressed mining town of Paradise.
   Although the writing needs to be beefed up, the series admirably
aspires to a lean, terse, authentic feel, and Horsley, in real life
a Colorado horseman, was made to play Westerns. In the pilot, Cord
tries to shield the kids from his violent way of life, even as the
boys become fascinated by gunplay and Cord seeks revenge against
the men who shot him.
   The kids are inoffensive in the pilot. They are 13-year-old
Claire, played by Jenny Beck; 11-year-old Joseph (Matthew Newmark);
8-year-old Benjamin (Brian Lando), and 5-year-old George, played by
Michael Carter.
   They could provide some kid appeal if the show were at an
earlier time, but it is sandwiched between distinctly adult hours,
CBS news show ``48 Hours'' and the night-time soap ``Knots
Landing.''
   To get a more adult audience, the series could and should make
more of the romantic tension between the handsome desperado Cord
and the ice queen Amelia Lawson, the local merchant played by the
fine Sigrid Thornton (``Man from Snowy River'').
   ``Paradise'' premieres Oct. 27 and is on opposite NBC's hit
comedy lineup on Thursday, a timeslot that is definitely not
paradise.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
