<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews ADV00   09-19 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, ADV 00,0536</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Chicago 19'' (Reprise) _ Chicago
   
   Chicago, the band, is approaching its 20th year in showbiz
firmly planted in the netherworld of ``adult contemporary'' music.
``Chicago 19,'' the latest offering by the former kings of Top 40,
gives a bad name to contemporary adults everywhere.
   A totally forgettable assortment of weak songs straining to be
anthems of love, the album has only one song _ the pretty ``We Can
Last Forever'' _ with any potential as a pop hit, something which
used to be Chicago's stock in trade.
   Lyrically, the songs fall into three general categories. There
are a few ``I've been hurt but I'll survive'' numbers, a couple of
``I know you've been hurt but I'll make things better'' tunes and a
some standard-issue whines about lost love.
   There are artists who can make out of such emotions music that
is tough, strong and moving. Then there are records such as
``Chicago 19,'' which take the same ingredients and ... spin around
about 33 times a minute.
   There are no satanic messages on ``Chicago 19,'' and no
endorsements of drug abuse. But this one really deserves a warning
label.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``The Indescribable Wow'' (Virgin) _ Sam Phillips
   
   Behind a shocking pink cover and even more ostentatious title is
an utterly charming record. Sam Phillips' ``The Indescribable Wow''
is a describable delight.
   As Leslie Phillips, she recorded several Christian albums before
turning to the pop music market. She decided to change her first
name, supposedly ignorant of the Sam Phillips who founded Sun
Records.
   The 26-year-old California native has a little-girl voice and a
knack for writing memorable melodies. With producer and boyfriend
T-Bone Burnett, she's crafted an inventive record rich with 1960s
influences.
   The wistful ``She Can't Tell Time'' sounds like an outtake from
the Beatles' ``Rubber Soul,'' while ``Remorse'' quotes liberally
from the Fab Four's ``She's a Woman.''
   Like most albums, ``The Indescribable Wow'' has its strong songs
and filler. But Phillips and Burnett save their most imaginative
arrangements for the weak songs, keeping boredom at bay.
   ``What Do I Do,'' for instance, is so slight it would probably
sound incomplete if strummed on an acoustic guitar. Burnett and
guest Van Dyke Parks turn it into a mini-operetta, with a full
orchestra and dreamy staggered vocals.
   ``Holding on to the Earth'' is sinister-sounding with a Farfisa
organ and what sounds like a sitar.
   Burnett is savvy enough to let the strong material stand almost
by itself. Phillips' voice is so seductive in ``I Don't Want to
Fall in Love'' that she won't be able to say the same for her
listeners. ``I Don't Know How to Say Goodbye to You'' and ``I Can't
Stop Crying'' are two other heartbreakers.
   Phillips and Burnett make a fine studio team, as any lover of
classic pop music will be able to attest.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
