<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Bagwell ADV30-02   09-19 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Bagwell, ADV 30-02,0709</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv30-02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, Sept. 30-Oct. 2, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Wendy Bagwell Still Can't Tune His Guitar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irrepressible Wendy Bagwell has spent
more than a quarter century as a gospel music singer and humorist
and still has trouble tuning his well-traveled guitar.
   ``I still don't know how,'' Bagwell says in a cheerful burst of
self-deprecation.
   Moments before performing in Carnegie Hall 25 years ago, he had
to seek help to get his trusty guitar ready.
   ``I asked somebody in another group if it sounded like it was in
tune,'' he recalled. ``That tells you where I am as a musician.''
   Where he is as an entertainer is celebrating the 30th
anniversary of Wendy Bagwell and the Sunliters, one of gospel
music's most popular and enduring groups.
   ``It's been great,'' he said, alluding to sweet memories of
singing and cracking jokes in hot school auditoriums and small town
churches and dusty fairs since the late 1950s.
   ``If I wipe out this year, I can look up at the Lord and say
thanks for letting me make it with no talent.''
   The record indicates otherwise. The five-member group has
recorded 60 albums, toured Europe, sold several million records,
has a wall covered with awards and has made countless people laugh.
   Bagwell is best known for his record, ``Here Come the
Rattlesnakes,'' an amusing song based on a true story about the
time the Sunliters performed in a church near the Kentucky-West
Virginia line. Soon they discover church members getting rattlers
out of a box as part of the worship service.
   In the key line, the terrified Bagwell discovers there's no back
door.
   ``Where do they want one?'' he asks.
   The song is on the album ``This, That and the Other,'' which
continues to sell. Two million copies have been sold, an
extraordinary amount for gospel music.
   ``It got us off big orange drinks and weenies for a while to
come,'' Bagwell says.
   It also led to him being named comedian of the year by Record
World magazine. ``I didn't even know I WAS a comedian,'' he said.
   The Sunliters' concerts, held just about every weekend, are a
50-50 mix of music and humor.
   Some of the humor is inspired by the audience, such as when
someone gets up and walks toward the back.
   ``Don't write nothin' on the wall,'' Bagwell is fond of saying
to the red-faced person.
   Toward the end of the performance, the light touch is set aside
and veteran singer Jan (``little Jan'') Buckner tells about how,
when she was a baby, her mother was killed by a drunken driver.
   She recounts her time in orphanages and foster homes and then
the group performs the gospel song ``I Firmly Promise You.''
   ``The best compliment we get is from people who say they laughed
'til their stomach hurt and then they cried at the end of the
program,'' Bagwell said.
   Down through the years, Bagwell said, cautious record companies
have wanted him to tone down his humor. These days he refuses,
saying, ``People aren't all that starchy about things.''
   He's resisted offers to cross over into pop music, saying,
``We're blessed where we are. It's mighty good people we sing to.''
   The group rarely works seven straight days for a couple of
reasons. For one, they like to be home on Sunday to attend their
own church.
   ``I never wanted to wear people out,'' Bagwell adds. ``What's
that saying? `I love turnip greens, but not seven days a week.' ''
   He's been telling audiences for years that he's from Smyrna,
Ga., just outside Atlanta. That's not true.
   ``I really live in Hiram. It ain't on the way to nothin'. The
only way you'd come here is on purpose. There's no one-way streets
or red lights.''
   And still he struggles with his guitar.
   ``I played just three chords as a young man. Nowadays, with this
complicated stuff, there's songs I still can't find the chords to.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 30-Oct. 2</NOTE>
