<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1247EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-EXP--VolcanoResearch Adv22   09-19 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EXP--Volcano Research, Adv 22,0684</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv22</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Thursday, Sept. 22, and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Augustine Research May Provide Valuable Information</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL JENKINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTINE VOLCANO, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Working from a plywood shack
and a collection of tents perched on the flank of Augustine
Volcano, researchers are setting up a high-tech system to measure
the volcano's shudders to within an inch.
   When they're done, scientists using briefcase-sized laser
instruments ``could detect less than that, but it's a matter of
whether you believe it,'' says Gene Iwatsubo of the U.S. Geological
Survey, one of the researchers trying to puzzle out how the volcano
works and whether its eruptions can be predicted.
   ``The thrust of the research is to try to find precursors, signs
of eruption,'' says Juergen Kienle, a University of Alaska
geophysics professor. ``The more precursors you have, the better
off you are.''
   Augustine Volcano juts 4,000 feet out of Kamishak Bay on the
west side of Cook Inlet. It appears benign but there have been six
major eruptions since its discovery in 1778. One, in 1883,
triggered a 30-foot wave that destroyed houses and boats at Port
Graham, nearly 50 miles away.
   Computer models show a slide-generated tsunami would reach
Homer, a Kachemak Bay fishing community of 4,000 people about 70
miles away, in about an hour. A smaller wave would reach Anchorage,
175 miles away, three hours later.
   ``We can't assess the probability of a slide occurring,'' says
state seismologist John Davies. ``All we're saying is there is a
possiblity. We have no way to calculate the likelihood. But if we
can't calculate the possibility, we feel it's best to monitor it.''
   Information that may enable scientists to predict eruptions
accurately at Augustine may be of great value to other parts of the
world where millions of people live in the shadows of volcanoes _
or on them.
   ``If you tell a mayor there is a 5 percent chance his town will
be wiped out, it's hard for him to take action,'' Davies says. ``If
you tell him there's a 75 percent chance his town is going to be
wiped out, he can act.''
   Kienle and seven researchers from the University of Alaska
Geophysical Institute and USGS have been pounding in benchmarks and
performing surveys and gas studies, a $100,000 effort by the
state-federal cooperative Alaska Volcano Observatory formed this
year. A magnetic study also is planned.
   ``This is really an uncomplicated volcano,'' Kienle says. ``This
one is really easy to deal with. It's very beautiful. Very active.''
   Augustine, the most active of some 60 volcanoes in the Aleutian
Arc, erupted in 1812, 1883, 1935, 1964, 1976 and 1986, when it
spewed ash over much of south-central Alaska, disrupting air
traffic.
   Seismographs sensitive enough to detect passing planes, nearby
boats and high winds were placed on the volcano in 1970. Their
tracings on machines in Fairbanks mapped the 1976 eruption, and the
eight months of seismic activity before the eruption 10 years later.
   In January and February of 1986, scientists began briefing the
Air Force, Federal Aviation Administration and state Division of
Emergency Services about a possible eruption. Early March 26, the
seismographs showed earthquakes at the rate of about 50 per day.
Within hours, the rate to 500, then 5,000. Augustine blew its top
the next day.
   ``It's a constant process of becoming better at forecasting when
the volcano will become active,'' Kienle says. ``We are getting
better. We will continue to get better.''
   Four seismographs ring the volcano at an elevation of about
1,000 feet and two are near the peak. Three sets of tiltmeters
measure changes in the surface.
   ``One of the things we're discovering is that most volcanoes
have their own uniqueness,'' Davies says. ``Not every detail that
one learns at one volcano is applicable to another. It's the
hopeful assumption that you can apply it elsewhere. I don't think
it is a long-shot hope. I think it's likely.
   ``The value is obvious. ''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sept. 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
