<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:FordProbe     09-19 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Ford Probe,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Ford Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>(EDITORS: Also moving on business wire.)
^By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With little advertising and less fanfare, the
Ford Probe is speeding through dealer showrooms, keeping most
buyers waiting at least six weeks for delivery of a car that may be
carving its own market niche.
   Since its formal introduction last May, the Probe, built beside
the Mazda MX-6 at Mazda Motor Manufacturing USA Corp.'s Flat Rock
plant south of Detroit, is being sold three months in advance of
assembly line runs, Ford Motor Co. analyst Ray Windecker said.
   Delivery time can vary depending on what kind and color
automobile a customer wants.
   The American car-buying public got a dose of what Ford had in
mind months before its formal introduction. The news media,
specifically the automotive magazines, sang the car's praises.
   ``By the time the cars were introduced, more than one-third of
the car-buying age populous was aware of the car,'' Windecker said.
   ``I don't think there's been that much excitement about a
domestic car since a Taurus,'' another Ford that was introduced in
December 1985, said Beth Fusco, an auto analyst with Moody's
Investor Services in New York City.
   ``They did a lot of advance promotion for the car in
magazines,'' she said. ``I thought that was a pretty sophisticated
send-off. I think they did a good job promoting it, and I think the
car is selling itself.''
   Probe's base price is $11,490 with a 2.2 liter, four-cylinder
engine. The car, with hidden headlamps and a swept-back rear deck,
can be upgraded with a turbocharged engine and option packages to
$17,292.
   Earlier this summer, scores of Probes reached the end of the
assembly line at Flat Rock needing repairs.
   Mazda quality control manager James G. Bouck said the quality
problems were created when a second shift was added at the plant _
a joint-venture between Ford and Mazda _ and some workers were
retrained and moved from one shift to another.
   Bouck, who moved to Mazda from General Motors Corp., said Mazda
has more stringent quality demands that some other automakers. That
can result in more cars landing in repair lots before being shipped
to dealers.
   ``Our repair inventory is about 300 now,'' he said, calling it
an expected number.
   Probe sales have grown at a steady clip _ about 600 cars more
are sold each month than in the preceding one. No one at Ford would
reveal projected sales figures, but Windecker said demand has
outstripped those projections.
   It's too early to tell exactly where Probe will fit into the
American car market.
   ``They are creating a different niche for themselves,'' Fusco
said. But, she cautioned, ``I think you have to be really careful
when you're creating a niche.
   ``Look what GM did with Fiero,'' she said, referring to the
Pontiac two-seater that sold well in its first few years on the
market before falling off dramatically. GM stopped making the car
earlier this year.
   Analysts said the Probe has capitalized on the No. 2 and most
profitable automaker's strengths _ solid design, careful marketing
and reliability.
   ``They have done many things right,'' said Richard Henderson, an
analyst with the Pershing Division of Donaldson, Lufkin and
Jenrette in New York City. ``It's a combination of many, many
little factors, some borrowed from Europe, some from North America
and some borrowed from Mazda.
   ``Combine that with a nice fit in its product mix ... and you've
got a very successful car,'' Henderson said.
   Like other newly introduced cars, Probe's engineering initially
may take a back seat to its looks.
   ``What is there out there in that price range that looks that
neat?'' asked Fusco. ``I think people buy cars because they look
good, and secondarily because the quality is good and the warranty
is good.''
   Like other Fords, Probe carries a one-year bumper-to-bumper
warranty and a six-year, 60,000-mile powertrain warranty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:Security     09-19 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Security,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's automakers and suppliers are
offering a growing array of anti-theft devices in an effort to stem
the growing number of stolen vehicles.
   Most of the devices marketed by the Big Three, Honda, Mazda,
Nissan and Toyota involve alarms that honk the horn and flash the
headlights to scare off a would-be car thief. Others systems
disengage starter motors.
   Most of the devices supplied by automakers as standard equipment
come on the maker's more expensive cars. The systems are optional
on many less-expensive models.
   Then there are devices that an owner can pick up at a local auto
parts store _ things that fit around the steering column like a big
doughnut, menacing-looking hooks that lock the steering wheel to
the brake pedal, and still other systems that detect motion and
sound, such as breaking glass.
   Despite all the technology put into anti-theft systems by
automakers and parts suppliers, there was a 5.3 percent rise in the
number of car thefts in the nation from 1986 to 1987, the latest
annual figures available from the FBI.
   And the National Auto Theft Bureau in Chicago says while those
devices may stymie thieves, most of the cars stolen nowadays fall
into two categories _ cars in which keys were left in the ignition
and cars that were simply towed away.
   ``Approximately 13 percent of the recovered (stolen) vehicles
still had the owner's keys in the vehicles ...'' said Tim Kett of
the organization. ``About 10 percent of the vehicles were towed.
This is a common technique used (by thieves) in urban areas.''
   When tow trucks aren't used by thieves, there are a variety of
products offered outside dealerships designed to keep a driver's
car where the driver left it.
   Collars that cover ignition switches and joints in steering
columns can prevent the plastic covering from being easily removed,
exposing wiring for the column controls, including the ignition.
   Alarms that sound when a door is pried open when windows are
smashed or when the car moves also are available.
   Motion detectors have caused some headaches, especially in
heavily urban areas, when they can be activated by a nudge from a
passerby or another vehicle, for instance.
   Aaron Lowe, director of government affairs for the Vehicle
Security Association, a trade organization for makers and marketers
of alarm and vehicle protection systems, said the security industry
is beginning to make more sophisticated and less-sensitive motion
detectors.
   There are some systems available in the after-market which can
alert a driver through a pager that someone may be trying to get
into a car. There are systems which interrupt the electrical or
fuel systems when a door, hood or trunk is opened.
   ``There are a wide range of things a consumer can get, depending
on where they are and what they want to protect,'' Lowe said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880919-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:SafestCars     09-19 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Safest Cars,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Safest Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: This story moved previously on the wires.)</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The likelihood of injury from a car accident
ranges widely among different car models, but for the most part
safety increases with automobile size, according to an insurance
industry report.
   The report on injury claims involving 207 popular models shows
that small cars have by far the highest injury loss records, while
station wagons and large cars often afford the greatest protection.
   According to the insurance group, the Mercedes-Benz SDL-SEL
sedan, which is equipped with a driver-side airbag, had the best
safety record with injury losses that were 58 percent lower than
the average for all cars. Close behind was the Pontiac Safari
station wagon.
   The least safe car was the 4-door Chevrolet Spectrum which had
injury losses that were 78 percent above average, followed by the
4-door Chevrolet Sprint and 4-door Hyundai Excel, both of which had
losses 67 percent above average, the report said.
   Of the 10 cars with the best injury loss record, nine were
categorized as ``large'' cars including five station wagons and
vans. The Saab 9000 was the only ``mid-size'' car in the top 10
vehicles, ranking fifth best with injury losses 51 percent lower
than average.
   The 10 vehicles with the worst injury loss record were all in
the small sedan or small sports car category.
   Exceptions to the general trend that small cars afford the least
protection include another Saab model, the Saab 900, as well as the
Volkswagen Vanagon, the Toyota van, Porsche 944 coupe and Mercedes
Benz 380-560 SL convertible. All are in the ``small'' category but
had better than average injury loss records.
   But except for the Saab 900, all 60 of the ``small'' sedan
models had higher injury losses than average.
   The report by the Highway Loss Data Institute, an insurance
industry research group, covered 1985-87 model cars, but spokesmen
said the findings can be used as a guide for later model vehicles
as well.
   ``The loss experience of most cars is consistent from one model
year to another,'' said Brian O'Neill, the institute's president.
   The report said the results were adjusted to take into account
various ``non-vehicle factors'' such as types and ages of drivers
that might be associated with particular vehicles.
   The 2-door Chevrolet Cavalier was the only mid-size car to have
``substantially worse than average'' injury losses _ 36 percent
worse than average for all vehicles.
   All but two of the 35 ``large'' cars, station wagons, vans and
speciality cars had lower than average injury losses. The 4-door
Oldsmobile Delta 88 and Cadillac Fleetwood-Deville were the
exceptions, ranked as average.
   Of the 207 cars and vans included in the study, 40 had safety
records that were characterized as ``substantially better'' than
average, while 32 were ``substantially worse.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
