<HEAD>Cars: Conversion Vans</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY702</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cars, pickups, jeeps, trucks, recreation vehicles _ and now,
conversion vans.
   One more option in considering wheels in an auto-conscious
country is the conversion van, a full-size utility and minivan that
is shipped without windows and seats and such and then converted to
a passenger vehicle.
   Some van converters start with a sheet metal box, a motor and
wheels and add seating, sidewalls, insulation, wiring, seat belts,
wood trim, radios and TVs, windows, and exterior trim.
   Conversion van sales increased 13 percent in 1987, according to
the Automotive News.
   ``We posted a 38 percent increase and are projecting even
greater interest in the 1989 model year,'' says William T. Becker,
vice president of marketing, advertising and consumer relations for
Glaval Inc., an Elkhart, Ind., conversion company.
