<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:Models     09-19 0159</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Models,0163</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Models</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1929 Duesenberg J., the 1931 Bugatti Royale and the 1928
Isotta Fraschini are among the 12 classic automobiles in the
Franklin Mint Precision Model collection.
   Model-makers at the Franklin Mint near Philadelphia sculptured
prototypes of the luxury cars on a 1:43 scale, noting details
inside and out, including tiny instruments and gauges on the
dashboards.
   Matching dies were made for each of the components, at least 50
parts for each model, which was then painted and hand-polished.
   Among the models is that of the 1931 Bugatti Royale, which
weighed in a 7,150 pounds and now valued at more than $8 million,
with some estimates over $20 million.
   Tom Monaghan, whose businesses include Domino's Pizza and the
Detroit Tigers baseball team, paid $8.1 million in 1986 for one of
six Bugatti Royales ever manufactured, said to be the only one not
housed in a museum.
</TEXT>
