<DOCNO> AP880919-0245 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 0250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a BC-SPE--Cars:Insurance     09-19 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-SPE--Cars: Insurance,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cars: Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Comparison shopping'' for an auto insurer can result in
sharply reduced insurance costs.
   ``While all auto insurance policies may appear similar, quite
the opposite is true,'' says Charles F. Wright, assistant vice
president, Aetna Life & Casualty, ``and a smart consumer can often
save hundreds of dollars.
   Some of the money-saving discounts offered by various companies,
he says, include:
   _ A ``total account'' credit to those who insure both car and
home with the same company. The credit differs from state to state,
Wright says, but is usually 10 percent off the auto premium, or 5
percent off both auto and homeowner premiums.
   _ Some companies offer a ``first accident forgiveness'' which,
after five continous accident-free years, guarantees that rates
will not go up after a first at-fault accident.
   _ Car pool commuters often qualify for discounts.
   _ Installing anti-theft devices in your car may qualify you for
a discount. ``A 5 percent credit is typical for an alarm-only
device or an active disabling mechanism which prevents the car from
starting,'' says Wright. Some companies offer a 10 percent credit
for a passive disabling device that automatically prevents the car
from starting.
   _ You can save money by insuring children who drive infrequently
because they are away at school on the parents' policy rather than
separately.
   _ Check the companies that make discounts available to females
between 30 and 64 years old who are the only drivers in the
household.
   _ Good driver discounts are offered by some companies to drivers
with accident-and-violation free records and to motorists driving
fewer than a certain number of miles a year.
   _ Some states require discounts be given to drivers who take
driver training or defensive driving courses.
   _ Drivers still at school may be entitled to a ``good student
discount'' program by maintaining a high scholastic average.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
