<2ND_LINE>PM-American Brands,0338</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No `Pac-Man' Defense This Time, Tobacco Chief Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Brands Inc., which recently thwarted a
hostile takeover with the ``Pac-Man defense'' of buying the suitor,
won't re-use the strategy to derail another possible attempt that
has emerged, the tobacco giant's chairman said in an interview
published today.
   ``You can bet this isn't going to be a Pac-Man,'' William J.
Alley was quoted as telling the Wall Street Journal.
   Speculation that American Brands would re-deploy the Pac-Man
surfaced after New York investor  LeBow's maneuvering was interpreted by
American Brands
executives as a ruse to induce them to buy Liggett, which has lost
market share in recent years to competitors, the Journal said.
   It quoted Alley as calling LeBow's move ``an outrageous ploy to
get us to bail them out from what appears to be a deteriorating
situation at Liggett.''
   The newspaper also quoted Alley as saying American Brands isn't
for sale, he has no interest in talking with LeBow and ``we
wouldn't take Liggett if they gave it to us.''
   Based in Greenwich, Conn., American Brands is a diversified
tobacco company with a 7.2 percent share of the cigarette market,
selling brands that include Lucky Strike, Pall Mall and Tareyton.
   Liggett, based in Durham, N.C., has a 3 percent market share and
makes such brands as Chesterfield, L&M and Eve.
</TEXT>
