<HEAD>Investors May Offer To Buy Service Merchandise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Service Merchandise Co. Inc. said a
group of investors that includes Chairman Raymond Zimmerman may be
preparing an offer to acquire the company in a leveraged buyout
transaction.
   S.P. Braud, vice president and chief financial officer of
Service Merchandise, said Sunday it appears that the investor
group, which also includes other senior management, intends to take
the company private.
   The company's shares now are traded on the over-the-counter
market.
   Based on the company's 33.3 million outstanding shares and
closing stock price of $13.50 a share Friday, Service Merchandise
has a market value of $449.5 million.
   Service Merchandise, the largest catalog showroom retailer in
the United States, said in a news release Sunday that a special
committee of the company's board of directors was set up to respond
to any such offer and to take other action related to a possible
sale.
   ``The investor group has informed the special committee that,
given relevant financing restrictions, any offer it might make
would be at or near recent market prices for the company's stock,''
the release said.
   Zimmerman declined to comment on any possible deal.
