<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Lower On Follow-Through</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, with soybeans falling substantially in
a continuation of the selling flurry that erupted near the close of
Friday's session.
   The decline was technically motivated, since fundamental
supply-and-demand factors were bullish for soybeans, analysts said.
   Investment houses were major sellers of soybean futures, said
Dale Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc.
   ``They're looking for some sort of support down here'' at price
levels 40 cents to 50 cents a bushel below last week's highs, he
said.
   Weekend rains in Brazil, where the soybean crop is just getting
started, also pressured U.S. soybean futures prices, analysts said.
   Grain futures basically followed the soybean market lower,
although early losses in the wheat market were limited by
confirmation of new sales of subsidized U.S. wheat to Algeria and
Morocco, Gustafson said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 2\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.16{ a bushel; corn was }
cent to 2{ cents lower with September at $2.77 a bushel; oats were
4} cents to 6 cents lower with December at $2.60 a bushel; soybeans
were 8 cents to 12 cents lower with September at $8.38 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed while pork futures were lower in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .50 cent lower to .30 cent higher with October
at 69.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .70 cent
higher with September at 80.05 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to
.17 cent lower with October at 37.80 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .22 cent to .70 cent lower with February at 50.15
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled higher on Friday.
</TEXT>
