<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1206EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-Rice     09-19 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Rice,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Agricultural Union Will Ask U.S. Farmers For Help</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's powerful Zenchu agricultural union said it
plans to seek support from U.S. farmers in its fight to protect the
Japanese rice market from foreign imports.
   A spokesman for Zenchu, the Central Union of Agricultural
Cooperatives, said at a meeting Monday it would send a team of
representatives to the United States to seek support directly from
American farmers.
   The union Monday also called for a demonstration by 1 million
Japanese in October to show their support for the union's stance.
   Last week, the U.S. Rice Millers Association filed a complaint
with the U.S. Trade Representative's office under Section 301 of
the recently passed U.S. omnibus trade law, which requires the
president to retaliate against a country failing to give equal
access to its markets.
   The U.S. trade office turned down a similar complaint under the
old Section 301 before the omnibus trade law was passed.
   Union Executive Director Tokuo Matsumoto emphasized at the
meeting that the rice growers have the support of Japanese
consumers.
   Matsumoto also said that, ``the U.S. market for corn and wheat
is effectively closed, so it is strange to criticize the closed
nature of the Japanese rice market.''
   Matsumoto said it was impossible to make a simple comparison
between prices in an open and closed market.
   ``It is necessary to consider various factors such as wages and
consumer prices in general,'' he said.
</TEXT>
