<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-CSXRestructuring     09-19 0296</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CSX Restructuring,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Announces Restructuring Program, Will Repurchase Stock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. is embarking on a billion-dollar
restructuring program aimed at focusing the company's resources on
its transportation businesses, officials announced today.
   CSX officials said the company would repurchase up to 60 million
common shares and sell the company's natural gas transmission and
natural gas liquids processing businesses, Texas Gas Transmission
Corp. of Owensboro, Ky. and CSX NGL Corp. of Houston.
   The company is ``immediately launching an aggressive program
designed to significantly reduce operating and overhead costs,''
officials said. It will also consider selling some of its resort
properties.
   Wall Street reacted enthusiastically to the announcement. CSX
stock rose sharply on the New York Stock Exchange today, trading at
$30.75 a share, up $3.87{ from Friday.
   CSX said it would purchase up to 40 million shares, representing
26 percent of its outstanding stock, through a ``Dutch auction''
beginning later this week.
   Under the auction, shareholders will be invited to specify
prices ranging from $28 to $33 per share for their holdings. The
company will then select a single purchase price and will buy up to
40 million shares offered at or below that price.
   The offer is being mailed to shareholders this week and will
close Oct. 18, CSX spokesman Thomas E. Hoppin said.
   The company then may repurchase the remainder of the 60 million
shares, approximately 38 percent of its oustanding shares, in the
open market or in private negotiations, officials said.
   At $33 a share, the buyback would cost CSX $1.98 billion.
   Initial funding for the repurchase will come from cash and
short-term borrowings.
   The company also said it will redeem four series of preferred
stock issued by its subsidiaries CSX Transportion Inc. and Seaboard
Coast Line Railroad Co.
</TEXT>
