<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Output     09-19 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Output,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Industrial Output Up 3.5 Percent in First Half</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The index of industrial production in the
European Economic Community rose an estimated 3.5 percent in the
first half of 1988 from the same period last year, the EEC said.
   Eurostat, the trading bloc's statistics agency, said Monday that
by comparison, industrial output in the United States rose 6
percent in the first half and in Japan by nearly 11 percent.
   The increase in the EEC index was led by a 6.1 percent jump in
production of capital goods, Eurostat said. Output of consumer
goods rose 3.2 percent and of intermediate products by 2.6 percent.
   The index, using 1980 as a basis year at 100, was calculated at
111.5 in June, up from 110.1 in May and an average 107.4 for all of
1987.
   Eurostat said the gains in output in the first half in the 12
EEC nations varied from 2.5 percent and 3 percent in West Germany
and France, to around 5 percent in Britain, Italy and Spain and to
nearly 10 percent in Luxembourg and Ireland.
   The Netherlands was the only EEC country where industrial output
fell in the first half. It declined by 3.3 percent, mainly because
of a drop in natural gas production.
</TEXT>
