<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Immigrants-Poll 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Immigrants-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Majority of Americans View Immigrants As Negative Impact On
Economy</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 bgng `Nineteen percent ...' to ADD that
remainder had no clear opinion.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of Americans believe immigrants
have a negative impact on the economy, and almost half said the
newcomers contribute little to American culture, according to a
poll published today.
   ``A lot of our old prejudices are still at work,'' said Maurice
A. Roberts, editor of Interpreter Releases, a Washington-based
national immigration journal, said of the Los Angeles Times poll.
   The poll surveyed 1,418 people nationwide last weekend, four
months after the one-year immigrant legalization program ended and
two months after the government began full enforcement of sanctions
against employers who hire illegal aliens.
   Asked whether immigrants get more or less from the U.S economy
through social services and unemployment benefits than they
contribute through taxes and work, 64 percent of the respondents
said immigrants take more than they give.
   Nineteen percent said immigrants contributed more, while 4
percent said immigrants benefited and contributed equally to the
economy. The rest of the respondents had no clear opinion,
according to the poll.
   Asked whether immigrants have made a contribution in the last
decade to American culture, 46 percent said they haven't, while 40
percent said immigrants have enriched the culture. The rest had no
clear opinion.
   The margin of error was four percentage points in either
direction.
</TEXT>
