<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pillsbury-Godfather's     09-19 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury-Godfather's,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Sells Godfather's Pizza Inc. to Management Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co. announced Monday the sale of
its Godfather's Pizza unit to the restaurant division's management.
   Terms of the agreement were not announced, Pillsbury said in a
prepared statement.
   Godfather's Pizza, which will remain based in Omaha, Neb., has
542 restaurants, 178 of which are company-owned. It is the nation's
fifth-largest pizza restaurant chain.
   The management group, led by its president, Herman Cain, began
negotiations with Pillsbury last March, when the parent company
announced its desire to sell the Omaha-based restaurant chain.
   Godfather's Pizza was founded in Omaha by Willy Theisen in 1973
and sold its first franchise a year later.
   Godfather's became a public company in 1982 and a year later
merged with Chart House Inc. to form DiversiFoods Inc., a
Chicago-based restaurant concern which included 377 Burger King
stores.
   At its peak in 1984, Godfather's had 911 restaurants generating
$365 million in annual sales.
   Pillsbury acquired Diversifoods in 1985, primarily for its
Burger King franchises.
   Cain, who served as vice president of Burger King's Philadelphia
region since 1983, was appointed president of Godfather's in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
