<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Close Sharply Lower On Lack of Demand</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures closed sharply lower Monday on
the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting disappointment in the lack
of foreign and domestic demand, analysts said. Grain futures prices
also declined.
   Soybean contracts for September and January delivery traded down
the permitted limit of 30 cents a bushel during the session but
recovered slightly before the close.
   ``A lot of bulls are throwing in the towel, backing away from
the market,'' said Mario Balletto, soybean market analyst in New
York with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   ``There's no buying showing up from users,'' he said. ``That's
still the big lament in the market.''
   Three soybean meal contracts closed down the $10-a-ton limit for
that market. The September contract, which has no limit, closed
down $12.80 at $261 a ton.
   At the close, wheat was 1 cent to 6 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.97 a bushel; corn was 2
cents to 6} cents lower with September at $2.72 a bushel; oats were
3{ cents to 6\ cents lower with September at $2.54 a bushel;
soybeans were 15\ cents to 27{ cents lower with September at $8.20
a bushel.
</TEXT>
