<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     09-19 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Slightly; Gold Prices Continue Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower Monday in slow European
trading, reflecting dealer reluctance to speculate in advance of
meetings by the International Monetary Fund and Group of Seven
finance ministers this week.
   Gold slid lower, persisting in a slide that has pushed prices to
the lowest levels since early last year.
   The dollar's performance might ``be repeated every day this
week,'' one dealer said.
   The IMF and World Bank are to begin a meeting on international
debt in West Berlin on Thursday. In addition, the G-7 finance
ministers are to hold a meeting of their own there on Saturday to
discuss economic policy.
   The G-7 industrialized nations are the United States, West
Germany, Japan, France, Great Britain, Italy and Canada.
   Dealers will watch both meetings for a change in direction for
the dollar.
   The dollar's failure to rally last week after the release of
strong U.S. trade figures has left the market confused, dealers
said. Few want to sell the U.S. currency and few want to buy, they
said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar inched up 0.04 yen to a closing 133.80 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at a higher rate of 133.90 yen.
   In London, the dollar fell slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.6785 to buy one pound, little changed from $1.6758 late
Friday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday
included: 1.8695 West German marks, down from 1.8763; 1.5793 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5835; 6.3520 French francs, down from 6.3795;
2.1100 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1151; 1,393.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,398.50; 1.2194 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2232.
   Gold continued its slide from last week, reaching a morning low
of $405 a troy ounce in Zurich, before hectic buying helped the
metal regain some lost ground.
   Gold finished lower in Zurich, closing at $408.50 compared with
$411.00 late Friday.
   In London, gold fell to $409.30 a troy ounce, compared with late
Friday's $412.00.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.07 to close at $411.40.
   Silver bullion prices fell on the London market where the metal
was trading at $6.28 a troy ounce, compared with $6.40 Friday.
</TEXT>
