<HEAD>Compaq Announces New, Smaller Desktop Computer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Compaq Computer Corp., continuing its market
battle with industry giant IBM, announced Monday a smaller,
full-power desktop computer in its growing line of products.
   The Compaq Deskpro 386-20e offers more standard features than
the company's larger 386-based personal computers in a smaller
package, said Compaq President Rod Canion.
   The unit is being aimed at users of 286-based personal computers
who need a faster, compatible unit. It is also being introduced in
direct competition with International Business Machines Corp.'s
Personal System-2 Model 70-121, which is comparably sized and
priced, Compaq said.
   The Deskpro incorporates Compaq's Flex architecture in a smaller
form, offering compatibility with the industry standard while
running 25 percent faster than the IBM PS-2 Model 70-121, Canion
said.
   The models range in price from $5,199 to $7,999.
   The 386 is short for the 80386, Intel Corp.'s most powerful
microprocessor and the successor to the Intel 80286.
</TEXT>
