<1ST_LINE>u f BC-UnisysMainframes 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Unisys Mainframes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unisys Announces Upgraded Mainframe Computers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to update with delay in 2200-400; picks up
3rd graf, The new ...; INSERTS 1 graf after 6th graf, Unisys said
..., to include use of Hitachi chips.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp., working to retain the loyalty of
its big customers, on Monday announced faster mainframe computers
as well as software that speeds up transactions such as airline
reservations and banking.
   However, Unisys announced a three-month delay in its previously
announced 2200-400 computers, which will be available by March
instead of by the end of 1988.
   The new 2200-600 mainframe computers, which had been delayed two
or three years, are expected to slow or stop the defection of
Unisys customers to other makers of big computers, particularly
International Business Machines Corp., said Jay Stevens, an analyst
for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   The new machines are the successors to the 1100-90 computers of
Sperry Corp., which Burroughs Corp. took over two years ago to form
Unisys.
   The 1100 series is a favorite with banks and airlines, both of
which are heavy users of a style of computing called on-line
transaction processing. Unisys said it could achieve an
industry-best 6,500 transactions per second by closely tying
together four computers, each containing four processors.
   Unisys said the 2200-600 computers complete the renewal of the
1100 line, which it promised at the time of the Burroughs-Sperry
merger.
   The computers use semiconductors and packaging technology from
Hitachi Ltd., but Unisys said it intends eventually to drop its
reliance on the Japanese company.
   Prices range from $2 million for a base model to $29 million for
the model capable of 6,500 transactions per second, Unisys said.
The computers will be available next year between March and June.
   The new software for transaction processing runs on the old as
well as the new machines.
</TEXT>
