<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Interco 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0391</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Interco, 1st Ld-Writethru,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rales Group Assails Interco Resistance, Warns of `Unfortunate
Consequences'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 10th graf with no-comment from Interco spokesman.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investor group trying to acquire Interco Inc.
for $2.6 billion warned the manufacturing company Monday of
``unfortunate consequences'' if it proceeds with an anti-takeover
restructuring that includes asset sales.
   ``You have refused to communicate with us concerning our
interest in acquiring Interco for nearly two months,'' complained
Steven and Mitchell Rales, the brothers who lead the takeover
group, Cardinal Acquisition Corp., in a letter to Interco's board.
The letter was released publicly.
   It was the Rales' response to an Interco filing with the
Securities and Exchange Commission last week in which the St.
Louis-based company disclosed the possibility of a defensive
restructuring to thwart an unsolicited takeover.
   Interco said it had retained a group of unidentified bankers to
explore how to finance the restructuring, which could include the
sale of assets such as the company's Ethan Allen furniture concern.
   Such a move could make Interco, a diversified manufacturer with
products that also include London Fog raincoats and Florsheim
shoes, an unattractive acquisition target to the Rales brothers,
Washington-based investors known for their takeover forays.
   Their letter assailed what they called Interco's ``vague
references to a `recapitalization plan' which to date is only
mythical. Not once have you provided stockholders with any
information concerning timing or value.''
   The letter also reiterated that the Rales group's $70-a-share
offer is good only for the company in its present form.
   ``In order to avoid any unfortunate consequences should you
decide to pursue asset sales, we expect to be consulted well in
advance so that we can evaluate the effect that any such sale would
have on our offer,'' the letter stated. ``In addition, we wish to
participate in any such sale process with a full and fair
opportunity to bid.''
   The group did not elaborate on the meaning of ``unfortunate
consequences,'' but presumably was warning of legal action or a
shareholder proxy fight to block any restructuring that would spoil
its strategy.
   Interco spokesman David Garino said the company had no comment
on the Rales letter.
   The Rales group first moved to acquire Interco in late July, but
the company has repeatedly rejected the overtures. The group owns
about 8.7 percent of Interco's 38.4 million shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
