<FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1714EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CSX Bjt   09-19 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CSX, Bjt,0504</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CSX Restructuring Will Increase Stockholder Return, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. said Monday it would buy back up
to 60 million of its common shares and sell off two natural gas
units in a billion-dollar restructuring that will allow the company
to concentrate on its transportation business.
   CSX said it would begin repurchasing shares this week through a
``Dutch auction,'' in which shareholders are invited to offer their
holdings at a price between $28 and $33 per share. The company will
choose one price and purchase up to 40 million shares offered at or
below that price.
   Depending on market conditions, the remainder of the 60 million
shares would be purchased on the open market or in private
negotiations, officials said.
   At $33 a share, the restructuring would cost CSX a total of
$1.98 billion.
   Investors reacted enthusiastically to the CSX announcement, and
bid the company's stock up $3.75 a share to $30.50 in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading.
   Wall Street analysts said the proposal would benefit CSX
shareholders.
   ``It's extremely positive,'' said transportation analyst Jeff
Medford at Wheat First Securities Inc. in Richmond. Reducing the
number of shares outstanding would make the return for stockholders
substantially higher, Medford said.
   The restructuring indicated CSX management is concerned about
generating revenue for stockholders, a change from its apparent
position in the past several years, Medford said.
   Medford said he believes the true market value of CSX is higher
than its current trading price, but he said the company should have
no problem finding takers for its buy-back offer.
   ``Most institutions have been disappointed with CSX's operating
performance,'' he said.
   CSX stock prices have been lagging at about 25 percent below
their pre-October 1987 price, while the market as a whole is only
about 10 or 11 percent below its pre-crash value, according to
analyst Andrew Geller of Provident National Bank in Philadelphia.
   Medford said the company had the cash available to buy back the
shares without selling assets, but he called the planned sale of
CSX's natural gas transmission and natural gas liquids processing
businesses, Texas Gas Transmission Corp. of Owensboro, Ky. and CSX
NGL Corp. of Houston, a sound business move.
   The restructuring continues CSX's moves over the past year to
reduce costs by making payroll cuts and selling assets, Geller
said. CSX said it will considering selling additional assets such
as its luxury resort properties and will launch ``an aggressive
program designed to significantly reduce operating and overhead
costs.''
   Hays T. Watkins, CSX chairman and chief executive officer, said
the restructuring ``evidences our continued commitment to
increasing stockholder value by concentrating our resources on our
core transportation businesses.''
   Medford attributed the change in direction of CSX's management
to John Snow, president and chief operating officer.
   The Richmond-based CSX is the parent company of CSX
Transportation, CSX Energy, CSX Properties and CSX Technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
