<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     09-19 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0554</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar and Gold Both Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar weakened marginally Monday in scanty
trading, reflecting currency-dealer reluctance to do much business
ahead of some potentially significant meetings and economic reports.
   Gold prices eroded further, persisting in a slide that has
pushed bullion to the lowest levels in about 18 months. Republic
National Bank of New York quoted gold at $409.20 a troy ounce as of
4 p.m. EDT, down $2.55 from Friday.
   Foreign exchange brokers said a spate of possibly market-moving
news expected during the week incited a cautious attitude toward
the dollar.
   Aside from meetings planned by the International Monetary Fund,
World Bank and the finance ministers of leading industrialized
democracies, the United States will report a final revision of
second-quarter economic growth and the August rate of inflation. In
addition, Japan will report a range of economic statistics and
Britain will report its money supply growth figures.
   ``There seems to be a thousand reasons not to trade, and that
seems to be what happened,'' said John Baker, chief dealer at the
New York branch of Bank Julius Baer & Co.
   Some dealers said they were growing pessimistic about the
dollar's ability to strengthen. They said the currency's failure to
appreciate sharply in the aftermath of a large reduction in the
U.S. monthly trade deficit reported last week was viewed as a
reason to start selling dollars.
   In Tokyo, the dollar rose 0.04 yen to 133.80 yen. Later in
London it was quoted at a higher rate of 133.90 yen. But by the
time trading ended in New York the dollar weakened to 133.54 yen,
compared with 134.12 yen level Friday.
   The British pound strengthened slightly against the dollar in
London, to $1.6785 from $1.6758. Later in New York sterling fetched
$1.6787, unchanged from Friday.
   Other late-dollar rates in New York vs. levels late Friday:
1.8677 West German marks, down from 1.8711; 1.5780 Swiss francs,
down from 1.5808; 1.2189 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2232; 6.3495
French francs, down from 6.3630; and 1,391.75 Italian lire, down
from 1,399.00.
   Other late-dollar rates in Europe vs. levels late Friday: 1.8695
marks, down from 1.8763; 1.5793 Swiss francs, down from 1.5835;
6.3520 French francs, down from 6.3795; 2.1100 Dutch guilders, down
from 2.1151; 1,393.50 Italian lire, down from 1,398.50; 1.2194
Canadian dollars, down from 1.2232.
   Gold continued to weaken, reflecting what dealers called
investor disillusionment with the metal's value as a hedge against
inflation.
   ``I think basically we have an exhausted market in which there's
no buying, so any metal that comes into the market isn't finding
receptive buyers,'' said Jeffrey Nichols, head of American Precious
Metals Advisers, a New York-based consulting concern. ``There's
nothing particularly unusual that went on today except for more of
the same pessimism.''
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
fell $2.50 a troy ounce to $409.20. Earlier, gold fell $3.07 in
Hong Kong to $441.40; in Zurich it fell $2.50 to $408.50; and in
London it fell $2.70 to $409.30.
   Silver for current delivery rose 4.4 cents on the New York Comex
to $6.37 a troy ounce. Earlier in London, silver slid 12 cents to
$6.28.
</TEXT>
