<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     09-19 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0817</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Dive On Lack Of Demand</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply Monday on the Chicago Board
of Trade, reflecting disappointment in the lack of foreign and
domestic demand, analysts said. Grain futures prices also declined.
   On other markets, gold and platinum futures retreated while
silver rallied; energy futures rose; livestock and meat were mixed;
and stock-index futures advanced.
   Several soybean contracts traded down the permitted limit of 30
cents a bushel during the session but recovered slightly before the
close. Prices ended at their lowest levels since Aug. 23.
   ``A lot of bulls are throwing in the towel, backing away from
the market,'' said Mario Balletto, soybean market analyst in New
York with Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   ``There's no buying showing up from users,'' he said. ``That's
still the big lament in the market.''
   Mickey Luth, soybean analyst with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
Chicago, termed export sales and shipments ``lousy,'' adding that
the soybean market was beginning to feel pressure from the
advancing harvest.
   More soybeans usually come to market at harvest-time as farmers
and grain handlers clean out their bins to make room for the new
crop.
   Luth said the soybean market's recent pattern of long, slow
rallies followed by sharp breaks was typical of tight-supply years.
The Agriculture Department expects soybean production this year to
be 23 percent below last year's level.
   The market has been trading in a broad range from $8 to $10 a
bushel and is unlikely to go higher barring major problems with the
Brazilian soybean crop, he said.
   Corn and wheat futures followed the soybean market but losses in
wheat were limited by talk of new export business with Morocco and
Algeria, analysts said.
   The USDA confirmed after the close it had accepted bids from
exporters on sales of 100,000 metric tons of subsidized wheat to
Morocco and 50,000 metric tons to Algeria.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 6} cents lower with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.96\ a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 7{
cents lower with September at $2.71\ a bushel; oats were 4 cents to
6{ cents lower with September at $2.52 a bushel; soybeans were 12}
cents to 28{ cents lower with September at $8.21 a bushel.
   Gold futures prices declined for the fourth straight day on New
York's Commodity Exchange and posted new 18-month lows.
   But gold appeared ``oversold'' from a technical standpoint, said
Stephen Platt, an analyst in Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``It looks like you've basically exhausted the downside momentum
for now,'' he said.
   Precious metals futures all opened lower on Monday but drew
support from a late firming of crude oil prices, Platt said. Silver
closed higher, gold finished slightly lower and platinum was down
sharply.
   The platinum market ``seemed like it finally caught up with some
of the weakness in both gold and silver,'' he said.
   Platinum, traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange, settled
$13.10 to $14.90 lower with October at $503 a troy ounce.
   Gold settled $2.70 to $3.10 lower with October at $410.20 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 3.5 cents higher with September at
$6.37 a pound.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, West Texas Intermediate
crude oil settled 7 cents lower to 16 cents higher with October at
$14.73 a barrel; heating oil was .01 cent lower to .12 cent higher
with October at 41.36 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .25
cent lower to .15 cent higher with October at 44.24 cents a gallon.
   Live cattle prices were mostly lower, with October and December
deliveries hardest hit, in response to Friday's monthly USDA
cattle-on-feed report.
   The report showed fewer marketings and fewer cattle placed on
feedlots during August than the futures market had expected. The
numbers suggested supplies of slaughter-ready cattle would remain
plentiful through the end of the year, then tighten a bit early
next year.
   Hog futures also wee mixed, partly in anticipation of the USDA's
quarterly hogs and pigs report, which will be released Sept. 30,
analysts said, while frozen pork bellies declined in a technical
sell-off.
   Live cattle settled .35 cent lower to .10 cent higher with
October at 69 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .55
cent higher with September at 79.85 cents a pound; hogs were .30
cent lower to .27 cent higher with October at 37.67 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .70 cent to 1.20 cents lower with February
at 49.52 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, with the contract for December delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index settling .20 point higher at 271.85 points.
</TEXT>
