<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Ramada-HCC     09-19 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Ramada-HCC,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ramada Directors Reject Takeover Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The directors of Phoenix-based Ramada Inc. have
rejected a $368 million takeover offer by the owners of the Hyatt
hotel chain.
   The 10-member board met for more than four hours on Friday
before announcing the offer by HCC Corp. of Chicago, a Hyatt
affiliate, was ``not in the best interests of Ramada and its
shareholders,'' Ramada spokesman Joe Cole said.
   Jay Pritzker, HCC president, had given Ramada until the close of
business Friday to respond to his corporation's offer of $10 a
share for all stockholders other than HCC.
   The Ramada board based its decision in part on an opinion of
Salomon Brothers Inc., a New York-based financial adviser, that
HCC's proposal was ``grossly inadequate and unfair from a financial
point of view,'' Cole said.
   Ramada operates or franchises the operation of more than 600
hotels under the Ramada and Rodeway chains, runs several casinos
through its Gaming Group and is entering the mid-priced,
family-dining market with Marie Callender's restaurants.
   Ramada stock closed at $10 a share Monday, unchanged from
Friday's price, in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
