<1ST_LINE>r f AM-KDISaleTalks     09-19 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-KDI Sale Talks,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>KDI Management May Buy Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   KDI Corp. said Monday its board was
considering the possible sale of the diversified manufacturer to a
management-led investor group for about $185 million.
   Eugene A. Cafiero, KDI's chairman and chief executive officer,
heads the group that is exploring whether to purchase the
diversified Cincinnati-based manufacturer for $19 a share.
   At the end of August, KDI had 9.7 million shares outstanding,
which at $19 a share would place the purchase offer at almost $185
million.
   KDI stock closed at $17.87{ a share, up 37{ cents, in New York
Stock Exchange composite trading Monday.
   Ariadne Australia Ltd. of Sidney, Australia, owns 49.7 percent
of KDI, enough for a controlling interest in the company. The
Australian business began considering in May whether to sell its
shares, leading Cafiero and his group to express their interest in
a buyout of KDI.
   Cafiero and his group said their willingness to purchase KDI
required execution of definitive agreements no later than Wednesday
morning.
   Cafiero, former chairman and president of Chrysler Corp., became
KDI president in October 1986.
   His success in turning the company around during 1987 was
reflected in its sales, which increased 11 percent from the
previous year to $314.4 million.
   Income for the company, whose products include swimming pools
and chemicals, jumped 189 percent to $18.8 million.
</TEXT>
