<HEAD>Primerica Terminates Agreement to Sell Pennsylvania Life</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Primerica Corp., which plans to merge
with Commercial Credit Group Inc., said Monday that in light of the
proposed combination it was terminating an agreement to sell its
Pennsylvania Life Insurance Co. subsidiary.
   Primerica announced in April it had agreed in principle to sell
Santa Monica, Calif.-based Pennsylvania Life and two affiliates to
American National Insurance Co. of Galveston, Texas, for about $240
million.
   Kenneth M. Koprowski, a Primerica spokesman, said that because
Commercial Credit and Pennsylvania Life are both engaged in
financial services, it made sense to review the decision to sell
the insurance company.
   Last month, Primerica agreed to be acquired by Commercial Credit
in a $1.65 billion, mostly stock deal.
   Primerica is engaged in financial services and specialty
retailing. Its other subsidiaries include the investment firm Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
