<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Halliburton-Gearhart     09-19 0188</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Halliburton-Gearhart,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge's Ruling On Merger Will Come Before Friday, Company Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston judge said she would rule before Friday
on the state attorney general's request for an injunction to keep
Halliburton Co. from acquiring Gearhart Industries, Halliburton
officials announced Monday.
   State District Judge Sharolyn Wood set trial for 10 a.m. EDT
Wednesday, after the case was transferred from Austin to facilitate
the defendants' request for an immediate trial.
   Halliburton officials said they wanted the matter settled before
Friday, when some Gearhart creditors have the right to withdraw
their consent to the merger, which could force the oil well
evaluation and geophysical services company into bankruptcy.
   The state attorney general's office obtained a temporary
restraining order last week, temporarily blocking the acquisition
valued at about $300 million.
   Gearhart officials at the company's Fort Worth headquarters,
speaking at a special meeting of the board of directors, reaffirmed
their belief that the terms of the proposed merger with Halliburton
are in the best interests of the company and its shareholders.
   The Gearhart officials also told board members they were
confident Wood would allow the merger.
</TEXT>
